00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:28.080
The Rosenwald Collection is
an ambitious graphic arts

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:31.580
collection with thematic
concentrations and everything

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:35.240
from the history of science
to the decorative arts.

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:40.210
In many ways, the Rosenwald
Collection and the vision

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:42.290
of the man who created it,

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:45.920
was the inspiration
for this symposium.

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:49.720
Lessing Rosenwald was a
collector that was inspired

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:51.550
by the history of printing.

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:56.490
And how that technology
encouraged historical change.

00:06:56.490 --> 00:07:00.690
He celebrated this interest by
collecting illustrated books

00:07:00.690 --> 00:07:05.590
that documented or sometimes
created shifts in taste

00:07:05.590 --> 00:07:09.350
and intellectual tradition
over the last five centuries.

00:07:09.350 --> 00:07:13.360
Now, as someone with a
purely humanities background,

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:15.860
I found Lessing's
collected books

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:19.350
on science particularly exotic.

00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:25.840
Euclid's Elements of Geometry,
Vesalius' Human Dissections,

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:28.570
[Inaudible] impossibly
complex celestial

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:32.600
and geometric calculators,
Galileo's moon.

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:37.210
I wanted to find a way to
talk about these books,

00:07:37.210 --> 00:07:41.860
about the profound and
excited dialogue that had

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:45.160
such a massive historical
impact.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:48.930
And I eventually
realized that my interest

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:53.770
in these books really were
their images and the ability

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:58.330
of these images to convey
meaning hundreds of years

00:07:58.330 --> 00:08:00.160
after their publication.

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:04.930
And it was this interest
that inspired this symposium.

00:08:04.930 --> 00:08:07.950
So the harbingers
of historic shifts

00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:11.590
and scientific understanding
were often changes in methods

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:16.680
of image production, from wood
to metal, from metal to stone,

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:20.500
from stone to the wide-ranging
methods of photomechanical

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:22.450
and photographic production.

00:08:22.450 --> 00:08:26.200
It was these images, flawed
as they may have been,

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:28.770
that most people
experienced new,

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:33.450
heady and exciting revelations
in mathematics, physics,

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:37.150
biology and the cosmos.

00:08:37.150 --> 00:08:41.670
Now, in 2018, digital tools
are sounding the trumpets

00:08:41.670 --> 00:08:46.050
of a new chapter in the history
of scientific illustration.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:48.850
While Robert Hooke's
engravings brought us dozens

00:08:48.850 --> 00:08:52.550
of miniscule phenomena,
the point of a needle,

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:57.210
a strand of silk, the barbs
of a stinging nettle --

00:08:57.210 --> 00:09:00.610
digital visualization
tools can now envision

00:09:00.610 --> 00:09:03.240
and circulate images
of infinitesimal

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:05.950
yet vast and unique bioscapes.

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:08.240
And visualize structural
variations

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:11.000
within the human genome.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.460
The speakers here today and
tomorrow will discuss this long

00:09:14.460 --> 00:09:17.830
and varied history of
scientific illustration,

00:09:17.830 --> 00:09:23.190
of intellectual dialogue,
of radicalism and orthodoxy,

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:26.600
of artistic and technological
innovation.

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:28.950
But within all of these talks,

00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:32.530
we find gratifyingly
common questions.

00:09:32.530 --> 00:09:36.950
How do we imagine the universe
and our place within it?

00:09:36.950 --> 00:09:40.290
How can we capture the
wonder and the mystery

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:44.220
of the natural world
and the human body?

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:46.050
How do very human choices

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:51.530
in illustration processes
impact public understanding?

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:55.980
I'd like to think that
this symposium is our way

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:58.020
of celebrating this
complicated history

00:09:58.020 --> 00:10:00.190
and these complicated questions.

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:04.170
Over the next two days, you
will hear historians talking

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:07.220
about finding our
place in the universe.

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:10.240
Artists will address
scientific convention.

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:12.900
Biologists will talk
about breakthroughs

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:14.240
in historic illustration

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:19.570
and technologists will face the
frontiers of cultural heritage,

00:10:19.570 --> 00:10:22.570
storytelling and access.

00:10:22.570 --> 00:10:25.750
It's in this spirit of
dialogue and discovery

00:10:25.750 --> 00:10:29.220
that we warmly welcome you to
Imagining the Extraordinary.

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:31.020
Thank you.

