00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:25.190
The night sky has always
been a source of wonder,

00:13:25.190 --> 00:13:27.420
of mystery and of utility.

00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:30.980
In the ancient world, it was
important to map the heavens

00:13:30.980 --> 00:13:33.680
and learn the movements of
the wandering stars, the sun

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:37.960
and moon, and Mercury, Venus,
Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn.

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:41.300
Timekeeping, planning the
farming year, the calendar

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:43.660
of religious festivals,
navigation

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:47.030
and astrological divination
were motivations enough

00:13:47.030 --> 00:13:50.490
for serious scientific
study of the heavens.

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:55.160
But science has always also
been motivated by curiosity,

00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:58.560
by wonder, by the beauty
of the natural world.

00:13:58.560 --> 00:14:01.950
As Nicolaus Copernicus puts
it in the first sentence

00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:06.380
of <i>De revolutionibus </i>, "Among
the many various literary

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:10.620
and artistic pursuits which
invigorate men's minds,

00:14:10.620 --> 00:14:14.760
the strongest affection and
utmost zeal should, I think,

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:18.120
promote the studies concerned
with the most beautiful objects,

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:20.560
most deserving to be known.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:24.040
What indeed is more beautiful
than heaven, which of course,

00:14:24.040 --> 00:14:26.990
contains all things of beauty?"

00:14:26.990 --> 00:14:30.880
I want to stress this aspect of
scientific discovery, curiosity,

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:33.190
wonder, the aesthetics.

00:14:33.190 --> 00:14:35.020
Because as well as
being a driving force

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:38.390
to scientific inquiry, it
is also to a greater extent

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:41.410
than is sometimes
appreciated, a driving force

00:14:41.410 --> 00:14:44.610
in the making of
scientific books.

00:14:44.610 --> 00:14:48.260
A young person visiting a
literary home cast his eyes

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:50.430
over the thousands of
books lining the walls

00:14:50.430 --> 00:14:51.730
and on the tables.

00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:56.870
He asked nervously, "Have
you read all these books?"

00:14:56.870 --> 00:15:01.660
His host's reply, "I have never
bought a book I did not intend

00:15:01.660 --> 00:15:04.190
to read."

00:15:04.190 --> 00:15:06.220
[Laughter] This is the
secret of publishing.

00:15:06.220 --> 00:15:11.200
You have to sell more books than
are actually going to be read.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:15.850
In this, pictures
play a major role.

00:15:15.850 --> 00:15:17.520
Pictures sell books.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:20.280
Historians of science
sometimes forget this.

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:23.730
And this is one of the reasons
that images can get overlooked.

00:15:23.730 --> 00:15:29.910
I'm going to look at three kinds
of astronomical images which are

00:15:29.910 --> 00:15:32.920
of some importance to the
development of astronomy,

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:35.810
to our understanding of
our place in the universe,

00:15:35.810 --> 00:15:39.320
and to our appreciation
of its beauty.

00:15:39.320 --> 00:15:42.570
The images are mostly well-known
but by looking at them

00:15:42.570 --> 00:15:45.300
from the point of view of
their origins, the technology

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:47.590
of their production
and their impact

00:15:47.590 --> 00:15:51.110
on the nonprofessional readers,
I hope to give you some hints

00:15:51.110 --> 00:15:53.330
about their place
in cultural history,

00:15:53.330 --> 00:15:55.910
not just the grand
narrative of the development

00:15:55.910 --> 00:15:59.810
of astronomy told by
intellectual historians.

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:05.410
Three things are essential
to understanding the heavens

00:16:05.410 --> 00:16:08.520
and they will require
the use of images.

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:12.300
First, we need a map
of the fixed stars.

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:15.580
Only once their positions are
known can we track the movements

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:18.830
of the wandering stars, the
strange dance of the planets

00:16:18.830 --> 00:16:22.880
as they advance in one
direction and then loop back.

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:25.620
So that's my first topic.

00:16:25.620 --> 00:16:29.080
My second topic is a geometrical
model of these movements,

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:31.930
the heliocentric
system of Copernicus.

00:16:31.930 --> 00:16:35.100
And finally, I want to look
at the first investigations

00:16:35.100 --> 00:16:38.870
of the heavens not with geometry
but by direct observation

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:44.140
with the telescope, Galileo's
<i>Siderius Nuncius </i>of 1610.

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:48.490
So let's start with star maps.

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:52.350
The night sky is
a confusing sight.

00:16:52.350 --> 00:16:54.120
In order to make
some sense of it,

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:57.260
it became traditional
probably in prehistoric times

00:16:57.260 --> 00:17:01.450
to group together stars that
suggested the shapes of animals,

00:17:01.450 --> 00:17:03.550
gods or mythological figures.

00:17:03.550 --> 00:17:05.970
And these are the
constellations.

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:08.230
They are arbitrary
groups of stars

00:17:08.230 --> 00:17:12.080
but they provide a framework
defining star positions verbally

00:17:12.080 --> 00:17:14.700
with descriptions such
as the Bright Star

00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:18.000
in the right shoulder of Orion.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.300
More accurate positions would
be provided by coordinates

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:24.210
but the verbal descriptions
as well as the names

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:27.270
for specific stars
continue to be used

00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:28.970
and constellation
figures continue

00:17:28.970 --> 00:17:31.190
to be prominent features
on star maps,

00:17:31.190 --> 00:17:33.070
even for professional
astronomers

00:17:33.070 --> 00:17:34.800
into the 19th century.

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:37.890
And they're still important
for amateur astronomers.

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:46.290
Constellation figures with star
positions were first printed

00:17:46.290 --> 00:17:50.620
in Venice in 1482 in
the mythological poem,

00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:53.030
"Poeticon Astronomicon"
attributed

00:17:53.030 --> 00:17:56.580
to the Roman historian
Gaius Julius Hyginus.

00:17:56.580 --> 00:18:01.040
But the stars dotted about
the constellation figures have

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:05.710
little to do with their
real positions in the sky.

00:18:05.710 --> 00:18:09.280
Albrecht Durer's famous woodcut
celestial maps of the northern

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:10.580
and southern hemispheres --

00:18:10.580 --> 00:18:13.550
we're just looking at
the northern one here --

00:18:13.550 --> 00:18:19.200
are the first printed maps
with accurate star positions.

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:23.300
The lettering on
the map credits --

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:25.680
well, actually, it's not
on the map but anyway.

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:27.730
I think it may be
on the other map.

00:18:27.730 --> 00:18:31.920
But well, the contributors
to the map are credited

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:34.410
as Johannes Stabius,
who is astronomer

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:39.080
to Maximillian the First,
who drew the coordinate grid,

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:42.410
the Nuremberg astronomer
Conrad Heinfogel,

00:18:42.410 --> 00:18:47.390
who positioned the stars on
the grid, and finally, Durer,

00:18:47.390 --> 00:18:50.380
who drew the constellation
figures around the stars.

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:53.600
The image is printed from a
large, a very large woodblock.

00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:55.780
It's about 17 inches wide.

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:57.080
And it would have been executed

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:00.850
by a professional block
cutter, not by Durer himself.

00:19:00.850 --> 00:19:04.340
So the print is a collaboration
between at least four people.

00:19:04.340 --> 00:19:07.400
And we should bear this in
mind when loosely referring it

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:11.950
to as -- referring to it
as Durer's planisphere.

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:17.860
The sun, moon and planets move
within a band of sky known

00:19:17.860 --> 00:19:21.930
as the zodiac which is tilted at
an angle to the Earth's equator.

00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:23.990
Here, you can see the
familiar constellations

00:19:23.990 --> 00:19:26.630
of the zodiac arranged
anti-clockwise

00:19:26.630 --> 00:19:29.220
around the graduated circle.

00:19:29.220 --> 00:19:32.320
Durer's constellation figures
are shown from the back

00:19:32.320 --> 00:19:35.030
as if we were looking
at the celestial sphere

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:38.610
from the outside as if
looking at a celestial globe.

00:19:38.610 --> 00:19:42.150
These designs for the
constellation figures were

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:46.830
important models for
later celestial mapmakers.

00:19:46.830 --> 00:19:54.690
In the corners of the print,
you can see the four depictions

00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:57.270
of ancient authorities
on the sky.

00:19:57.270 --> 00:20:03.860
So we have the Greek poet
Aratus, the Roman poet Manilius,

00:20:03.860 --> 00:20:07.380
Al-Sufi, who is an
astronomer working

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:09.410
in Baghdad in the 10th century.

00:20:09.410 --> 00:20:12.430
And finally, looking
suspiciously

00:20:12.430 --> 00:20:16.720
like the Mad Hatter
is Claudius Ptolemy.

00:20:17.990 --> 00:20:21.550
Ptolemy was of Greek
origin and he wrote in Greek

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:24.180
but because he -- but he
became a Roman citizen

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:25.480
and lived in Alexandria.

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:29.970
So this is why he's referred to
on the map as Ptolemy of Egypt.

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:36.560
Ptolemy's textbook,
the <i>Almagest </i>,

00:20:36.560 --> 00:20:39.580
written in the 2nd
century CE is one

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:42.420
of the most influential
scientific treatises

00:20:42.420 --> 00:20:44.270
of all time.

00:20:44.270 --> 00:20:47.820
Although an epitome
was published in 1496,

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:51.890
the full text was not in print
until 1515, the same year

00:20:51.890 --> 00:20:54.310
as the woodcut planisphere.

00:20:54.310 --> 00:20:58.760
The <i>Almagest </i>contains a
catalogue of fixed stars

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:01.060
and a geometrical
model of the universe

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:03.540
with the stationary
Earth at the center.

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:07.650
This model is known as
the Ptolemaic system.

00:21:07.650 --> 00:21:09.620
Ptolemy arranged his catalogue

00:21:09.620 --> 00:21:14.230
of 1022 stars in
48 constellations.

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:17.170
Star locations within the
constellations are given

00:21:17.170 --> 00:21:21.530
verbally on the left and
by coding it for longitude

00:21:21.530 --> 00:21:26.160
and latitude in degrees with a
scale of brightness or magnitude

00:21:26.160 --> 00:21:29.590
from one, the brightest
to six, the faintest.

00:21:29.590 --> 00:21:32.690
These are in the
table on the right.

00:21:32.690 --> 00:21:34.600
Ptolemy's constellations

00:21:34.600 --> 00:21:36.950
and star catalogue
actually lasted longer

00:21:36.950 --> 00:21:38.410
than his planetary system

00:21:38.410 --> 00:21:41.610
for while the geocentric model
was replaced, although not

00:21:41.610 --> 00:21:42.960
without a struggle

00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:47.230
by the heliocentric sun-centered
model put forward by Copernicus

00:21:47.230 --> 00:21:49.040
in the 16th century, most

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:52.970
of Ptolemy's constellations
are still in use today.

00:21:56.460 --> 00:22:00.480
Although Durer's planispheres
are the first printed star maps,

00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:04.190
the first set of charts in
book form to show the positions

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:05.490
of the stars relative

00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:09.340
to one another accurately is
Piccolomini's De le stelle

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:13.040
fisse, printed at
Venice in 1540.

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:18.250
The magnitude of each star is
indicated by the use of symbols.

00:22:18.250 --> 00:22:21.360
So these maps are a
graphic representation

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:25.470
of Ptolemy's catalogue, the
numerical coordinates translated

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:29.590
into positions and the
magnitudes into symbols.

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:34.740
It was another 50 years
before Giovanni Paolo Gallucci

00:22:34.740 --> 00:22:38.380
published the first star atlas
to combine constellation figures

00:22:38.380 --> 00:22:41.120
with accurate star positions.

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:44.610
So now, we have all the elements
of the typical star atlas.

00:22:44.610 --> 00:22:47.590
A series of maps with
constellation figures,

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:52.460
accurate star positions,
and a system of coordinates.

00:22:52.460 --> 00:22:55.760
Gallucci took his star positions
from the catalogue printed

00:22:55.760 --> 00:23:00.500
at the end of Copernicus'
<i>De revolutionibus </i>of 1543.

00:23:00.500 --> 00:23:03.900
Copernicus made a few
corrections to Ptolemy based

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:07.530
on fresh observations and he
changed the coordinate system.

00:23:07.530 --> 00:23:10.970
But his catalogue is
essentially Ptolemy's catalogue.

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:20.550
The images on these two small
Venetian atlases, Piccolomini

00:23:20.550 --> 00:23:22.740
and Gallucci, are
like the planisphere

00:23:22.740 --> 00:23:24.320
with constellation
figures designed

00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:27.470
by Durer printed
from woodblocks.

00:23:27.470 --> 00:23:34.030
Very different in appearance is
<i>Uranometria </i>of Johann Bayer

00:23:34.030 --> 00:23:37.340
printed at Augsburg in 1603.

00:23:37.340 --> 00:23:41.960
Here you see the elaborate
engraved title page

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:45.260
and here is one of the maps.

00:23:45.260 --> 00:23:47.720
This is one of the most
beautiful star atlases

00:23:47.720 --> 00:23:49.550
and the first to
have charts printed

00:23:49.550 --> 00:23:52.050
from copper plate engraving.

00:23:52.050 --> 00:23:55.140
It was also the most
accurate to date being based

00:23:55.140 --> 00:23:56.870
on the star positions calculated

00:23:56.870 --> 00:23:59.840
by the Danish astronomer
Tycho Brahe from new

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:02.850
and highly accurate
observations.

00:24:02.850 --> 00:24:07.990
As well as using these more
accurate positions established

00:24:07.990 --> 00:24:09.550
by the Danish astronomer,

00:24:09.550 --> 00:24:13.070
Bayer also introduced a
new system of nomenclature.

00:24:13.070 --> 00:24:17.170
In each constellation, he gave
the principal stars the letters

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:20.550
of the Greek alphabet in
descending order of magnitude.

00:24:20.550 --> 00:24:25.890
Thus the star in Orion's left
shoulder is Alpha Orionis.

00:24:25.890 --> 00:24:27.820
Being one of the
brightest stars in the sky,

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:30.680
it also has its own
name, Betelgeuse.

00:24:30.680 --> 00:24:33.110
But most stars do not
have individual names

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:35.160
and Bayer's nomenclature
is important

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:36.930
and still in use today.

00:24:36.930 --> 00:24:40.590
But above all, Bayer
provided the first really

00:24:40.590 --> 00:24:42.260
accurate plates.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:45.660
Gallucci had shown the way by
providing scales and gridlines

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:47.980
but his small page
size and the costliness

00:24:47.980 --> 00:24:49.970
of the woodcut illustrations
meant

00:24:49.970 --> 00:24:52.610
that his star positions could
not be read off the plate

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:54.330
with any accuracy.

00:24:54.330 --> 00:24:56.720
Bayer's much larger
plates and the finer lines

00:24:56.720 --> 00:24:58.260
of engraving allowed him

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:01.550
to achieve a quite new
level of precision.

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:05.760
The plates are about
18 inches wide.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:09.020
So if you compare these with
Gallucci's page which is

00:25:09.020 --> 00:25:10.960
about seven inches wide,

00:25:10.960 --> 00:25:16.230
but Bayer's atlas is still
small compared to later atlases.

00:25:16.230 --> 00:25:20.070
John Flamsteed's atlas of
1729 is almost twice as wide

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:24.330
as Bayer's at 32 inches and
some atlases were even bigger.

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:27.230
The plates are generally
attributed

00:25:27.230 --> 00:25:31.470
to the German engraver
Alexander Mayer around early use

00:25:31.470 --> 00:25:36.370
of stipple engraving where the
image is made up of small dots.

00:25:36.370 --> 00:25:37.940
This is the perfect technique

00:25:37.940 --> 00:25:41.770
for rendering the constellation
figures so that they are easy

00:25:41.770 --> 00:25:43.860
to read without interfering

00:25:43.860 --> 00:25:47.540
with the star symbols
and their lettering.

00:25:49.080 --> 00:25:52.690
Bayer's atlas was important
for practicing astronomers.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:54.070
We know that when Flamsteed

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:56.350
of the Royal Greenwich
Observatory made his great

00:25:56.350 --> 00:26:00.940
3000-star catalogue, beginning
his observations in the 1670s,

00:26:00.940 --> 00:26:04.140
he used Bayer's charts to
locate the naked eye stars,

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:08.320
filling in the new
telescopic stars between them.

00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:11.510
But as with most books,
professional users make

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:13.930
up only part of the market.

00:26:13.930 --> 00:26:17.160
These well-drawn and finely
engraved mythological figures

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:18.540
would have appealed to buyers

00:26:18.540 --> 00:26:21.300
of other high-end
illustrated books.

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:22.870
Important for the publisher

00:26:22.870 --> 00:26:25.500
of what must have been a very
expensive book to produce.

00:26:25.500 --> 00:26:30.970
So I'll the evolution of
star atlases with here

00:26:30.970 --> 00:26:32.350
with Bayer's atlas published

00:26:32.350 --> 00:26:36.830
in 1603 representing the
situation just a few years

00:26:36.830 --> 00:26:39.310
before Galileo started
looking at the heavens

00:26:39.310 --> 00:26:40.610
through his telescope.

00:26:40.610 --> 00:26:42.940
But before we get to Galileo,

00:26:42.940 --> 00:26:46.250
what about the wandering stars
whose movements are defined

00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:48.970
with reference to
the fixed stars?

00:26:58.040 --> 00:27:00.480
This diagram is one
of the most famous

00:27:00.480 --> 00:27:01.820
in the history of science.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:04.330
It is, of course,
the heliocentric.

00:27:04.330 --> 00:27:06.280
It is, of course, the
heliocentric model

00:27:06.280 --> 00:27:10.310
of the universe in Nicolaus
Copernicus <i>De revolutionibus</i>

00:27:10.310 --> 00:27:12.980
<i>orbium coelestium</i>
or <i>The Revolutions</i>

00:27:12.980 --> 00:27:18.180
<i>of the Heavenly Spheres</i>
published at Nuremberg in 1543.

00:27:18.180 --> 00:27:22.670
This is the diagram that
shows that our world is not

00:27:22.670 --> 00:27:24.220
at the center of the universe

00:27:24.220 --> 00:27:28.530
but just one among the other
five known planets circling

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:30.100
the sun.

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:32.670
One of the advantages
of the new system was

00:27:32.670 --> 00:27:35.730
that it made it possible to
compute periods and distances

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:38.510
of the planets from the sun.

00:27:38.510 --> 00:27:41.970
The diagram shows how
elegantly this works.

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:44.490
With the planets ordered
by the time each takes

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:50.020
to orbit the sun related to its
relative distance from the sun.

00:27:50.020 --> 00:27:52.020
The period of each
planet is given

00:27:52.020 --> 00:27:54.830
in the legend on each circle.

00:27:54.830 --> 00:27:57.400
The outermost planet,
Saturn, has a period

00:27:57.400 --> 00:28:01.270
of 30 years then comes Jupiter
at 12 years, Mars at two years,

00:28:01.270 --> 00:28:04.310
Earth, one year, of course
and the inner planets,

00:28:04.310 --> 00:28:08.750
Venus and Mercury with periods
of nine months and 80 days.

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:13.690
The outermost sphere is labeled
Stellarum Fixarum sphaera

00:28:13.690 --> 00:28:18.080
immobilis, the immovable
sphere of the fixed stars.

00:28:18.080 --> 00:28:19.630
I want you to remember
this phrase,

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:25.240
the immovable sphere
of the fixed stars.

00:28:25.240 --> 00:28:28.200
Copernicus had been working
on his treatise for many years

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:31.870
when the young Joachim Rheticus
arrived at the monastery

00:28:31.870 --> 00:28:35.880
in Frombork in Poland where
Copernicus was a priest.

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:38.090
This was in 1539.

00:28:38.090 --> 00:28:43.230
This neatly written manuscript
was completed two years later

00:28:43.230 --> 00:28:45.480
in 1541.

00:28:45.480 --> 00:28:49.430
It seems to be a presentation
manuscript, not printer's copy.

00:28:49.430 --> 00:28:51.240
And it certainly was
not the manuscript

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:52.870
that went to the printer.

00:28:52.870 --> 00:28:56.710
A copy was made after
Rheticus had left Frombork

00:28:56.710 --> 00:28:59.390
and sent to him in Nuremberg.

00:28:59.390 --> 00:29:02.320
At some point, some very
interesting changes were made

00:29:02.320 --> 00:29:04.000
to this famous diagram.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:08.280
What we are familiar with in
the printed book is not what is

00:29:08.280 --> 00:29:10.800
in Copernicus' own manuscript.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:14.980
In the manuscript,
there are eight circles.

00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:19.420
But in the woodcut,
there are nine circles.

00:29:19.420 --> 00:29:24.040
An extra circle has been
introduced within the sphere

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:28.590
of the Earth with a sphere
for the moon around it.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:31.190
I'm sure you can -- so sorry.

00:29:38.210 --> 00:29:43.840
So there is the Earth,
Telluris com Luna but here,

00:29:43.840 --> 00:29:48.970
it's now got its own circle and
an extra circle for the moon.

00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:55.250
Copernicus believed that
the planets were carried

00:29:55.250 --> 00:29:56.990
around in solid orbs.

00:29:56.990 --> 00:29:58.600
The introduction of a circle

00:29:58.600 --> 00:30:01.040
in the Earth's sphere implies
something quite different.

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:04.010
Not a solid sphere in rotation

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:06.550
but the Earth moving
freely through space.

00:30:06.550 --> 00:30:11.280
The line in the diagram
indicating an orbital path.

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:12.990
Since Rheticus oversaw
the printing

00:30:12.990 --> 00:30:15.580
of <i>De revolutionibus </i>in
Nuremberg or at any rate,

00:30:15.580 --> 00:30:17.060
in the early stages,

00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:19.180
he presumably supplied
the block cutter

00:30:19.180 --> 00:30:21.020
with a sketch to work from.

00:30:21.020 --> 00:30:23.350
In this case, he would
have been responsible

00:30:23.350 --> 00:30:25.460
for introducing the
circle for the Earth

00:30:25.460 --> 00:30:28.610
and the subsidiary
circle for the moon.

00:30:28.610 --> 00:30:33.270
Innumerable textbook diagrams
supposedly illustrating the

00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:35.660
Copernican system followed this

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:37.080
and showed the planets
positioned

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:40.750
on the circles rather
than between them.

00:30:40.750 --> 00:30:43.170
Copernicus actually
thought that the planets --

00:30:43.170 --> 00:30:46.070
of the planets being carried
around in solid spheres

00:30:46.070 --> 00:30:50.030
within which they had
further complex movements.

00:30:50.030 --> 00:30:53.590
Just as in the Ptolemaic
system, in the Copernican model,

00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:57.040
the planets moved in small
circle called "epicycles"

00:30:57.040 --> 00:31:01.280
at the same time as being
carried around in their spheres.

00:31:01.280 --> 00:31:06.210
This was necessary to account
for their looping dance.

00:31:06.210 --> 00:31:10.430
The ambiguous woodcut in <i>De
revolutionibus </i>is responsible

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:13.920
for the misconception that the
Copernican system involved the

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:16.500
planets moving through
space along circular paths

00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:19.240
without epicycles and
therefore more elegant

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:24.290
than Ptolemy's system which
also required epicycles.

00:31:24.290 --> 00:31:28.080
In fact, orbital paths without
epicycles were not introduced

00:31:28.080 --> 00:31:31.000
until later in the
century by Johannes Kepler.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:37.590
Then something curious happens
outside the sphere of the Earth.

00:31:37.590 --> 00:31:44.240
The next ring is empty
so this ring is empty.

00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:47.410
And all the lettering has now
been shifted to the outside

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:51.970
of the lines compared to how
it was in the manuscript.

00:31:56.400 --> 00:31:58.230
So the lettering
from Mars, Jupiter,

00:31:58.230 --> 00:32:00.200
Saturn are now sitting
on the lines.

00:32:00.200 --> 00:32:03.490
And so by analogy with the
Earth's path, they seem also

00:32:03.490 --> 00:32:07.690
to indicate not solid
spheres but orbital paths.

00:32:07.690 --> 00:32:09.200
But shifting the
lettering to the outside

00:32:09.200 --> 00:32:12.430
of the circle has another
highly significant effect.

00:32:12.430 --> 00:32:17.890
The sphere of the fixed stars
no longer has any boundary.

00:32:17.890 --> 00:32:19.890
This, I think, gave a hint

00:32:19.890 --> 00:32:23.620
for another significant
reinterpretation of Copernicus.

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:28.880
In 1576, a startlingly
new picture

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:30.810
of the universe was printed.

00:32:30.810 --> 00:32:33.500
Both in this diagram
and in his text,

00:32:33.500 --> 00:32:35.210
Thomas Digges states
emphatically

00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:38.360
that the universe is infinite.

00:32:38.360 --> 00:32:42.390
He also shows the
planets confined --

00:32:42.390 --> 00:32:45.750
he also shows the planets
confined in their spheres

00:32:45.750 --> 00:32:47.990
as Copernicus had intended.

00:32:47.990 --> 00:32:50.760
So he's correcting the
Copernican diagram.

00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:53.450
He's correcting the <i>De
revolutionibus </i>by carefully

00:32:53.450 --> 00:32:55.170
reading the text.

00:32:55.170 --> 00:32:58.660
So in fact, this is the
first really accurate diagram

00:32:58.660 --> 00:33:05.500
of what Copernicus was getting
at, apart from the fixed stars.

00:33:05.500 --> 00:33:08.610
Digges' major intervention
concerns his interpretation

00:33:08.610 --> 00:33:11.310
of what Copernicus says about
the size of the universe

00:33:11.310 --> 00:33:15.140
and the possibility of
an infinite universe.

00:33:15.140 --> 00:33:18.300
This woodcut appears in an
appendix to a new addition

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:21.140
of the popular almanac
by Thomas Digges' father,

00:33:21.140 --> 00:33:25.080
Leonard called "A
Prognostication Everlasting"

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:26.380
which was based

00:33:26.380 --> 00:33:30.310
on the traditional Ptolemaic
Earth-centered universe.

00:33:30.310 --> 00:33:33.870
Thomas reprints his father's
work with a few corrections

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:38.520
and adds a perfect description
of the celestial orbs according

00:33:38.520 --> 00:33:42.330
to the most ancient
doctrine of the Pythagoreans.

00:33:42.330 --> 00:33:44.360
Lately revived by Copernicus

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:47.990
and by geometrical
demonstrations are proved.

00:33:47.990 --> 00:33:52.520
And the free translation
with some additions of parts

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:55.040
of the first book of
<i>De revolutionibus </i>,

00:33:55.040 --> 00:33:59.110
it's the first English account
of the Copernican system

00:33:59.110 --> 00:34:03.430
and the first publication of the
heliocentric diagram in Britain.

00:34:03.430 --> 00:34:07.020
But with a hugely significant
addition of an infinity

00:34:07.020 --> 00:34:10.340
of stars beyond the
solar system.

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:14.640
This was before Giordano Bruno's
more metaphysical speculations

00:34:14.640 --> 00:34:17.510
on the infinite universe
which was possibly influenced

00:34:17.510 --> 00:34:19.870
by Digges and was
published eight years later,

00:34:19.870 --> 00:34:23.180
also in London in 1584.

00:34:24.460 --> 00:34:27.620
Digges' work has recently been
discussed by David Wootton

00:34:27.620 --> 00:34:31.230
in his well-received <i>History
of the Scientific Revolution,</i>

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:33.250
<i>the Invention of Science </i>.

00:34:33.250 --> 00:34:39.360
According to Wootton, and I
quote, "The illustration spreads

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:42.500
over two pages and it
appears to have been added

00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:46.060
as an afterthought as the
book went through the press.

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:49.170
Binders were never quite
sure what to do with it

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:54.220
to incorporate it as a foldout
page or as a two-page spread.

00:34:54.220 --> 00:34:59.940
As you can see, the text of
the first part ends finis

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:03.970
so this is the end of Leonard
Digges' part of the book.

00:35:09.540 --> 00:35:13.550
But the image has
[inaudible] or 43 printed

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:16.750
in the upper right corner of
the sheet in the last page

00:35:16.750 --> 00:35:21.040
of the first part of the text
is obviously [inaudible] or 42.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:23.460
So it's clearly intended
to be bound here

00:35:23.460 --> 00:35:24.760
as an upright foldout.

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:27.840
As a frontispiece and
the kind of title page

00:35:27.840 --> 00:35:29.860
to Thomas Digges'
Perfect Description

00:35:29.860 --> 00:35:32.650
of the Celestial Orbs since
there's no other title page

00:35:32.650 --> 00:35:34.700
to this part of the book.

00:35:34.700 --> 00:35:37.300
Third, the bibliographical
analysis shows

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:39.550
that it cannot possibly
be an afterthought.

00:35:39.550 --> 00:35:41.850
It is an integral part

00:35:41.850 --> 00:35:45.160
of the book printed
along with the text.

00:35:45.160 --> 00:35:47.970
I mention this as
a cautionary note.

00:35:47.970 --> 00:35:49.270
Paying a little attention

00:35:49.270 --> 00:35:51.900
to the physical object
might have saved Wootton

00:35:51.900 --> 00:35:53.630
from his condescending
suggestion

00:35:53.630 --> 00:35:56.370
that the illustration
was an afterthought.

00:35:56.370 --> 00:36:00.290
And by implication, of less
importance than the text.

00:36:00.290 --> 00:36:01.590
On the contrary,

00:36:01.590 --> 00:36:03.400
it was carefully planned
from the beginning.

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:05.310
The woodcut would have
been an expense --

00:36:05.310 --> 00:36:07.010
would have been expensive
to make

00:36:07.010 --> 00:36:11.610
and printing it complicated
the production process.

00:36:11.610 --> 00:36:16.030
So let's look at
it more closely.

00:36:16.030 --> 00:36:21.990
The lettering within the outer
ring states that this orb

00:36:21.990 --> 00:36:25.940
of stars fixed indefinitely
out extended itself

00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:30.330
in altitudes spherically
and therefore immovable.

00:36:30.330 --> 00:36:34.720
It is garnished with perpetual
shining glorious lights

00:36:34.720 --> 00:36:38.360
innumerable far excelling
the sun both

00:36:38.360 --> 00:36:41.070
in quantity and quality.

00:36:41.070 --> 00:36:45.370
The striking thing about this
diagram and the reason it is

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:48.970
so often reproduced is that
the fixed stars are not

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:52.300
in the outer sphere
which only has text in it

00:36:52.300 --> 00:36:56.860
but are outside it and at
variable distances from the sun.

00:36:56.860 --> 00:37:01.050
In the text, Digges explains
that the stars are fainter,

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:02.720
the farther out they are,

00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:06.120
until our sight is no longer
sharp enough to distinguish them

00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:09.230
and the greatest
number are, as he says,

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:13.390
by reason of their wonderful
distance, invisible unto us.

00:37:13.390 --> 00:37:18.270
I asked you to remember the
label on the outermost sphere

00:37:18.270 --> 00:37:19.920
in the Copernican diagram,

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:24.050
the immovable sphere
of the fixed stars.

00:37:24.050 --> 00:37:26.580
A central tenet of the
Copernican system is

00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:28.920
that the Earth is not
stationary but spins

00:37:28.920 --> 00:37:31.640
on its axis every 24 hours.

00:37:31.640 --> 00:37:34.250
So when we see the heavens
wheeling over our heads,

00:37:34.250 --> 00:37:35.780
they are not really moving.

00:37:35.780 --> 00:37:40.270
We are. Copernicus could
not detect any paradox

00:37:40.270 --> 00:37:41.570
in the fixed stars.

00:37:41.570 --> 00:37:43.270
No measurable difference
in the angles

00:37:43.270 --> 00:37:45.290
between the stars
wherever we are

00:37:45.290 --> 00:37:47.720
on our annual journey
around the sun.

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:52.030
So the sphere of the fixed stars
must be at an immense distance

00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:54.280
from the planetary spheres.

00:37:54.280 --> 00:37:58.310
Copernicus only says that this
distance appears to be infinite,

00:37:58.310 --> 00:38:02.780
appears to be infinite compared
with the tiny dot of the Earth.

00:38:02.780 --> 00:38:06.460
Whether the universe outside
the fixed stars is infinite is

00:38:06.460 --> 00:38:09.210
something that he,
Copernicus, said should be left

00:38:09.210 --> 00:38:10.990
to the natural philosophers.

00:38:10.990 --> 00:38:13.770
And historians have debated
whether Copernicus really

00:38:13.770 --> 00:38:16.100
believed in an infinite
universe.

00:38:16.100 --> 00:38:19.580
But the crucial thing is that
even if he did, he still meant

00:38:19.580 --> 00:38:23.690
that the fixed stars are
contained in a spherical shell.

00:38:23.690 --> 00:38:28.010
The astonishing new idea put
forward by Digges in his text

00:38:28.010 --> 00:38:30.810
and in the image is that
there is no boundary

00:38:30.810 --> 00:38:32.190
to the fixed stars.

00:38:32.190 --> 00:38:34.500
They extend out to infinity.

00:38:34.500 --> 00:38:37.970
The majority so far off that
they are invisible to us.

00:38:41.640 --> 00:38:45.170
Another early English
Copernican, William Gilbert,

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:48.870
well-known for his pioneering
work on magnetism, wrote a work

00:38:48.870 --> 00:38:53.860
on cosmology sometime in the
1580s but it was not published

00:38:53.860 --> 00:38:55.560
until after his death.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:58.140
This is "De mundo
nostro sublunari"

00:38:58.140 --> 00:39:00.200
in which Gilbert made
clear that he believes

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:02.960
that the universe is
infinite and that the stars

00:39:02.960 --> 00:39:07.210
and planets move
through a vacuum.

00:39:07.210 --> 00:39:09.500
Gilbert distinguished
between light-giving stars

00:39:09.500 --> 00:39:11.170
and reflecting bodies.

00:39:11.170 --> 00:39:12.470
And it has been suggested

00:39:12.470 --> 00:39:14.940
that this image demonstrates
Gilbert's belief

00:39:14.940 --> 00:39:17.170
in multiple solar systems.

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:19.700
The largest stars
might indicate suns

00:39:19.700 --> 00:39:23.530
and the smaller stars, planets.

00:39:23.530 --> 00:39:26.750
But we have here to
be even more careful

00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:29.840
about taking the
illustration to be an expression

00:39:29.840 --> 00:39:31.960
of the author's ideas.

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:36.380
The woodcut is an accurate
representation of the diagram

00:39:36.380 --> 00:39:39.400
in the manuscript which
survives in the British Library.

00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:43.010
But it was compiled from
Gilbert's papers sometime

00:39:43.010 --> 00:39:46.080
after his death in 1603.

00:39:46.080 --> 00:39:48.750
We don't know if the diagram
is derived from something

00:39:48.750 --> 00:39:51.750
that Gilbert drew or
if it was introduced

00:39:51.750 --> 00:39:56.990
by his younger half-brother
when he assembled the text.

00:39:56.990 --> 00:39:58.940
Whatever the source
of the diagram,

00:39:58.940 --> 00:40:00.240
it is clearly influenced
by Digges.

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:02.800
And I think that
the largest stars

00:40:02.800 --> 00:40:05.740
in this woodcut simply
represent brighter stars

00:40:05.740 --> 00:40:08.380
and would refer --
therefore refer back

00:40:08.380 --> 00:40:11.750
to the tradition begun
by Piccolomini in 1540,

00:40:11.750 --> 00:40:15.210
as we saw earlier where the
different symbols represent

00:40:15.210 --> 00:40:17.510
different magnitudes.

00:40:32.270 --> 00:40:34.370
Having looked at the
maps of the heavens

00:40:34.370 --> 00:40:38.140
up to Bayer's beautiful
[inaudible] of 1603

00:40:38.140 --> 00:40:41.960
and then the movement of the
planets against the background

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:45.790
of the fixed stars, for the last
part of my talk, I want to look

00:40:45.790 --> 00:40:48.210
at the book to put an
end to speculation,

00:40:48.210 --> 00:40:50.950
if not to controversy.

00:40:54.190 --> 00:40:56.290
In the words of the
great Galileo scholar,

00:40:56.290 --> 00:40:59.160
Albert Van Helden,
after the publication

00:40:59.160 --> 00:41:04.290
of Galileo's <i>Sidereus
Nuncius </i>in 1610, the universe

00:41:04.290 --> 00:41:08.640
and the way in which it was
studied would never be the same.

00:41:08.640 --> 00:41:12.500
The universe would
never be the same.

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:16.370
<i>Sidereus Nuncius </i>, the
"Starry Messenger" was decisive

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:19.120
because instead of debating
with ancient authority

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:21.960
and using complex
geometrical models,

00:41:21.960 --> 00:41:24.700
Galileo used visual arguments.

00:41:24.700 --> 00:41:28.640
He shows us what he
observed for the first time

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:32.650
with the telescope and argues
that this leads inevitably

00:41:32.650 --> 00:41:36.250
to conclusions about the
nature of the universe.

00:41:37.680 --> 00:41:40.690
Digges' speculation that
the more distant stars were

00:41:40.690 --> 00:41:44.230
invisible to the naked eye
was excitedly confirmed

00:41:44.230 --> 00:41:48.890
when Galileo first focused his
telescope on the fixed stars.

00:41:48.890 --> 00:41:52.000
Referring to the classification
of the stars introduced

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:55.310
by Ptolemy, remember the first
magnitude is the brightest

00:41:55.310 --> 00:42:02.150
and the sixth is the faintest,
Galileo writes, "With the glass,

00:42:02.150 --> 00:42:05.580
you will detect below the
stars of the sixth magnitude

00:42:05.580 --> 00:42:08.360
such a crowd of others
that escaped natural sight

00:42:08.360 --> 00:42:10.440
that it is hardly believable.

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:15.520
For you may see more than six
further gradations of magnitude.

00:42:16.930 --> 00:42:20.760
Here, Galileo shows part of
the constellation of Orion

00:42:20.760 --> 00:42:23.540
on the left and the
Pleiades on the right.

00:42:23.540 --> 00:42:26.520
The large open stars
are the ancient stars,

00:42:26.520 --> 00:42:28.890
that is, the naked eye stars.

00:42:28.890 --> 00:42:32.600
The new stars are solid black.

00:42:32.600 --> 00:42:36.350
Of different sizes to
indicate different magnitudes.

00:42:36.350 --> 00:42:40.880
The woodcut on the left shows
the three naked eye stars

00:42:40.880 --> 00:42:43.160
in Orion's belt.

00:42:43.160 --> 00:42:44.460
I'm sure you can see that.

00:42:44.460 --> 00:42:52.280
So here's the belt and then
there are six in Orion's sword.

00:42:53.570 --> 00:42:58.130
Surrounding them are 18 more
stars revealed by the telescope

00:42:58.130 --> 00:43:00.050
and never seen before.

00:43:00.050 --> 00:43:04.880
It's one of the many
puzzles about this book

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:07.520
that the woodcut is
too big for the page.

00:43:07.520 --> 00:43:09.070
In this copy, the star

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:11.900
on the right is almost
full and into the gutter.

00:43:11.900 --> 00:43:13.640
I'm not using fanciful
language here.

00:43:13.640 --> 00:43:15.490
The gutter is the
bibliographer's term

00:43:15.490 --> 00:43:20.150
for the inner margins
of the book.

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:22.350
Even in Galileo's
original drawing,

00:43:22.350 --> 00:43:24.890
the page barely contains
the stars.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:32.230
The printed woodcut follows the
finished drawing very closely

00:43:32.230 --> 00:43:35.470
and the dimensions
are identical.

00:43:35.470 --> 00:43:39.320
In many copies, one or more of
the stars at the top of the page

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:43.280
and one on the left are cropped
or trimmed away by the binder,

00:43:43.280 --> 00:43:44.690
one of the reasons
that the Library

00:43:44.690 --> 00:43:47.350
of Congress' untrimmed
copy which is on show

00:43:47.350 --> 00:43:50.690
in the exhibition
is so important.

00:43:50.690 --> 00:43:53.760
It might be argued that
this is a rhetorical device,

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:55.990
the unbounded page
becomes a metaphor

00:43:55.990 --> 00:43:59.250
for the boundless,
infinite universe.

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:01.610
Whether or not this
was in Galileo's mind,

00:44:01.610 --> 00:44:03.420
it could well have
had this resonance

00:44:03.420 --> 00:44:06.940
for contemporary readers
as it does for us today.

00:44:10.080 --> 00:44:12.780
Now the discovery of the vast
numbers of stars invisible

00:44:12.780 --> 00:44:14.610
to the naked eye is only one

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:18.370
of the discoveries
reported in Galileo's book.

00:44:18.370 --> 00:44:21.560
What made Galileo particularly
anxious to rush his book

00:44:21.560 --> 00:44:25.400
into print was his discovery
of the satellites of Jupiter

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:28.830
which he dedicated to Cosimo
de Medici calling them the

00:44:28.830 --> 00:44:31.190
Medician stars.

00:44:31.190 --> 00:44:35.510
The satellites of Jupiter helps
to confirm the Copernican theory

00:44:35.510 --> 00:44:38.530
by showing that the Earth was
not unique in the solar system

00:44:38.530 --> 00:44:41.270
in having satellites or moons.

00:44:41.270 --> 00:44:44.120
The -- excuse me --

00:44:44.120 --> 00:44:47.240
the <i>Sidereus Nuncius</i>
is a news book

00:44:47.240 --> 00:44:49.870
and Galileo could
easily have been scooped.

00:44:49.870 --> 00:44:54.310
Third of the great
revolutions in the book

00:44:54.310 --> 00:44:57.430
which actually comes first
is Galileo's discovery

00:44:57.430 --> 00:45:00.250
of mountains on the moon.

00:45:00.250 --> 00:45:03.770
This contradicted Aristotelian
orthodoxy that everything

00:45:03.770 --> 00:45:05.940
in the heavens must be
perfect and unchanging

00:45:05.940 --> 00:45:08.030
and the moon, a perfect sphere.

00:45:08.030 --> 00:45:12.950
The impact of the printed
images is remarkable.

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:16.050
Nothing like this in
terms of either the medium

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:19.400
or the message had
been seen before.

00:45:19.400 --> 00:45:23.130
There are four images,
one of which is repeated.

00:45:23.130 --> 00:45:26.000
In the first image,
the new moon is shown

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:27.860
on the fourth or fifth day.

00:45:27.860 --> 00:45:30.220
The terminator, the
division between light

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:34.620
and dark is not a smooth curved
line as seen with the naked eye.

00:45:34.620 --> 00:45:39.030
But the telescope
reveals it to be jagged,

00:45:39.030 --> 00:45:42.050
uneven, on a sinuous curve.

00:45:42.050 --> 00:45:45.520
Several white spots are
seen in the dark areas.

00:45:45.520 --> 00:45:48.160
And dark spots in
the bright areas.

00:45:48.160 --> 00:45:51.190
The white spots gradually
enlarge and merge

00:45:51.190 --> 00:45:52.490
with the bright areas

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:56.850
of the moon while more
appear in the dark part.

00:45:56.850 --> 00:46:01.070
Galileo explains this by analogy
with terrestrial geography.

00:46:01.070 --> 00:46:04.430
Only the peaks of mountains
are illuminated at sunrise

00:46:04.430 --> 00:46:06.180
and the valleys are in shadow.

00:46:06.180 --> 00:46:09.910
But the dark shadows diminish
as the sun climbs higher

00:46:09.910 --> 00:46:13.470
until the whole valley
is flooded with light.

00:46:13.470 --> 00:46:17.810
The first and third
quarters are shown here

00:46:17.810 --> 00:46:19.910
to illustrate how
the shadows cast

00:46:19.910 --> 00:46:24.330
by the sun define the huge
mountains around the large area

00:46:24.330 --> 00:46:27.190
in the upper part of the moon.

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:30.560
Unlike the mountains,
the appearance

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:36.030
of the large ancient spots
on the moon, the ones seen

00:46:36.030 --> 00:46:39.240
with the naked eye, do
not change as the angle

00:46:39.240 --> 00:46:41.090
of illumination changes.

00:46:41.090 --> 00:46:43.170
They might, following
the opinion

00:46:43.170 --> 00:46:44.470
of Pythagoras [inaudible].

00:46:44.470 --> 00:46:51.020
Here, the second image is
repeated and a fourth is added,

00:46:51.020 --> 00:46:53.030
continuing the visual evidence

00:46:53.030 --> 00:46:56.400
for the vast mountain
range in the upper area.

00:46:56.400 --> 00:47:02.170
Now these are etchings,
intaglio plates printed

00:47:02.170 --> 00:47:05.120
on a separate operation
from the text.

00:47:05.120 --> 00:47:07.120
The text was printed first

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:10.550
by the letterpress printer using
a common press on the left,

00:47:10.550 --> 00:47:13.730
in this contemporary
image, leaving blank spaces

00:47:13.730 --> 00:47:15.230
for the illustrations.

00:47:15.230 --> 00:47:18.670
The etchings were then
printed into these spaces

00:47:18.670 --> 00:47:23.230
in a separate workshop
using the rolling press

00:47:23.230 --> 00:47:25.570
which is quite a
different kind of press

00:47:25.570 --> 00:47:26.870
which is shown on the right.

00:47:26.870 --> 00:47:30.150
And as the caption to this
plate explains, this is a press

00:47:30.150 --> 00:47:32.770
for printing images from
incised copper plates.

00:47:36.330 --> 00:47:38.920
The plates are rather
clumsily printed

00:47:38.920 --> 00:47:40.790
with a significant
amount of surface tone.

00:47:40.790 --> 00:47:44.710
And there are ink
deposits on the plate edges

00:47:44.710 --> 00:47:46.920
which have not been
well-cleaned before being put

00:47:46.920 --> 00:47:48.220
to the rolling press.

00:47:48.220 --> 00:47:50.680
So this -- so this is
sort of surface tone.

00:47:50.680 --> 00:47:53.260
It hasn't been cleared off

00:47:53.260 --> 00:47:56.970
and then there are some actual
ink deposits along here.

00:48:00.610 --> 00:48:03.010
The lines and dots of
the image are created

00:48:03.010 --> 00:48:06.210
by etching identified by
the fluidity of the lines

00:48:06.210 --> 00:48:07.510
and the blunt ends

00:48:07.510 --> 00:48:10.440
of the strokes viewed
under magnification.

00:48:10.440 --> 00:48:12.570
The circular outline seems
to have been made with a pair

00:48:12.570 --> 00:48:14.800
of compasses but
rather carelessly

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:17.630
as the lines have
doubled up in places.

00:48:17.630 --> 00:48:22.610
There was little
conventional syntax of lines

00:48:22.610 --> 00:48:25.370
or cross-hatching which we
would expect at this period.

00:48:25.370 --> 00:48:27.140
Both the etching
and the printing

00:48:27.140 --> 00:48:30.100
of the plates seem
amateurish in comparison

00:48:30.100 --> 00:48:33.200
with what one would expect
of etching for this period.

00:48:33.200 --> 00:48:35.340
For example, in the
contemporary,

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:39.950
by the contemporary Venetian
etcher Odoardo Fialetti.

00:48:52.330 --> 00:48:55.980
Original watercolor
drawings by Galileo survive.

00:48:55.980 --> 00:48:59.670
But they are not the direct
originals for the etchings.

00:48:59.670 --> 00:49:02.980
Six moons are shown here and
a seventh is on another half

00:49:02.980 --> 00:49:05.960
of the sheet numbered eight.

00:49:05.960 --> 00:49:08.140
These finished drawings
are presumably based

00:49:08.140 --> 00:49:10.590
on earlier sketches
as the field of view

00:49:10.590 --> 00:49:13.440
of Galileo's telescope could
only take in at most half

00:49:13.440 --> 00:49:15.610
of the moon's surface.

00:49:15.610 --> 00:49:17.810
Galileo could never
have seen the whole disk

00:49:17.810 --> 00:49:21.370
of the moon looking like this.

00:49:21.370 --> 00:49:24.600
The four etchings in the
printed book are even further

00:49:24.600 --> 00:49:28.320
from what was visible through
the telescope on any one night.

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:32.000
In the text, Galileo describes
observations of the surface

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:34.250
of the moon over
several nights but refers

00:49:34.250 --> 00:49:36.980
in each case to the first image.

00:49:36.980 --> 00:49:40.640
The etching is a composite
combining geographical features

00:49:40.640 --> 00:49:43.970
of the lunar surface only
visible on different nights.

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:49.010
Even more extreme
is the appearance

00:49:49.010 --> 00:49:55.550
of the large round crater in the
lower half of the moon's disk.

00:49:55.550 --> 00:49:59.220
The crater on these two images
is derived from earlier sketches

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:03.870
of the crater alone and
drawn to a larger scale.

00:50:03.870 --> 00:50:07.040
These are subsidiary figures.

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:10.640
Overlaying them on the main
image creates a completely

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:12.930
erroneous view of the moon.

00:50:12.930 --> 00:50:17.150
The crater is nowhere near
this big but representing it

00:50:17.150 --> 00:50:20.360
in this way allows
Galileo to argue his point

00:50:20.360 --> 00:50:22.810
without introducing
another etching.

00:50:22.810 --> 00:50:28.540
The four etchings are synthetic
images making a visual argument

00:50:28.540 --> 00:50:30.710
in support of Galileo's
contention

00:50:30.710 --> 00:50:33.950
that the changing appearance
of the moon surface as it waxes

00:50:33.950 --> 00:50:37.780
and wanes are due to the shadows
cast by its physical features,

00:50:37.780 --> 00:50:43.980
huge mountains, valleys, and
seas like those on Earth.

00:50:43.980 --> 00:50:47.340
When the <i>Sidereus Nuncius</i>
was published in 1610,

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:49.790
the dominant form of book
illustration was engraving,

00:50:49.790 --> 00:50:51.280
not etching.

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:54.840
With an established syntax
for representing the effects

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:57.380
of light on uneven surfaces,

00:50:57.380 --> 00:51:01.310
the <i>Sidereus Nuncius </i>was the
messenger bringing the news

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:03.860
of Galileo's discoveries
to the public.

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:06.410
The etchings certainly
gave a sense of immediacy

00:51:06.410 --> 00:51:09.500
to the printed pages
than the stiffer style

00:51:09.500 --> 00:51:13.560
of engraving would have
done which the stiffer style

00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:16.470
of engraving would
not have done.

00:51:16.470 --> 00:51:19.610
The full scientific report
was intended to follow.

00:51:19.610 --> 00:51:23.690
Writing to Cosimo de Medici
in the summer of 1611,

00:51:23.690 --> 00:51:28.020
Galileo informed his patron,
"I want to draw the phases

00:51:28.020 --> 00:51:32.180
of the moon for a whole period
with the utmost diligence

00:51:32.180 --> 00:51:34.730
and imitate them
in minute detail.

00:51:34.730 --> 00:51:37.160
And I want to have
them engraved in copper

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:40.320
by an excellent artist."

00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:43.770
Galileo was well aware that his
images were not accurate maps

00:51:43.770 --> 00:51:47.410
of the lunar surface and the
etchings was somewhat informal

00:51:47.410 --> 00:51:49.350
for a scientific treatise.

00:51:49.350 --> 00:51:52.300
For that, he needed a new
series of observations

00:51:52.300 --> 00:51:55.870
and engravings made by a
professional printmaker.

00:51:55.870 --> 00:51:59.830
In the event, Galileo next
turned his attention to sunspots

00:51:59.830 --> 00:52:03.720
and it was Johannes
Hevelius who, in 1647,

00:52:03.720 --> 00:52:06.570
published the first accurate
engravings of the moon surface

00:52:06.570 --> 00:52:09.510
for a full lunation in
a spectacular series

00:52:09.510 --> 00:52:12.820
of 20 engravings in
an imposing folio.

00:52:12.820 --> 00:52:16.130
But that's another story.

00:52:16.130 --> 00:52:20.690
So where does Galileo
leave us in 1610?

00:52:20.690 --> 00:52:22.870
In 1603, the positions

00:52:22.870 --> 00:52:24.910
of the fixed stars had
been accurately mapped

00:52:24.910 --> 00:52:26.430
by Johann Bayer.

00:52:26.430 --> 00:52:29.740
His beautiful atlas was on the
library tables of the wealthy

00:52:29.740 --> 00:52:33.410
and it was also later used by
astronomers like John Flamsteed.

00:52:33.410 --> 00:52:36.710
As Thomas Digges realized
and Galileo confirmed

00:52:36.710 --> 00:52:39.810
with the telescope,
there were far more stars

00:52:39.810 --> 00:52:41.530
than Bayer had recorded.

00:52:41.530 --> 00:52:44.060
At greater and greater
distances,

00:52:44.060 --> 00:52:46.930
stars are fainter and fainter.

00:52:46.930 --> 00:52:50.080
There must, as Digges
pointed out, be many stars

00:52:50.080 --> 00:52:52.490
which are simply too
faint for us to see.

00:52:52.490 --> 00:52:56.120
Not only was the Earth no longer
the center of the universe

00:52:56.120 --> 00:52:59.200
but the universe
itself had no end.

00:52:59.200 --> 00:53:01.780
The Earth, as Copernicus
had explained,

00:53:01.780 --> 00:53:03.500
was just another planet.

00:53:03.500 --> 00:53:07.400
There are other planets like
ours, other solar systems.

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:11.250
Men in the moon,
extraterrestrial life,

00:53:11.250 --> 00:53:15.750
such speculations were
not long in coming.

00:53:15.750 --> 00:53:18.870
John Wilkins' <i>Discovery of a
World in the Moone </i>published

00:53:18.870 --> 00:53:23.250
in 1638, is an account of the
new world, the new world view

00:53:23.250 --> 00:53:26.110
of Copernicus, Kepler
and Galileo.

00:53:26.110 --> 00:53:30.980
The Galileo moon -- Galilean
moon has Earth-like features

00:53:30.980 --> 00:53:33.480
and says Wilkins
on the title page,

00:53:33.480 --> 00:53:36.530
"Tis probable there may
be another habitable world

00:53:36.530 --> 00:53:38.130
in that planet."

00:53:38.130 --> 00:53:43.800
The image is a woodcut
with type set below it.

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:48.150
A very rare, it's a very rare
case of a title page designed

00:53:48.150 --> 00:53:50.370
as a double page spread.

00:53:50.370 --> 00:53:54.220
This is a very self-conscious
combination of text and image.

00:53:54.220 --> 00:53:55.780
Again, it's no afterthought.

00:53:55.780 --> 00:53:58.810
The makers of this book
put a lot of care into this

00:53:58.810 --> 00:54:00.990
and we need to take
it seriously.

00:54:00.990 --> 00:54:05.570
The woodcut is reproduced
as the top half

00:54:05.570 --> 00:54:07.120
of the engraved title page

00:54:07.120 --> 00:54:10.970
of the second enlarged
edition of Wilkins' book.

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:17.830
Below this, the figures of
Galileo on the left is copied

00:54:17.830 --> 00:54:20.590
from the Latin edition
of Galileo's dialogue

00:54:20.590 --> 00:54:22.790
on the two world systems

00:54:22.790 --> 00:54:25.970
where the other figures
are Aristotle and Ptolemy.

00:54:31.260 --> 00:54:34.710
Copernicus uncertain

00:54:34.710 --> 00:54:39.540
and perplexed says,
"What if it is true?"

00:54:39.540 --> 00:54:43.660
And Galileo gesturing to the
superior vision of the eagle

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:48.780
which his telescope had given
him says, "Here are his eyes."

00:54:48.780 --> 00:54:52.910
And Kepler says, "And his
wings," hinting that to find

00:54:52.910 --> 00:54:55.500
out more, we should fly
to the moon referring

00:54:55.500 --> 00:54:59.050
to his science fiction dream,
<i>Somnium </i>, written in 1608

00:54:59.050 --> 00:55:03.500
and published in 1634, a few
years before Wilkins' discovery.

00:55:03.500 --> 00:55:06.480
The scroll on which the
title is written is a map

00:55:06.480 --> 00:55:08.210
of the moon's surface.

00:55:08.210 --> 00:55:14.020
The top half of the engraving
elaborating on the woodcut

00:55:14.020 --> 00:55:16.560
in the first edition
is a wonderful example

00:55:16.560 --> 00:55:20.310
of how much information can
be packed into a small space.

00:55:20.310 --> 00:55:22.530
And this is only possible
with the fine lines

00:55:22.530 --> 00:55:26.170
of engraving rather than the
coarser lines of woodcut.

00:55:26.170 --> 00:55:29.630
What you see here on the screen
is less than four inches wide.

00:55:29.630 --> 00:55:35.410
Here are the stars of different
magnitudes taken from Digges

00:55:35.410 --> 00:55:38.390
but in the planetary system --
but in the planetary system,

00:55:38.390 --> 00:55:40.700
the planets are on
orbital paths in space,

00:55:40.700 --> 00:55:43.380
not confined to solid spheres.

00:55:43.380 --> 00:55:46.500
The Earth is personified
as Ceres,

00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:48.840
the goddess of agriculture.

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:51.870
With her, with actually
is with her sickle

00:55:51.870 --> 00:55:53.780
and her sheaf of corn.

00:55:53.780 --> 00:55:56.200
She is yearning for her
daughter, Proserpina,

00:55:56.200 --> 00:55:58.700
personified as the moon.

00:55:58.700 --> 00:56:01.900
Combining -- combined
with this is a lesson

00:56:01.900 --> 00:56:05.910
in astronomy demonstrating how
the planets are lit by the sun

00:56:05.910 --> 00:56:08.840
and the phases of the
moon as shown below.

00:56:08.840 --> 00:56:13.380
This is a serious scientific
work, not mere science fiction

00:56:13.380 --> 00:56:15.270
like William Godwin's <i>Man</i>

00:56:15.270 --> 00:56:18.260
<i>in the Moon </i>which was
published in the same year.

00:56:18.260 --> 00:56:24.930
So in conclusion, I hope that I
have shown, I have convinced you

00:56:24.930 --> 00:56:28.470
that the printed book
shaped the universe.

00:56:28.470 --> 00:56:32.090
The production of printed
images was not unproblematic

00:56:32.090 --> 00:56:35.380
but the efforts made by
authors, editors and publishers

00:56:35.380 --> 00:56:39.190
to put ideas into pictorial
form shows how important these

00:56:39.190 --> 00:56:41.010
images were.

00:56:41.010 --> 00:56:45.010
Copernicus' <i>De revolutionibus</i>
is a handsomely produced folio,

00:56:45.010 --> 00:56:48.390
a worthy companion to books
of theology or philosophy.

00:56:48.390 --> 00:56:51.980
Engraving allowed Bayer to
produce more accurate charts

00:56:51.980 --> 00:56:55.140
and provide the opportunity
to present multiple layers

00:56:55.140 --> 00:56:57.660
of allegory and science
in a book

00:56:57.660 --> 00:57:00.690
for both connoisseurs
and astronomers.

00:57:00.690 --> 00:57:04.790
High quality printing
and illustration helped

00:57:04.790 --> 00:57:09.090
to sell these books and not
just to professional scientists.

00:57:09.090 --> 00:57:11.150
These, in turn, helped
to bring the meaning

00:57:11.150 --> 00:57:14.680
of the scientific findings
to a wide audience.

00:57:14.680 --> 00:57:18.060
Images were necessary
for professional readers,

00:57:18.060 --> 00:57:21.500
perhaps even more so for book
owners who were not going

00:57:21.500 --> 00:57:24.740
to follow the science
too closely.

00:57:24.740 --> 00:57:27.670
It is said that we live in
a visual age and I wonder

00:57:27.670 --> 00:57:30.420
if images are significant
to scientific discovery

00:57:30.420 --> 00:57:32.990
and communication
as they once were.

00:57:32.990 --> 00:57:35.110
I'm looking forward to the
lectures on modern science

00:57:35.110 --> 00:57:36.590
in this symposium to learn more.

00:57:36.590 --> 00:57:38.390
Thank you.

00:57:38.390 --> 00:58:10.290
[ Applause ]

