instruments,

00:59:07.970 --> 00:59:11.560
rare books and works on paper.

00:59:11.560 --> 00:59:19.970
Sometime ago, I asked Dr. Raposo
when and why he decided to work

00:59:19.970 --> 00:59:22.350
with heavenly objects.

00:59:22.350 --> 00:59:31.270
He answered, "At the age of 18,
that is, a long, long time ago,

00:59:31.270 --> 00:59:36.930
I founded a local astronomy
club with some friends.

00:59:36.930 --> 00:59:40.210
We often went to
school associations,

00:59:40.210 --> 00:59:45.270
festivities to show the moon
and other celestial objects

00:59:45.270 --> 00:59:52.640
through a telescope to attendees
of all ages and walks of life.

00:59:52.640 --> 00:59:58.400
I always liked to talk about
history topics in these events

00:59:58.400 --> 01:00:03.190
such as Galileo, astronomy
and navigation in the age

01:00:03.190 --> 01:00:06.970
of discoveries, the
discovery of the Uranus."

01:00:09.060 --> 01:00:16.030
"I irrevocably became fascinated
with astronomy around 1993

01:00:16.030 --> 01:00:18.030
when there was a lot of hype

01:00:18.030 --> 01:00:22.750
about the Perseids
meteor shower.

01:00:22.750 --> 01:00:27.340
Even though the shower was
not at least to the eyes

01:00:27.340 --> 01:00:31.990
as a beginner observer in a
factory town in the suburbs

01:00:31.990 --> 01:00:38.350
of Lisbon as spectacular as
the media promised it to be.

01:00:38.350 --> 01:00:45.290
It made me look up and want
to identify the constellations

01:00:45.290 --> 01:00:51.520
and learn more about
astronomy in general."

01:00:51.520 --> 01:00:59.020
Dr. Raposo's talk is about
[inaudible] the heavens size,

01:00:59.020 --> 01:01:04.550
scale and depth in
astronomical illustrations.

01:01:04.550 --> 01:01:06.350
Dr. Raposo?

