01:01:40.590 --> 01:01:43.720
who finds himself
working in an institution

01:01:43.720 --> 01:01:48.890
which some 88 years now, has
been precisely in the business

01:01:48.890 --> 01:01:53.550
of scientific visualization,
the Adler Planetarium in Chicago

01:01:53.550 --> 01:01:57.920
which was the first optical
projection planetarium

01:01:57.920 --> 01:01:59.340
in America.

01:01:59.340 --> 01:02:04.940
And through our sky show,
through our exhibitions,

01:02:04.940 --> 01:02:08.480
through our, for example,
space visualization laboratory

01:02:08.480 --> 01:02:12.380
which is a part of the Adler
where you can go to daily

01:02:12.380 --> 01:02:16.680
and see some really impressive
images and visualizations

01:02:16.680 --> 01:02:18.260
and talk to an expert.

01:02:18.260 --> 01:02:21.400
We've been trying
precisely to visualize

01:02:21.400 --> 01:02:25.090
and to present the heavens
before our audiences.

01:02:25.090 --> 01:02:29.900
I would like to share a brief
story with you, a recent story.

01:02:29.900 --> 01:02:33.910
One of this is I was at one of
our neighbors, the Field Museum

01:02:33.910 --> 01:02:36.250
which is in the Museum
Campus in Chicago.

01:02:36.250 --> 01:02:40.140
And I met one of the volunteers
at the field museum, a lady who,

01:02:40.140 --> 01:02:42.150
when I told her that I
worked, I was curator

01:02:42.150 --> 01:02:44.510
at the Adler Planetarium,
she told me that, "Oh,

01:02:44.510 --> 01:02:46.490
I don't really like
to go to the Adler."

01:02:46.490 --> 01:02:49.040
Well, not a great
beginning of conversation

01:02:49.040 --> 01:02:50.730
but then I asked her,
"So why is that?"

01:02:50.730 --> 01:02:53.950
And she told me, "Well,
because it really reminds me

01:02:53.950 --> 01:02:56.410
that the universe is immense.

01:02:56.410 --> 01:02:59.670
The universe is overwhelming
and it makes me feel small."

01:02:59.670 --> 01:03:01.100
Well then, I felt relieved.

01:03:01.100 --> 01:03:03.020
Okay, we are doing
our job properly then

01:03:03.020 --> 01:03:05.700
because all of that is true.

01:03:05.700 --> 01:03:10.480
But in fact, imagining, more
than imagining the arrangements

01:03:10.480 --> 01:03:12.750
of the spheres in the sky, the
arrangements of the planets

01:03:12.750 --> 01:03:17.470
of the orbits, or imagine
the surfaces of other bodies,

01:03:17.470 --> 01:03:22.390
thinking of the scale, the size
and thinking of space precisely

01:03:22.390 --> 01:03:26.750
as space and our place in it,
is effectively challenged.

01:03:26.750 --> 01:03:31.950
And what I would like to do over
the next 30 minutes or so is

01:03:31.950 --> 01:03:35.520
to take you in a journey
through the Adler Planetarium

01:03:35.520 --> 01:03:40.950
collections to see some examples
and to show you some examples

01:03:40.950 --> 01:03:45.480
of how this three-dimensional
thinking in astronomy

01:03:45.480 --> 01:03:50.420
and in cosmology expressed
itself through the centuries.

01:03:50.420 --> 01:03:55.230
In the Middle Ages, one of
the most important tools

01:03:55.230 --> 01:03:58.210
to teach astronomy was
the armillary sphere

01:03:58.210 --> 01:04:02.770
which appears here in this
lovely manuscript fragment.

01:04:02.770 --> 01:04:06.470
The armillary sphere represents
the central hearth as according

01:04:06.470 --> 01:04:10.210
to Aristotle and Ptolemaic
universe surrounded

01:04:10.210 --> 01:04:13.870
by the major astronomical
circles.

01:04:13.870 --> 01:04:17.850
It is not exactly a physical
model of the universe but more

01:04:17.850 --> 01:04:21.830
of a tool that helps think of
the centrality of the Earth

01:04:21.830 --> 01:04:25.560
and of those astronomical
circles which are fundamental

01:04:25.560 --> 01:04:28.760
to understand every other
motion and phenomena in the sky

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:30.630
as projected in the
celestial field.

01:04:30.630 --> 01:04:34.350
But nonetheless, it did
convey the strong impression

01:04:34.350 --> 01:04:37.050
of the place of the
Earth in the arrangement

01:04:37.050 --> 01:04:39.300
and in the order of things.

01:04:39.300 --> 01:04:41.930
In this frontispiece,

01:04:41.930 --> 01:04:45.630
with French mathematician
Oronce Fine --

01:04:45.630 --> 01:04:48.000
Oronce Fine appears
holding a [inaudible] light

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:51.840
in conversation with the muse
Urania and look that above him,

01:04:51.840 --> 01:04:53.940
we see a complex diagram

01:04:53.940 --> 01:04:58.360
in which the armillary sphere is
combined with a typical diagram

01:04:58.360 --> 01:05:02.290
of the arrangement of the
orbs precisely to give this,

01:05:02.290 --> 01:05:06.250
convey this idea that the
arrangement of the orbs

01:05:06.250 --> 01:05:08.890
and the sphere all
converge in this idea

01:05:08.890 --> 01:05:11.470
of how things are
arranged in the cosmos

01:05:11.470 --> 01:05:18.630
and how motions can be
understood from the idea

01:05:18.630 --> 01:05:21.860
of this relative arrangements.

01:05:21.860 --> 01:05:23.760
Armillary spheres
sometimes were taken

01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:26.330
to high degrees of complexity.

01:05:26.330 --> 01:05:30.480
In this example from 1562,

01:05:30.480 --> 01:05:34.030
by the prominent instrument
maker Gualterus Arsenius,

01:05:34.030 --> 01:05:39.140
the armillary sphere includes a
substantial number of circles.

01:05:39.140 --> 01:05:43.530
It's a very intricate
arrangement that has the purpose

01:05:43.530 --> 01:05:46.250
of simulating different
motions of the heavens

01:05:46.250 --> 01:05:50.040
and explain different
motions in the sky.

01:05:50.040 --> 01:05:51.940
You see that it's a
very elaborate piece

01:05:51.940 --> 01:05:54.550
and even the fact that it
survives [inaudible] suggest

01:05:54.550 --> 01:05:56.920
that well, made by
a prominent maker

01:05:56.920 --> 01:06:01.200
and such an exquisite piece,
more than a teaching tool

01:06:01.200 --> 01:06:04.190
or more than a model of the
universe, it was also a symbol

01:06:04.190 --> 01:06:06.440
of intellectual sophistication.

01:06:06.440 --> 01:06:09.300
And we might guess
maybe of status

01:06:09.300 --> 01:06:12.340
of the owner having the
universe and an object

01:06:12.340 --> 01:06:16.620
that reproduced its
motions basically at hand.

01:06:18.130 --> 01:06:22.650
Some paper engineering was
also used to try to make sense

01:06:22.650 --> 01:06:29.860
of the complex, the complexity
of planetary orbits as presented

01:06:29.860 --> 01:06:34.610
in the works of Ptolemy and then
has explained through the works

01:06:34.610 --> 01:06:37.210
of other authors such
as Georg von Peurbach.

01:06:37.210 --> 01:06:40.470
Here, we see a manuscript,
a [inaudible] manuscript

01:06:40.470 --> 01:06:43.210
with volvelles illustrating
Peurbach's famous Theoricae

01:06:43.210 --> 01:06:46.480
novae planetarium, the new
theories of the planets,

01:06:46.480 --> 01:06:51.260
which was a work that had wider
circulation and was widely used

01:06:51.260 --> 01:06:55.340
as a textbook in the 15th
and in the 16th centuries.

01:06:55.340 --> 01:06:58.880
And what you see on
your left here --

01:06:58.880 --> 01:07:02.890
so this is essentially a paper
device with movable parts

01:07:02.890 --> 01:07:07.800
which would convey to
the user a better sense

01:07:07.800 --> 01:07:12.240
of how the intricate arrangement
of circles and circular motions

01:07:12.240 --> 01:07:15.880
that we heard of in the first
talk actually could explain

01:07:15.880 --> 01:07:20.550
and help predict the position
of a planet in the sky.

01:07:20.550 --> 01:07:23.650
But imagining the
specific arrangement

01:07:23.650 --> 01:07:28.120
for each planet was
actually quite complicated.

01:07:28.120 --> 01:07:30.780
Here we see this illustration
which is almost daunting,

01:07:30.780 --> 01:07:37.600
really, where you see an attempt
of representing well on an image

01:07:37.600 --> 01:07:42.600
on a [inaudible] image
the arrangements in space

01:07:42.600 --> 01:07:46.190
of the specific arrangement
of orbs

01:07:46.190 --> 01:07:50.200
and circles for each planet.

01:07:50.200 --> 01:07:54.080
Some instrument makers undertook
the challenge of turning this

01:07:54.080 --> 01:07:57.080
into a natural three-dimensional
object.

01:07:57.080 --> 01:08:00.980
And what we're going to see
now in the image on your right,

01:08:00.980 --> 01:08:04.110
it's very much resembling
of an armillary sphere

01:08:04.110 --> 01:08:06.270
but it's actually
much more than that.

01:08:06.270 --> 01:08:09.130
While the armillary sphere
was pretty much just the basic

01:08:09.130 --> 01:08:11.210
representation of
the central Earth

01:08:11.210 --> 01:08:13.770
and the major astronomical
circles --

01:08:13.770 --> 01:08:17.820
that object on the right made
by Girolamo Della Volparia

01:08:17.820 --> 01:08:23.320
in Florence, 1582, it's
actually a material realization

01:08:23.320 --> 01:08:27.220
of the Ptolemaic theory
for the orbit of Mercury.

01:08:27.220 --> 01:08:30.060
And you see all the
arrangement of circles

01:08:30.060 --> 01:08:31.740
and how complex it was.

01:08:31.740 --> 01:08:35.090
So these were all
techniques and ideas

01:08:35.090 --> 01:08:38.570
that helped visualize the
complex arrangement of spheres

01:08:38.570 --> 01:08:40.330
that was used to --

01:08:40.330 --> 01:08:44.860
was necessary to explain the
celestial motions according

01:08:44.860 --> 01:08:47.710
to Ptolemy and the
theories of Ptolemy.

01:08:47.710 --> 01:08:51.210
Of course, they have -- with
the advent of the telescope

01:08:51.210 --> 01:08:58.010
and of telescopic observation
and we have heard already,

01:08:58.010 --> 01:09:01.690
we've heard substantially about
it in the first talk, of course,

01:09:01.690 --> 01:09:08.410
that the use of visual evidence
and the use of visual arguments

01:09:08.410 --> 01:09:12.040
to convey telescopic discoveries
and to inform debates

01:09:12.040 --> 01:09:15.450
about what these findings
really meant in terms

01:09:15.450 --> 01:09:16.750
of the order of things.

01:09:16.750 --> 01:09:19.610
Of course, it brings
about new challenges

01:09:19.610 --> 01:09:23.820
and opens new pathways
for visualization

01:09:23.820 --> 01:09:25.800
and for representation.

01:09:25.800 --> 01:09:27.870
And it's not only the
telescope, I think,

01:09:27.870 --> 01:09:30.050
and it's not only
the printed image

01:09:30.050 --> 01:09:34.850
that will help create really a
whole new image of the universe.

01:09:34.850 --> 01:09:37.520
There was already a
background to accommodate all

01:09:37.520 --> 01:09:40.820
of these new visual evidence.

01:09:40.820 --> 01:09:45.020
Developments in perspective
throughout the Renaissance

01:09:45.020 --> 01:09:46.880
[inaudible] new instruments

01:09:46.880 --> 01:09:52.840
to measure the extensive mapping
now extending to the whole world

01:09:52.840 --> 01:09:57.420
and refine old geographical
theories.

01:09:57.420 --> 01:09:59.900
And also the development of
the mapping of the heavens

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:03.390
which is eloquently represented
on your right together

01:10:03.390 --> 01:10:06.230
with the very mapping
of Earth in this image

01:10:06.230 --> 01:10:09.050
from the famous Andreas
Cellarius atlas,

01:10:09.050 --> 01:10:10.810
<i>Harmonia Macrocosmica </i>.

01:10:10.810 --> 01:10:13.040
All of these provides
a background

01:10:13.040 --> 01:10:16.510
in which visualization
of the universe,

01:10:16.510 --> 01:10:21.240
of its and of the celestial
objects will reach new heights.

01:10:21.240 --> 01:10:24.360
The old diagrams
showing the arrangements

01:10:24.360 --> 01:10:26.710
of the orbs will
still be widely used

01:10:26.710 --> 01:10:31.750
and they are still very
helpful to help situate

01:10:31.750 --> 01:10:38.850
and to illustrate the different
arrangements that are central

01:10:38.850 --> 01:10:41.790
to the debates of
the mid-17th century.

01:10:41.790 --> 01:10:43.440
So here we see Ptolemy here.

01:10:43.440 --> 01:10:47.190
This is the frontispiece of
Giovanni Battista Riccioli's

01:10:47.190 --> 01:10:50.590
"Almagestum novum" from 1651.

01:10:50.590 --> 01:10:55.350
And what we see here is pretty
much the visual synthesis

01:10:55.350 --> 01:10:59.270
of mid-17th century astronomy.

01:10:59.270 --> 01:11:05.970
You have here -- here, you
have Ptolemy basically assuming

01:11:05.970 --> 01:11:09.820
that he was wrong and his
system here is pretty much

01:11:09.820 --> 01:11:11.120
on the corner.

01:11:11.120 --> 01:11:14.800
And you see that Astraea or
what seems to be some kind

01:11:14.800 --> 01:11:19.090
of crossing between Astraea, the
goddess of justice and Urania,

01:11:19.090 --> 01:11:23.710
the muse of astronomy -- she is
weighing two competing systems,

01:11:23.710 --> 01:11:27.750
the system of Copernicus
and Riccioli's own version

01:11:27.750 --> 01:11:31.860
of the system of Tycho Brahe
whose basic principle is

01:11:31.860 --> 01:11:35.590
that you let the Earth
stay at the center

01:11:35.590 --> 01:11:39.890
but you put the sun
orbiting the Earth

01:11:39.890 --> 01:11:43.770
and then you can reason planets
orbiting the sun and in the case

01:11:43.770 --> 01:11:48.070
of Riccioli's own system, two
planets still orbit the Earth.

01:11:48.070 --> 01:11:52.410
And the trick was that
with a model like this,

01:11:52.410 --> 01:11:55.510
you could still explain
and accommodate things

01:11:55.510 --> 01:11:57.250
that you observed
with the telescope.

01:11:57.250 --> 01:12:01.700
So she has, for example, the
phases of Venus and Mercury.

01:12:01.700 --> 01:12:04.960
So there was no decisive
argument besides the issue

01:12:04.960 --> 01:12:08.060
of stellar parallax which
was impossible to measure

01:12:08.060 --> 01:12:09.450
at this point in history.

01:12:09.450 --> 01:12:12.230
And that was already
mentioned in the first talk.

01:12:12.230 --> 01:12:15.100
But there was no
decisive proof yet.

01:12:15.100 --> 01:12:18.640
But what's really fascinating
here is that if you look

01:12:18.640 --> 01:12:23.720
to the upper corners
of the frontispiece,

01:12:23.720 --> 01:12:27.190
you see the planets
represented with features

01:12:27.190 --> 01:12:30.390
that could be already
observed with the telescope.

01:12:30.390 --> 01:12:32.580
Note, for example,
the bands in Jupiter

01:12:32.580 --> 01:12:34.960
and the satellites
of Jupiter around it.

01:12:34.960 --> 01:12:39.820
And here, a planet that is
very familiar and recognizable,

01:12:39.820 --> 01:12:42.120
Saturn with its rings.

01:12:42.120 --> 01:12:45.740
And Saturn was precisely one
of the bodies that boast one

01:12:45.740 --> 01:12:49.610
of the major challenges
in terms of visualization.

01:12:49.610 --> 01:12:51.940
The varying appearances
of Saturn as seen

01:12:51.940 --> 01:12:54.840
through a telescope through
time was very intriguing.

01:12:54.840 --> 01:12:57.600
So for decades, since
Galileo first observed it

01:12:57.600 --> 01:13:02.240
with the telescope and
throughout the 1620s and 1630s,

01:13:02.240 --> 01:13:03.540
it was very intriguing

01:13:03.540 --> 01:13:06.790
to see Saturn showing sometimes
it had the appearance --

01:13:06.790 --> 01:13:08.610
it seemed that it
had two satellites,

01:13:08.610 --> 01:13:11.200
sometimes you could
see what astronomers

01:13:11.200 --> 01:13:14.820
at the time called
[inaudible] or handles.

01:13:14.820 --> 01:13:17.920
But it was difficult to figure
out what this really was.

01:13:17.920 --> 01:13:20.120
It was Christiaan Huygens,
the author of the book

01:13:20.120 --> 01:13:22.760
in which this illustration
appears,

01:13:22.760 --> 01:13:27.280
the book called <i>Systema
Saturnium </i>published in 1659,

01:13:27.280 --> 01:13:31.440
that came up with a
consistent explanation.

01:13:31.440 --> 01:13:35.760
He used good telescopes that he
built himself which are now some

01:13:35.760 --> 01:13:39.100
of the -- those telescopes are
now in the Boerhaave Museum

01:13:39.100 --> 01:13:40.770
in Leiden in the Netherlands.

01:13:40.770 --> 01:13:44.880
But he also made analogies
between the Earth-moon system.

01:13:44.880 --> 01:13:49.330
He also discovered the first
satellite of Saturn, Titan.

01:13:49.330 --> 01:13:51.020
And he also used some principles

01:13:51.020 --> 01:13:54.690
from the mechanistic
philosophy of Rene Descartes.

01:13:54.690 --> 01:13:58.150
So using all of these, but
above all, trying to figure

01:13:58.150 --> 01:14:04.280
out the relative positions of
the Earth and Saturn in the sky

01:14:04.280 --> 01:14:06.920
and imagining that
Saturn has a ring.

01:14:06.920 --> 01:14:10.080
He comes up with what
is basically the correct

01:14:10.080 --> 01:14:13.820
explanation in this very
striking illustration.

01:14:13.820 --> 01:14:17.340
So what you see here,
so you have the sun

01:14:17.340 --> 01:14:19.930
at the center, the Earth.

01:14:19.930 --> 01:14:27.310
And then you have Saturn with
its ring and what the outer ring

01:14:27.310 --> 01:14:32.150
of images actually shows to
you is how Saturn when seen

01:14:32.150 --> 01:14:34.730
from the Earth with a
telescope in a certain position

01:14:34.730 --> 01:14:36.870
and a certain relative
arrangement,

01:14:36.870 --> 01:14:39.650
what is the impression that
it produces in the telescope?

01:14:39.650 --> 01:14:44.810
And this image is quite
remarkable because it's not just

01:14:44.810 --> 01:14:46.920
about explaining the
different positions

01:14:46.920 --> 01:14:50.050
of the celestial bodies in
the sky but also an appeal

01:14:50.050 --> 01:14:52.690
to reposition the observer.

01:14:52.690 --> 01:14:55.640
So imagine what the
perspective of the observer is

01:14:55.640 --> 01:14:57.900
and what the relative
disposition

01:14:57.900 --> 01:14:59.600
of bodies in space are.

01:14:59.600 --> 01:15:04.280
And so, this is really
remarkable and this is really

01:15:04.280 --> 01:15:08.730
to a great extent, it's a
turning point in the way

01:15:08.730 --> 01:15:11.110
of visualizing things in space.

01:15:11.110 --> 01:15:15.650
Throughout the 18th century,
these objects, the orreries,

01:15:15.650 --> 01:15:20.230
mechanical models of the solar
system in which you have --

01:15:20.230 --> 01:15:23.820
well, a record of visual
mechanical representation

01:15:23.820 --> 01:15:27.060
of the Copernican and now, of
course, of the Newtonian view

01:15:27.060 --> 01:15:31.790
of the universe, of the planets
in their orbits around the sun.

01:15:31.790 --> 01:15:34.080
Orreries are extremely important

01:15:34.080 --> 01:15:37.900
in showing not just the
arrangement of the planets

01:15:37.900 --> 01:15:39.310
but also showing the order

01:15:39.310 --> 01:15:41.600
of the celestial
motions in the sky.

01:15:41.600 --> 01:15:44.960
And there is a rich
iconography about the orrery,

01:15:44.960 --> 01:15:48.110
this is probably one of the most
striking images of the orrery,

01:15:48.110 --> 01:15:50.550
the famous painting
by Joseph Wright

01:15:50.550 --> 01:15:53.650
which is [inaudible]
in an engraving.

01:15:53.650 --> 01:15:58.700
And you can see those three
children and one philosopher

01:15:58.700 --> 01:16:04.360
in the audience around the
orrery having this lively image

01:16:04.360 --> 01:16:06.650
of things moving in space.

01:16:06.650 --> 01:16:09.120
The Newtonian order
of the universe

01:16:09.120 --> 01:16:14.320
which also carried a metaphor
of a moral order, of the harmony

01:16:14.320 --> 01:16:17.270
of things, the harmony of the
heavens which was the same kind

01:16:17.270 --> 01:16:20.170
of moral harmony
that we were supposed

01:16:20.170 --> 01:16:22.120
to look for in our lives.

01:16:22.120 --> 01:16:24.890
Perhaps most of the times
unsuccessfully but still --

01:16:24.890 --> 01:16:27.070
still a powerful metaphor.

01:16:27.070 --> 01:16:31.850
And even in the 19th century,
when the orrery, now competed

01:16:31.850 --> 01:16:35.350
with many other technologies
of visualization,

01:16:35.350 --> 01:16:38.160
the idea of the orrery as
something that provides a sort

01:16:38.160 --> 01:16:41.950
of a key to the true
arrangements in motions

01:16:41.950 --> 01:16:44.430
of planets in the sky
is still very strong.

01:16:44.430 --> 01:16:47.790
Here on the left,
you see a plate

01:16:47.790 --> 01:16:51.030
from <i>Smith's Illustrated
Astronomy </i>,

01:16:51.030 --> 01:16:53.830
sort of a visual textbook in
astronomy that was produced.

01:16:53.830 --> 01:16:55.500
There were several editions

01:16:55.500 --> 01:16:58.840
and I suppose it must have
been widely used in schools

01:16:58.840 --> 01:17:02.470
in the U.S. And see, you look
here, the teacher is pointing

01:17:02.470 --> 01:17:07.250
at a diagram, a flat diagram
of the orbits of the planets

01:17:07.250 --> 01:17:10.370
and here, apparently
another teacher is pointing

01:17:10.370 --> 01:17:11.670
at Saturn in the model.

01:17:11.670 --> 01:17:13.600
And there's a figure
here which, of course,

01:17:13.600 --> 01:17:17.160
very beautifully we imagine is
putting, cranking the orrery

01:17:17.160 --> 01:17:18.700
and putting it in motion.

01:17:18.700 --> 01:17:20.920
[Inaudible] that it can
make this connection

01:17:20.920 --> 01:17:24.460
between the motions in the
model and the actual motions

01:17:24.460 --> 01:17:27.390
in the sky and answer
the problem.

01:17:27.390 --> 01:17:29.450
And that's a striking
image shows to you,

01:17:29.450 --> 01:17:31.810
the image on the
right shows you.

01:17:31.810 --> 01:17:35.370
You see Urania taking a young
lady who's looking at the orrery

01:17:35.370 --> 01:17:37.260
and she's taking
her to the heavens

01:17:37.260 --> 01:17:42.260
so the orrery is the very
key to the arrangements

01:17:42.260 --> 01:17:44.130
and the order of the planets.

01:17:44.130 --> 01:17:46.600
And the orrery is certainly
one of the ancestors

01:17:46.600 --> 01:17:51.150
of my own institution,
the Adler Planetarium.

01:17:51.150 --> 01:17:54.570
Here, we can see on the
left, you see the first model

01:17:54.570 --> 01:17:59.120
of a project planetarium
from 1925 made

01:17:59.120 --> 01:18:00.610
by the Carl Zeiss Company.

01:18:00.610 --> 01:18:03.960
And there, you can
see model number two

01:18:03.960 --> 01:18:07.300
which was the projector that was
set up at the Adler Planetarium

01:18:07.300 --> 01:18:11.900
in 1930 and which again, was the
first of its kind in America.

01:18:11.900 --> 01:18:13.200
It's important to remember

01:18:13.200 --> 01:18:16.260
that even though
originally the planetarium,

01:18:16.260 --> 01:18:18.030
the planetarium projector
was meant

01:18:18.030 --> 01:18:20.180
to reproduce what
we can actually see

01:18:20.180 --> 01:18:22.200
in the sky outdoors in the dome.

01:18:22.200 --> 01:18:25.110
Basically, it brought
the heavens indoors.

01:18:25.110 --> 01:18:29.110
But in the origins of the
orrery was the intention

01:18:29.110 --> 01:18:34.530
to create a connection as an
experience between what you see

01:18:34.530 --> 01:18:37.730
in the actual sky and what
the actual arrangement

01:18:37.730 --> 01:18:39.840
of the planets in space are.

01:18:39.840 --> 01:18:43.540
So the concept of the projection
planetarium was originally

01:18:43.540 --> 01:18:46.370
developed intended
as a counterpart

01:18:46.370 --> 01:18:49.210
to a Copernican orrery.

01:18:49.210 --> 01:18:50.510
So and the projector,

01:18:50.510 --> 01:18:54.050
the planetarium projector was
originally called the Ptolemaic

01:18:54.050 --> 01:18:57.010
planetarium precisely
because it brings us back

01:18:57.010 --> 01:18:58.690
to the geocentric perspective.

01:18:58.690 --> 01:19:00.890
And so the very idea
in the beginning was

01:19:00.890 --> 01:19:02.190
to create this connection

01:19:02.190 --> 01:19:04.230
between that geocentric
perspective

01:19:04.230 --> 01:19:08.480
and the actual arrangements
of the orbits of the planets

01:19:08.480 --> 01:19:11.390
in the sky and you see that in
this Copernican planetarium.

01:19:11.390 --> 01:19:15.070
You have a moving platform and
there's a gentleman here looking

01:19:15.070 --> 01:19:17.000
for some kind of periscope.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:20.380
And is looking at the
orrery in the ceiling.

01:19:20.380 --> 01:19:22.180
And supposedly what he's seeing

01:19:22.180 --> 01:19:26.770
in through the periscope is
how the planets would appear

01:19:26.770 --> 01:19:29.580
in profile in the actual sky.

01:19:29.580 --> 01:19:32.490
Now, one of the things
that planetariums and all

01:19:32.490 --> 01:19:36.040
of these models could not
convey efficiently was the idea

01:19:36.040 --> 01:19:39.100
of the true size,
the true dimensions

01:19:39.100 --> 01:19:43.050
of both the planets
and their orbits.

01:19:43.050 --> 01:19:45.860
And this has always been
a very important question.

01:19:45.860 --> 01:19:49.790
So in the 17th century, debates
about the sizes of stars,

01:19:49.790 --> 01:19:53.880
for example, were extremely
important in discussions

01:19:53.880 --> 01:19:56.610
about the actual
cosmological arrangement.

01:19:56.610 --> 01:19:57.910
Was Tycho right?

01:19:57.910 --> 01:19:59.420
Was Copernicus right?

01:19:59.420 --> 01:20:03.010
And the sizes of the stars
together with the debates

01:20:03.010 --> 01:20:06.140
about it being possible or
not to determine the parallax

01:20:06.140 --> 01:20:08.080
of stars, this was
extremely important

01:20:08.080 --> 01:20:11.050
in the cosmological
debates of the periods.

01:20:11.050 --> 01:20:12.410
Here we see going back

01:20:12.410 --> 01:20:15.600
to Andreas Cellarius'
<i>Harmonia Macrocosmica </i>,

01:20:15.600 --> 01:20:19.490
here we have again a very
striking illustration

01:20:19.490 --> 01:20:22.710
which pretty much I won't dare
say it was the first of its kind

01:20:22.710 --> 01:20:27.690
but sets up a visual convention
that will be extensively used

01:20:27.690 --> 01:20:30.680
in the following centers
to show relative sizes

01:20:30.680 --> 01:20:32.880
and dimensions of
celestial bodies.

01:20:32.880 --> 01:20:36.810
So basically, what this
image does is to superimpose

01:20:36.810 --> 01:20:40.960
in a single representation
bodies of different sizes

01:20:40.960 --> 01:20:44.900
as they were derived on the
basis of Ptolemy's theory.

01:20:44.900 --> 01:20:46.920
So basically, you
have the moon here.

01:20:46.920 --> 01:20:49.940
You have a scale here
which is marked in --

01:20:49.940 --> 01:20:51.770
sorry, you have the Earth here.

01:20:51.770 --> 01:20:53.070
So this is the Earth.

01:20:53.070 --> 01:20:54.550
And so basically, the diameter

01:20:54.550 --> 01:20:58.260
of the Earth is the
unit, the basic unit.

01:20:58.260 --> 01:21:00.430
And then you have
several bodies.

01:21:00.430 --> 01:21:04.110
You have the planets
and you also have stars

01:21:04.110 --> 01:21:07.290
that were supposedly of
different sizes according

01:21:07.290 --> 01:21:10.050
to their brightness which is
a conception that, of course,

01:21:10.050 --> 01:21:11.710
we know now that
it's not correct

01:21:11.710 --> 01:21:13.010
but that's not the point.

01:21:13.010 --> 01:21:17.680
This is a very powerful way of
representing the different sizes

01:21:17.680 --> 01:21:21.260
of celestial bodies by
showing their proportional

01:21:21.260 --> 01:21:22.900
relative sizes.

01:21:22.900 --> 01:21:25.130
It's Christiaan Huygens again

01:21:25.130 --> 01:21:32.190
who apparently is among the
first to use the same kind

01:21:32.190 --> 01:21:34.320
of convention [inaudible]
to convey the idea

01:21:34.320 --> 01:21:37.420
of the planets according
to the Copernican system.

01:21:37.420 --> 01:21:40.640
So in his <i>Kosmotheorus </i>which
was published posthumously

01:21:40.640 --> 01:21:45.070
and which is work in which
Huygens very much speculates

01:21:45.070 --> 01:21:48.210
about the possibility
of life existing

01:21:48.210 --> 01:21:51.040
in the other planets
based on the principle

01:21:51.040 --> 01:21:53.030
that the other planets again,

01:21:53.030 --> 01:21:54.670
must be pretty much
like the Earth.

01:21:54.670 --> 01:21:58.090
They simply, they are different
in size and in appearance

01:21:58.090 --> 01:21:59.390
but they must be the same thing.

01:21:59.390 --> 01:22:02.320
So they must have
their own inhabitants.

01:22:02.320 --> 01:22:04.900
And of course, with
developments in telescopes

01:22:04.900 --> 01:22:08.640
and in the growing use of the
telescope as a measuring device,

01:22:08.640 --> 01:22:11.000
a better knowledge --
sorry, a better knowledge

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:13.920
of planetary diameters
and the dimensions

01:22:13.920 --> 01:22:18.990
of the planets now allows
Huygens to create his model

01:22:18.990 --> 01:22:21.620
in which he represents the sun

01:22:21.620 --> 01:22:25.610
and then he can show the
relative sizes of the planets

01:22:25.610 --> 01:22:28.050
as compared to that of the sun.

01:22:28.050 --> 01:22:31.890
And of course, you see here
that the internal planets, Mars,

01:22:31.890 --> 01:22:36.130
the Earth, Venus and --
Mercury, Venus, the Earth

01:22:36.130 --> 01:22:38.510
and Mars are very, very small.

01:22:38.510 --> 01:22:42.370
But again, for Huygens, it was
essentially a matter of size

01:22:42.370 --> 01:22:44.160
and appearance because
he considered

01:22:44.160 --> 01:22:46.510
that all planets
potentially could have their

01:22:46.510 --> 01:22:47.830
own inhabitants.

01:22:47.830 --> 01:22:50.420
The same kind of
convention then will appear

01:22:50.420 --> 01:22:52.370
in different types
of publications.

01:22:52.370 --> 01:22:56.360
For example, in broadsides
which were popular publications

01:22:56.360 --> 01:22:58.630
that were aimed at a
variety of audiences,

01:22:58.630 --> 01:23:01.590
here we have a broadside
on the left.

01:23:01.590 --> 01:23:03.640
We have a broadside
by William Whiston,

01:23:03.640 --> 01:23:07.640
<i>A Scheme of the Solar System</i>
from around 1720 and you see

01:23:07.640 --> 01:23:10.640
that this is meant to represent
the arrangements of the orbits

01:23:10.640 --> 01:23:14.770
of the planets, also in there
with their relative sizes.

01:23:14.770 --> 01:23:16.910
And then you see
that's superimposed

01:23:16.910 --> 01:23:20.050
to this illustration which
also shows you the orbits

01:23:20.050 --> 01:23:23.050
of the comets, you
also have this diagram

01:23:23.050 --> 01:23:27.600
that again shows the relative
dimensions of the planets.

01:23:27.600 --> 01:23:30.170
Same thing here in
this illustration

01:23:30.170 --> 01:23:35.440
from 1763 from the Netherlands.

01:23:35.440 --> 01:23:40.740
And some authors will add
further visual strategies

01:23:40.740 --> 01:23:45.090
to convey further, convey this
idea of distances, of sizes

01:23:45.090 --> 01:23:48.580
and importantly, to
make the observer

01:23:48.580 --> 01:23:51.590
and the reader reposition
herself

01:23:51.590 --> 01:23:54.000
or himself in other worlds.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:23:55.520
So here in this plate

01:23:55.520 --> 01:23:59.800
from <i>Astronomy Explained upon
Sir Isaac Newton's Principles</i>

01:23:59.800 --> 01:24:02.660
Mwhich was an extremely
important book and plenty

01:24:02.660 --> 01:24:05.980
of editions throughout the 18th
century, very important book

01:24:05.980 --> 01:24:08.500
in the popularization
of the ideas of Newton,

01:24:08.500 --> 01:24:12.400
James Ferguson was himself a
very keen popularizer and maker

01:24:12.400 --> 01:24:14.270
of scientific instruments.

01:24:14.270 --> 01:24:17.750
And you see that here, you
have very much the same kind

01:24:17.750 --> 01:24:21.570
of conventions showing the
relative dimensions of orbits,

01:24:21.570 --> 01:24:23.730
showing the different
sizes of the planets

01:24:23.730 --> 01:24:26.330
in proportion to each other.

01:24:26.330 --> 01:24:30.560
But here, this is a
remarkable addition.

01:24:30.560 --> 01:24:34.840
What you see here is basically
the apparent size of the sun

01:24:34.840 --> 01:24:37.390
as seen from the
different planets beginning

01:24:37.390 --> 01:24:42.760
with from Mercury to -- this
one goes from Mercury to Saturn.

01:24:42.760 --> 01:24:46.040
And this is remarkable
because this is not just

01:24:46.040 --> 01:24:50.610
about showing different sizes
or showing different dimensions

01:24:50.610 --> 01:24:55.260
but again, appealing to the
observer and to the reader to go

01:24:55.260 --> 01:24:58.020
to different locations and
imagine how things would be seen

01:24:58.020 --> 01:25:00.700
from different locations.

01:25:02.160 --> 01:25:05.410
Here in this illustration
from <i>A Compendious System</i>

01:25:05.410 --> 01:25:07.670
<i>of Astronomy </i>by
Margaret Bryan,

01:25:07.670 --> 01:25:10.440
we see very much the
same kind of conventions.

01:25:10.440 --> 01:25:11.740
And it's interesting to note

01:25:11.740 --> 01:25:16.080
that these visual strategies
will appear throughout a large

01:25:16.080 --> 01:25:20.140
number of different
publications in which the image

01:25:20.140 --> 01:25:23.850
of the solar system
itself, it's changing.

01:25:23.850 --> 01:25:26.220
Notice here, for
example, "Georgium Sidus"

01:25:26.220 --> 01:25:28.920
which eventually was
renamed as Uranus.

01:25:28.920 --> 01:25:33.390
So this diagram already shows a
new planet that has been added

01:25:33.390 --> 01:25:36.470
to the inventory of
the known planets.

01:25:36.470 --> 01:25:38.200
And the more things
were discovered

01:25:38.200 --> 01:25:41.380
and during the first
half of the 19th century,

01:25:41.380 --> 01:25:44.110
several asteroids
were discovered

01:25:44.110 --> 01:25:47.620
and they were generally
considered as planets, at least,

01:25:47.620 --> 01:25:50.170
as long as you could still
include them in the model

01:25:50.170 --> 01:25:52.990
of the solar system, you
could still call them planets.

01:25:52.990 --> 01:25:56.540
By the mid-19th century,
perhaps around 10 were known.

01:25:56.540 --> 01:25:59.290
By the late, by the end of the
19th century, 500 were known

01:25:59.290 --> 01:26:01.730
and so eventually, they
had to be reclassified

01:26:01.730 --> 01:26:03.030
as a group of their own.

01:26:03.030 --> 01:26:06.090
But before of that, they were
entitled to their own presence

01:26:06.090 --> 01:26:07.860
in diagrams of the solar system.

01:26:07.860 --> 01:26:09.470
And here, you see
again from Asa Smith,

01:26:09.470 --> 01:26:12.800
here you see a diagram
showing the sizes

01:26:12.800 --> 01:26:15.210
of the planets including
the asteroids.

01:26:15.210 --> 01:26:17.330
And here is a very
interesting diagram

01:26:17.330 --> 01:26:21.160
which shows the relative
inclinations of the orbits

01:26:21.160 --> 01:26:25.230
of the planets in the solar
system, a very intricate image

01:26:25.230 --> 01:26:30.090
because it also includes
the asteroids.

01:26:30.090 --> 01:26:33.820
This was a period when
there was a growing market

01:26:33.820 --> 01:26:37.060
and a growing demand for
this kind of publication.

01:26:37.060 --> 01:26:39.030
There's a growing middle class.

01:26:39.030 --> 01:26:42.070
There's a growing
access to education.

01:26:42.070 --> 01:26:44.840
And of course, instrument
makers and printers try

01:26:44.840 --> 01:26:47.530
to take advantage of
these new market niches.

01:26:47.530 --> 01:26:51.430
This was also a period when
the techniques of projection

01:26:51.430 --> 01:26:56.370
and the Magic Lantern was
widely used in public lectures

01:26:56.370 --> 01:26:59.480
and widely used to convey
ideas about astronomy

01:26:59.480 --> 01:27:04.710
and other fields to
general audiences.

01:27:04.710 --> 01:27:06.670
Here we see a rather
remarkable example

01:27:06.670 --> 01:27:10.870
of how these visual [inaudible]
to convey the different sizes

01:27:10.870 --> 01:27:12.860
of the planets and
the different --

01:27:12.860 --> 01:27:16.970
and the distances and sizes of
their orbits appears in a set

01:27:16.970 --> 01:27:19.310
of transparencies
which how the idea is

01:27:19.310 --> 01:27:22.250
that he would hold the
transparency against the source

01:27:22.250 --> 01:27:24.260
of light and he -- and this,

01:27:24.260 --> 01:27:26.840
the image here would
gain vivid color.

01:27:26.840 --> 01:27:30.900
So it was in a sense bringing
the techniques of projection

01:27:30.900 --> 01:27:34.730
and the magic -- the
effect of the Magic Lantern

01:27:34.730 --> 01:27:37.170
to a small group,
a small audience

01:27:37.170 --> 01:27:41.130
and maybe more even a
domestic environment.

01:27:42.220 --> 01:27:46.080
This form of visual
representation is very enduring.

01:27:46.080 --> 01:27:49.040
We still use it nowadays
everywhere in planetaria

01:27:49.040 --> 01:27:50.730
and in science museums
all over the world.

01:27:50.730 --> 01:27:53.430
This is a gallery at
the Adler planetarium.

01:27:53.430 --> 01:27:57.170
And here, you have the
planets of the solar system,

01:27:57.170 --> 01:27:58.470
the Solar System Gallery.

01:27:58.470 --> 01:28:03.000
And we basically have the
planets at their relative sizes

01:28:03.000 --> 01:28:07.750
and here, you can see this is
the top of one of our theaters.

01:28:07.750 --> 01:28:09.630
And so that stands for the sun

01:28:09.630 --> 01:28:12.050
and these are the relative
sizes of the planets.

01:28:12.050 --> 01:28:13.450
This is very much reminiscence.

01:28:13.450 --> 01:28:15.870
You will see this kind of
thing in science museums

01:28:15.870 --> 01:28:17.430
and planetaria all
over the world.

01:28:17.430 --> 01:28:21.450
And this is very reminiscent
of the visual conventions

01:28:21.450 --> 01:28:23.280
and the strategies
that we just saw

01:28:23.280 --> 01:28:25.990
in those publications
and illustrations.

01:28:25.990 --> 01:28:27.570
Now, we always have
to challenge that.

01:28:27.570 --> 01:28:31.150
If you want to combine
the scale of the planets

01:28:31.150 --> 01:28:33.520
with the actual scale of
the orbits, in that case,

01:28:33.520 --> 01:28:38.140
it helps if you use a whole
city because the scale is

01:28:38.140 --> 01:28:41.800
so overwhelming that we cannot
really combine it efficiently

01:28:41.800 --> 01:28:43.350
within a planetarium.

01:28:43.350 --> 01:28:46.660
So this is again, this
is a kind of installation

01:28:46.660 --> 01:28:49.950
that you will also see in
different science sites

01:28:49.950 --> 01:28:52.640
and science museums and
planetaria all over the world.

01:28:52.640 --> 01:28:54.310
So we did at the
Adler Planetarium,

01:28:54.310 --> 01:28:58.400
we've been using 2015 and
so the idea is that in order

01:28:58.400 --> 01:29:04.180
to [inaudible] the scale
of the solar system,

01:29:04.180 --> 01:29:08.300
we would have the sun basically
at the door of the planetarium

01:29:08.300 --> 01:29:10.240
and then we will have the orbits

01:29:10.240 --> 01:29:13.470
of the planets extending
throughout the city.

01:29:13.470 --> 01:29:17.790
So it will be a 10-minute walk
to Mars which would be right

01:29:17.790 --> 01:29:19.570
by the Field Museum
and the Shedd Aquarium.

01:29:19.570 --> 01:29:22.290
But if you want to reach
Pluto, and of course,

01:29:22.290 --> 01:29:23.590
we have to include Pluto,

01:29:23.590 --> 01:29:26.970
not to hurt anyone's feelings
[laughter], you would have

01:29:26.970 --> 01:29:30.370
to go almost to Evanston to
the very limits of the city.

01:29:30.370 --> 01:29:34.440
So you would have the
super-imposition of well,

01:29:34.440 --> 01:29:38.190
the scale of the solar system
with the scale of the city

01:29:38.190 --> 01:29:39.830
which is a kind of
[inaudible] that they use

01:29:39.830 --> 01:29:43.810
to basically create the
sense of familiarity with all

01:29:43.810 --> 01:29:46.000
of these overwhelming scales.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:47.830
And I think the word
familiarity,

01:29:47.830 --> 01:29:50.050
it's very important here.

01:29:50.050 --> 01:29:52.470
But still, I think
nothing is compare --

01:29:52.470 --> 01:29:55.900
when we deal with scales and
sizes, we're still dealing

01:29:55.900 --> 01:29:58.150
at the very geometrical
and abstract level.

01:29:58.150 --> 01:30:01.080
I think nothing is more
compelling than natural,

01:30:01.080 --> 01:30:05.760
actually thinking of the
planets as actual places.

01:30:05.760 --> 01:30:10.070
And I think this sense of place,
it's pretty much what is --

01:30:10.070 --> 01:30:13.910
it underlies the space age
really because you don't,

01:30:13.910 --> 01:30:17.380
you don't send spacecraft
to moving dots in the sky.

01:30:17.380 --> 01:30:20.810
You send spacecraft to
places where you would expect

01:30:20.810 --> 01:30:25.060
to find some kind of
landscape topography features.

01:30:25.060 --> 01:30:27.440
Of course, the telescope
gave faces

01:30:27.440 --> 01:30:29.660
and features to the planets.

01:30:29.660 --> 01:30:32.540
And I find these plates
from Alain Mallet,

01:30:32.540 --> 01:30:36.970
this <i>Description de l'Univers</i>
from 1686, very striking

01:30:36.970 --> 01:30:39.940
because clearly, he
doesn't respect the scale

01:30:39.940 --> 01:30:43.010
and he presents the planets just

01:30:43.010 --> 01:30:45.800
against these bucolic
landscapes.

01:30:45.800 --> 01:30:48.530
But I think the fact that
he doesn't respect scale,

01:30:48.530 --> 01:30:51.280
he wants certainly to create
a compelling visual effect

01:30:51.280 --> 01:30:56.230
and I think there is some, there
is some kind of statement here

01:30:56.230 --> 01:30:58.240
that the planets have --

01:30:58.240 --> 01:31:01.280
are also part of our
cosmic landscape in a sense.

01:31:01.280 --> 01:31:04.020
And they have their own
features, their own landscapes

01:31:04.020 --> 01:31:07.520
and their own spatiality
as things here on Earth.

01:31:07.520 --> 01:31:11.030
Of course, we heard about how
the moon and how the discoveries

01:31:11.030 --> 01:31:12.590
in the moon excited
the imagination,

01:31:12.590 --> 01:31:16.200
the early modern imagination
and excited ideas about again,

01:31:16.200 --> 01:31:20.110
repositioning the observers, the
idea of traveling to the moon.

01:31:20.110 --> 01:31:23.380
The moon was, in fact, extremely
important because it's the --

01:31:23.380 --> 01:31:25.410
well, it's the closest
celestial body

01:31:25.410 --> 01:31:30.570
that we could actually map early
in the history of the telescope.

01:31:30.570 --> 01:31:34.320
So astronomers like
Hevelius and others

01:31:34.320 --> 01:31:38.720
in the 17th century produced
the first atlases of the moon.

01:31:38.720 --> 01:31:42.680
In many cases, using resorting
to conventions that were used

01:31:42.680 --> 01:31:46.040
in terrestrial photography and
even trying to use the same kind

01:31:46.040 --> 01:31:48.660
of nomenclature which
eventually gave way

01:31:48.660 --> 01:31:52.270
to a nomenclature more based
on the names of astronomers

01:31:52.270 --> 01:31:54.550
and scientists connected to
the moon, which of course,

01:31:54.550 --> 01:31:57.420
is sort of a self-reference
[inaudible]

01:31:57.420 --> 01:31:58.720
for astronomers themselves.

01:31:58.720 --> 01:32:02.280
But the fact is that these
moons really created this idea

01:32:02.280 --> 01:32:06.850
of a celestial body being
the celestial body becoming a

01:32:06.850 --> 01:32:10.450
cartographic object,
becoming a natural place.

01:32:10.450 --> 01:32:13.080
And throughout [inaudible]
the 19th century,

01:32:13.080 --> 01:32:15.950
even before photography
entered into the picture,

01:32:15.950 --> 01:32:20.760
we have very detailed maps of
the moon such as this chart

01:32:20.760 --> 01:32:24.190
of the moon with 25
plates by Julius Schmidt

01:32:24.190 --> 01:32:28.350
which really gives a very
strong topographic impression

01:32:28.350 --> 01:32:29.950
and image of the moon.

01:32:29.950 --> 01:32:33.870
But more than that, this
is still a representation

01:32:33.870 --> 01:32:35.570
on a sheet of paper.

01:32:35.570 --> 01:32:39.590
Julius Schmidt himself got
involved in giving a sort

01:32:39.590 --> 01:32:45.530
of a volumetric existence to
the moon by becoming involved

01:32:45.530 --> 01:32:47.900
in the making of
this moon globe.

01:32:47.900 --> 01:32:50.580
A very impressive moon globe
that was made in Germany

01:32:50.580 --> 01:32:53.560
under the coordination and the
supervision of Julius Schmidt

01:32:53.560 --> 01:32:59.760
and which eventually came to
the United States in the 1890s

01:32:59.760 --> 01:33:03.880
and was put on display as shown
in this photograph at what,

01:33:03.880 --> 01:33:05.180
at what at the time,

01:33:05.180 --> 01:33:06.910
it was called the
Field Columbian Museum.

01:33:06.910 --> 01:33:10.080
However, we know that there
are newspaper articles

01:33:10.080 --> 01:33:13.240
so before the globe was put on
display at the Field Museum,

01:33:13.240 --> 01:33:16.690
it was used as a kind
of a traveling exhibit.

01:33:16.690 --> 01:33:19.110
And it seems that it
was not very successful

01:33:19.110 --> 01:33:21.020
because people didn't
really seem to engage

01:33:21.020 --> 01:33:23.180
with it which is interesting.

01:33:23.180 --> 01:33:26.190
Could it be because it
basically just presented them

01:33:26.190 --> 01:33:30.210
with a very barren moon
and that was an exception?

01:33:30.210 --> 01:33:34.360
I think -- I find it
actually much more striking

01:33:34.360 --> 01:33:39.750
than these moon globes with its
three-dimensionality is the idea

01:33:39.750 --> 01:33:43.550
of again, the moon
having its own landscapes,

01:33:43.550 --> 01:33:44.850
being its own place.

01:33:44.850 --> 01:33:48.440
Here we have an extremely
interesting use of photography,

01:33:48.440 --> 01:33:52.890
not to photograph the moon
itself because when this book,

01:33:52.890 --> 01:33:54.720
<i>The Moon Considered
as a Planet, a World,</i>

01:33:54.720 --> 01:33:56.500
<i>and a Satellite</i>
by James Nasmyth

01:33:56.500 --> 01:33:58.210
and James Carpenter
was published,

01:33:58.210 --> 01:34:01.020
actually the first
edition is from 1874.

01:34:01.020 --> 01:34:04.000
Photography was not still --

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:06.190
astronomical photography
was not developed enough

01:34:06.190 --> 01:34:09.170
to make an accurate
mapping of the moon.

01:34:09.170 --> 01:34:14.680
But so Nasmyth used, made
plaster models of lunar craters

01:34:14.680 --> 01:34:18.300
and had to imagine some
lunar features to look

01:34:18.300 --> 01:34:21.480
like to create these
really, really impressive

01:34:21.480 --> 01:34:25.780
and striking images that
made us imagine, I think,

01:34:25.780 --> 01:34:30.250
made the reader imagine
herself as being in the moon.

01:34:30.250 --> 01:34:32.010
Although Nasmyth advised

01:34:32.010 --> 01:34:34.060
that it's probably not
a very good place to be

01:34:34.060 --> 01:34:36.570
and not a very suitable
place for life.

01:34:36.570 --> 01:34:39.540
But still, this idea of
the moon, of a landscape

01:34:39.540 --> 01:34:42.800
in another body, I
think, it's very striking.

01:34:42.800 --> 01:34:46.220
And nothing contributed as much
to that, I guess, as the debates

01:34:46.220 --> 01:34:48.900
around the supposed
canals of Mars.

01:34:48.900 --> 01:34:53.310
Here we see an image of Mars
with its supposed canals

01:34:53.310 --> 01:34:58.920
from 1908 or the appearance of
Mars in 1905 by Percival Lowell.

01:34:58.920 --> 01:35:01.650
So many of you know Percival
Lowell became fascinated

01:35:01.650 --> 01:35:05.030
with the idea that there
could be canals on Mars.

01:35:05.030 --> 01:35:06.330
And it was announced

01:35:06.330 --> 01:35:09.170
by an Italian astronomer
called Giovanni Schiaparelli.

01:35:09.170 --> 01:35:11.030
He talked about canal
in Italian.

01:35:11.030 --> 01:35:14.460
It was translated as canals
and it conveyed the impression

01:35:14.460 --> 01:35:18.310
that perhaps those were
artificial structures made

01:35:18.310 --> 01:35:22.670
by some kind of Martian
civilization.

01:35:22.670 --> 01:35:28.800
So here, we move from not only
Mars becomes a cartographic

01:35:28.800 --> 01:35:32.300
object but it becomes even
almost like an arena space

01:35:32.300 --> 01:35:34.850
for infrastructure
public works program

01:35:34.850 --> 01:35:36.150
which is quite impressive.

01:35:36.150 --> 01:35:38.900
And needless to say, what's
happening in all of these images

01:35:38.900 --> 01:35:43.730
and ideas is very much a
straightforward projection

01:35:43.730 --> 01:35:45.140
of things that are
happening in Earth.

01:35:45.140 --> 01:35:48.510
All of this is happening
in an age of empire,

01:35:48.510 --> 01:35:50.910
an age of great infrastructural
projects,

01:35:50.910 --> 01:35:54.860
an age of extensive
cartographic imperial projects.

01:35:54.860 --> 01:35:58.290
And so, the Martian canals are
very much a resonance in this.

01:35:58.290 --> 01:36:01.370
But they have a tremendous
effect in public imagination.

01:36:01.370 --> 01:36:05.310
For example, here we move
from the map of the planet

01:36:05.310 --> 01:36:09.850
with its supposed canals which
was just basically an effect

01:36:09.850 --> 01:36:12.720
of the brain trying to
connect disparate features

01:36:12.720 --> 01:36:14.310
and this was proved
in the 1940s,

01:36:14.310 --> 01:36:16.440
there were no canals
in Mars whatsoever.

01:36:16.440 --> 01:36:18.870
But Pandora's Box
had been opened.

01:36:18.870 --> 01:36:23.490
So the [inaudible], public
imagination will remain excited

01:36:23.490 --> 01:36:24.790
about Mars to this day.

01:36:24.790 --> 01:36:27.860
There is something, I guess,
that connects Elon Musk

01:36:27.860 --> 01:36:30.370
to what was happening
in this period,

01:36:30.370 --> 01:36:32.360
this fascination with Mars.

01:36:32.360 --> 01:36:37.210
And of course, space
artist Chesley Bonestell,

01:36:37.210 --> 01:36:40.410
[inaudible] too but
in the United States,

01:36:40.410 --> 01:36:42.950
Chesley Bonestell -- they
played a very important role

01:36:42.950 --> 01:36:45.690
in further exciting
the public imagination

01:36:45.690 --> 01:36:48.130
by depicting the planets,

01:36:48.130 --> 01:36:53.190
combining available scientific
information with well,

01:36:53.190 --> 01:36:54.660
a great leap of imagination.

01:36:54.660 --> 01:36:58.300
And of course, Bonestell before
becoming a fulltime space

01:36:58.300 --> 01:37:01.660
artist, he had worked as a
matte painter in Hollywood.

01:37:01.660 --> 01:37:05.700
So he was well acquainted
with perspective and shadow.

01:37:05.700 --> 01:37:08.150
And of course, he used
all of those techniques

01:37:08.150 --> 01:37:09.940
to create his very impressive

01:37:09.940 --> 01:37:12.570
and realistic planetary
landscapes.

01:37:12.570 --> 01:37:16.780
Here on Mars and here again, the
idea of relocating the observer.

01:37:16.780 --> 01:37:20.680
Mars, as it would be seen
from its larger satellite.

01:37:20.680 --> 01:37:25.620
And here, the famous painting
set on a scene from Titan.

01:37:25.620 --> 01:37:32.850
And Chesley Bonestell went even
further down the solar system

01:37:32.850 --> 01:37:37.360
and he even invited us
to position ourselves

01:37:37.360 --> 01:37:43.020
in other planets orbiting other
stars which is very impressive.

01:37:43.020 --> 01:37:45.360
Now imagining, we've
been talking essentially

01:37:45.360 --> 01:37:46.660
of the solar system.

01:37:46.660 --> 01:37:50.300
And now, I move to the
final part of my talk.

01:37:50.300 --> 01:37:53.510
Imagine the solar system,
imagine this through scale

01:37:53.510 --> 01:37:55.900
and its true dimensions
and getting the sense

01:37:55.900 --> 01:38:00.080
of place was difficult enough
but more so was to imagine

01:38:00.080 --> 01:38:03.390
to depict and to represent
the stellar heavens.

01:38:03.390 --> 01:38:06.880
Of course, we had the debates
and the rise of Copernicanism

01:38:06.880 --> 01:38:10.660
in the 17th century excited the
imagination of several authors

01:38:10.660 --> 01:38:13.950
and thinkers about
the possibility of

01:38:13.950 --> 01:38:16.340
or what was called the
plurality of worlds,

01:38:16.340 --> 01:38:17.640
the idea of other stars.

01:38:17.640 --> 01:38:22.780
So if the Earth is just a planet
orbiting the sun, it is possible

01:38:22.780 --> 01:38:27.580
that other stars have their
own planetary systems as shown

01:38:27.580 --> 01:38:33.580
in this theatrical frontispiece
of Fontenelle's <i>Dialogues</i>

01:38:33.580 --> 01:38:35.800
<i>on the Plurality of Worlds </i>.

01:38:35.800 --> 01:38:40.550
And here again, we see the same
idea in display by Nicolas Bion,

01:38:40.550 --> 01:38:45.410
in this case meant to illustrate
the ideas of Rene Descartes

01:38:45.410 --> 01:38:48.220
and this idea that
matter created vortices

01:38:48.220 --> 01:38:49.860
that kept things in motion.

01:38:49.860 --> 01:38:51.990
But interestingly, it's how --

01:38:51.990 --> 01:38:54.230
so we have the depiction
of the solar system here

01:38:54.230 --> 01:38:57.430
and then the solar system is
just another star among other

01:38:57.430 --> 01:39:01.510
stars with their own
planetary systems.

01:39:02.740 --> 01:39:04.980
Eventually the ideas of
Descartes are overthrown

01:39:04.980 --> 01:39:08.680
by Newton and Newtonian
mechanics.

01:39:08.680 --> 01:39:11.010
And in this very
dramatic representation

01:39:11.010 --> 01:39:15.280
of the Newtonian universe, which
interestingly was made by a man,

01:39:15.280 --> 01:39:19.140
Issac Frost, who was part of the
Muggletonian sect so he wanted

01:39:19.140 --> 01:39:21.210
with this image to show
this system is wrong

01:39:21.210 --> 01:39:23.490
and is not compatible
with the bible.

01:39:23.490 --> 01:39:26.840
However, it produced one of
the [inaudible] most beautiful

01:39:26.840 --> 01:39:29.490
and striking representations
of the Newtonian idea

01:39:29.490 --> 01:39:34.230
that stars are uniformly
distributed in space.

01:39:34.230 --> 01:39:37.630
And of course, here, the element

01:39:37.630 --> 01:39:41.400
that maybe stars have their
very own planetary systems.

01:39:41.400 --> 01:39:43.160
And note the colors
which are very impressive

01:39:43.160 --> 01:39:44.460
so this was a technique,

01:39:44.460 --> 01:39:46.120
an early printing
technique developed

01:39:46.120 --> 01:39:49.730
by George Baxter using
different woodcuts

01:39:49.730 --> 01:39:52.260
and colors producing
this striking effect.

01:39:52.260 --> 01:39:55.450
But now, even those
images convey this idea

01:39:55.450 --> 01:39:58.570
of the immensity of the universe
and the stellar universe.

01:39:58.570 --> 01:39:59.890
They don't really tell us much

01:39:59.890 --> 01:40:02.040
about how are stars
actually arranged in the sky?

01:40:02.040 --> 01:40:06.670
And more importantly, a question
that was [inaudible] question

01:40:06.670 --> 01:40:10.620
and not that many people
there to address at least

01:40:10.620 --> 01:40:15.010
up to the 18th century, what
is that white swath that we see

01:40:15.010 --> 01:40:16.770
across the sky, the Milky Way?

01:40:16.770 --> 01:40:18.320
Of course, that Galileo
and others knew

01:40:18.320 --> 01:40:20.420
when they pointed
their telescopes,

01:40:20.420 --> 01:40:22.940
they knew they were
essentially stars

01:40:22.940 --> 01:40:26.150
but why is there a concentration
of stars in that direction?

01:40:26.150 --> 01:40:29.230
One of the first authors
that not only speculates

01:40:29.230 --> 01:40:33.660
about the shape of the
Milky Way and that this --

01:40:33.660 --> 01:40:36.670
but also of the distribution
of stars is Thomas Wright.

01:40:36.670 --> 01:40:41.510
Thomas Wright was essentially
a teacher so he had many hats.

01:40:41.510 --> 01:40:44.320
So he was essentially a teacher
but he was also a surveyor

01:40:44.320 --> 01:40:47.280
and an architect who had
learned astronomy essentially

01:40:47.280 --> 01:40:48.580
by himself.

01:40:48.580 --> 01:40:51.930
And Thomas Wright's
project was not just

01:40:51.930 --> 01:40:55.070
to apprehend the structure
of the Milky Way but in fact,

01:40:55.070 --> 01:40:59.740
his major concern was to combine
the idea of a distribution

01:40:59.740 --> 01:41:02.230
of stars in the universe and
their order in the universe

01:41:02.230 --> 01:41:07.130
with the moral and divine
center of the order of things.

01:41:07.130 --> 01:41:11.020
So Wright essentially
speculates about the structure

01:41:11.020 --> 01:41:12.320
and distribution of stars.

01:41:12.320 --> 01:41:16.020
But he has one correct intuition
which is that if we see

01:41:16.020 --> 01:41:19.640
so many stars and this is
basically what is meant,

01:41:19.640 --> 01:41:21.620
what this plate is
meant to show.

01:41:21.620 --> 01:41:24.030
If you are here and if
you look in a direction

01:41:24.030 --> 01:41:27.940
where most stars are
concentrated, so of course,

01:41:27.940 --> 01:41:31.990
you will see a swath of
stars in the white swath

01:41:31.990 --> 01:41:33.960
in that direction in the sky.

01:41:33.960 --> 01:41:36.880
But now, what is the
actual arrangement of stars

01:41:36.880 --> 01:41:40.900
and what's our place in it
that produces this effect?

01:41:40.900 --> 01:41:44.630
Wright plays with
different concepts.

01:41:44.630 --> 01:41:46.930
So one of the concepts
he comes up with is

01:41:46.930 --> 01:41:50.730
that maybe the stars
are arranged in a sort

01:41:50.730 --> 01:41:55.350
of a sphere forming a kind of a
hollow globe and in the center

01:41:55.350 --> 01:41:57.960
of that globe, so here are
the stars and in the center

01:41:57.960 --> 01:42:00.870
of that globe is
the very divine,

01:42:00.870 --> 01:42:03.220
the center of divine
providence and the moral

01:42:03.220 --> 01:42:04.980
and divine center
of the universe.

01:42:04.980 --> 01:42:06.370
And if we are positioned here,

01:42:06.370 --> 01:42:10.030
if our sun is positioned
somewhere around here, so again,

01:42:10.030 --> 01:42:14.230
when we look in the tangential
direction to the sphere

01:42:14.230 --> 01:42:18.990
of stars, we will an effect
like the Milky Way in the sky.

01:42:18.990 --> 01:42:21.350
Wright was not using
observational evidence.

01:42:21.350 --> 01:42:23.410
So he was basically
speculating and he played

01:42:23.410 --> 01:42:26.780
with other possible
arrangements as well.

01:42:26.780 --> 01:42:29.230
So here in the analogy
of Saturn,

01:42:29.230 --> 01:42:33.950
he imagined how the stars
could create the appearance

01:42:33.950 --> 01:42:38.440
to an observer on Earth, if
they were distributed in rings

01:42:38.440 --> 01:42:43.650
around a center which is here
as the appearance of the planet

01:42:43.650 --> 01:42:46.790
but precisely just to emphasize
this idea of a metaphor.

01:42:46.790 --> 01:42:49.960
And even though Wright was
not very fond of the idea

01:42:49.960 --> 01:42:54.480
of multiple centers in the
universe, he also played

01:42:54.480 --> 01:42:57.790
with that hypothesis and this
is what this image actually

01:42:57.790 --> 01:42:59.090
shows you.

01:42:59.090 --> 01:43:00.390
And now, I would
like to show you

01:43:00.390 --> 01:43:03.060
to better help us visualize
how this would work in space.

01:43:03.060 --> 01:43:06.000
I would like to show you a
brief animation made by some

01:43:06.000 --> 01:43:10.500
of my colleagues at the Adler
Planetarium based on Wright's.

01:43:11.600 --> 01:43:15.480
So this an animation made by
my colleague, Mark Subbarao,

01:43:15.480 --> 01:43:18.500
who's the director of our
Space Visualization Laboratory

01:43:18.500 --> 01:43:20.510
and Julieta Aguilera, who's
no longer with the Adler

01:43:20.510 --> 01:43:23.200
but also worked in the Space
Visualization Laboratory.

01:43:23.200 --> 01:43:26.820
So here, we have original
Wright's illustration.

01:43:26.820 --> 01:43:28.360
So this is how the
stars would look

01:43:28.360 --> 01:43:30.930
like according to
that model of his.

01:43:30.930 --> 01:43:37.290
And now, we will soon
get into, precisely get

01:43:37.290 --> 01:43:40.800
into a tangential plane
for the sphere of the stars

01:43:40.800 --> 01:43:43.970
and get this impression
in space.

01:43:43.970 --> 01:43:50.130
But of course, again, these
conceptions, these of course,

01:43:50.130 --> 01:43:51.430
don't really have --

01:43:51.430 --> 01:43:54.870
don't really explain what
we actually are observing

01:43:54.870 --> 01:43:56.170
in the sky.

01:43:56.170 --> 01:43:59.140
It had the merit of trying to
bring and trying to materialize

01:43:59.140 --> 01:44:02.610
and to create a spatial
thinking about the arrangements

01:44:02.610 --> 01:44:05.620
of stars in the universe.

01:44:05.620 --> 01:44:08.850
But the connection between
actual astronomical observation

01:44:08.850 --> 01:44:12.280
and the attempt to study the
structure of the galaxy came

01:44:12.280 --> 01:44:14.160
with William Herschel.

01:44:14.160 --> 01:44:16.650
So William Herschel, who is
better known for his discovery

01:44:16.650 --> 01:44:20.230
of Uranus, his major project,
one of his major projects

01:44:20.230 --> 01:44:23.930
in astronomy was try to figure
out the structure of the galaxy.

01:44:23.930 --> 01:44:26.590
And he carried about him
extensive observing program

01:44:26.590 --> 01:44:29.210
using large telescopes
that he made himself

01:44:29.210 --> 01:44:33.000
and used some sort
of proto-statistics.

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:35.070
So basically, he made
several assumptions

01:44:35.070 --> 01:44:36.370
which now we know
are not correct.

01:44:36.370 --> 01:44:39.000
But he basically assumed
that he could see the borders

01:44:39.000 --> 01:44:40.300
of the galaxy.

01:44:40.300 --> 01:44:42.810
And so, he began by
pointing a telescope

01:44:42.810 --> 01:44:44.120
to different directions
in the sky

01:44:44.120 --> 01:44:47.160
and by counting how many stars
he could see in each direction.

01:44:47.160 --> 01:44:53.350
And so, by using that data, he
established this first attempt

01:44:53.350 --> 01:44:55.290
of a model of the galaxy.

01:44:55.290 --> 01:44:58.120
And again, I can show
you another animation.

01:44:58.120 --> 01:45:01.690
So basically what we have
here, and you have the Earth

01:45:01.690 --> 01:45:04.360
at the center and you
have most of the stars

01:45:04.360 --> 01:45:08.790
in the Milky Way concentrated
along a single plane.

01:45:08.790 --> 01:45:11.520
And even though, of course,
the actual model of the galaxy

01:45:11.520 --> 01:45:14.520
as according to the astronomy
of today is much different,

01:45:14.520 --> 01:45:18.740
the basic intuition that the
stars must be distributed along

01:45:18.740 --> 01:45:21.730
the same plane is
basically correct.

01:45:21.730 --> 01:45:24.270
And now, I would like to --

01:45:24.270 --> 01:45:27.970
I'd like to show you
another animation.

01:45:32.040 --> 01:45:33.890
So here, we have it again.

01:45:33.890 --> 01:45:35.480
It's basically again
the intuition

01:45:35.480 --> 01:45:38.250
that the stars are more or
less distributed along the

01:45:38.250 --> 01:45:39.550
same plane.

01:45:39.550 --> 01:45:42.160
And of course, that the idea

01:45:42.160 --> 01:45:44.230
of a spiral galaxy
comes much later.

01:45:44.230 --> 01:45:48.530
And I will actually end my talk
with that in a few minutes.

01:45:48.530 --> 01:45:49.870
So here, we have --

01:45:49.870 --> 01:45:52.230
so basically, from the
illustration made by Herschel,

01:45:52.230 --> 01:45:55.020
we turned that into the
actual distribution of stars.

01:45:55.020 --> 01:45:57.700
And here is the production of
the effect of the Milky Way

01:45:57.700 --> 01:46:01.240
so when you're looking precisely
in the direction of the plane

01:46:01.240 --> 01:46:04.570
where most of the
stars are concentrated.

01:46:04.570 --> 01:46:07.200
It was only in the 20th
century, even though it's

01:46:07.200 --> 01:46:10.290
such a familiar image, it
was only in the 20th century

01:46:10.290 --> 01:46:14.130
that astronomers were finally
able to prove that the shape

01:46:14.130 --> 01:46:17.970
of the galaxy is
actually a spiral shape.

01:46:17.970 --> 01:46:22.050
And what you see here is one of
two models, actual models made

01:46:22.050 --> 01:46:24.920
by William Morgan who was
at the Yerkes Observatory.

01:46:24.920 --> 01:46:29.260
And so he basically, by studying
the distribution of stars

01:46:29.260 --> 01:46:32.770
and clouds of gas, whose
positions are represented

01:46:32.770 --> 01:46:39.850
by this tiny cotton spheres, it
was already known that old stars

01:46:39.850 --> 01:46:44.080
in spiral galaxies tend to
be concentrated at the center

01:46:44.080 --> 01:46:47.530
of the galaxy and then you have
the younger stars, blue stars

01:46:47.530 --> 01:46:51.710
and you have ionized gas in
the outer arms of the galaxies.

01:46:51.710 --> 01:46:55.480
And so when Morgan and
his collaborators tried

01:46:55.480 --> 01:47:01.350
to map some clusters of the
young stars and ionized gas,

01:47:01.350 --> 01:47:03.750
they found these positions
and what you see here

01:47:03.750 --> 01:47:06.500
and this was presented
at the meeting

01:47:06.500 --> 01:47:10.220
of the American Astronomical
Society in 1951

01:47:10.220 --> 01:47:12.470
and Morgan had gotten
a standing ovation

01:47:12.470 --> 01:47:14.280
when he presented
this very model,

01:47:14.280 --> 01:47:18.050
that materialized what he had --

01:47:18.050 --> 01:47:21.660
what he had derived
from his data.

01:47:21.660 --> 01:47:24.270
So this is pretty much
where the first time

01:47:24.270 --> 01:47:26.880
where you can see more or
less, the spiral shapes

01:47:26.880 --> 01:47:31.410
of the galaxy being
derived and being presented

01:47:31.410 --> 01:47:33.130
which is now a very
familiar shape.

01:47:33.130 --> 01:47:37.210
So familiar that we even
have it in our backyard,

01:47:37.210 --> 01:47:38.710
in the Adler Planetarium.

01:47:38.710 --> 01:47:45.720
So what you see here on the left
is a model, a sculpture inspired

01:47:45.720 --> 01:47:48.870
on the spiral shape of
galaxy by Johan Dave Mooney.

01:47:48.870 --> 01:47:52.080
He replaced the gas with
the skyline of Chicago.

01:47:52.080 --> 01:47:55.450
And this is kind of our own
local Stonehenge in a sense.

01:47:55.450 --> 01:47:56.910
So you could call
it the Adlerhenge.

01:47:56.910 --> 01:47:59.510
So basically it's a
monument, it's a sculpture

01:47:59.510 --> 01:48:01.650
with several stones with
astronomical alignments

01:48:01.650 --> 01:48:05.530
but again, based on the
shape of the galaxy.

01:48:05.530 --> 01:48:08.290
So that pretty much that shape
that was first derived using

01:48:08.290 --> 01:48:12.190
that model is now pretty much a
very familiar image in astronomy

01:48:12.190 --> 01:48:15.990
to the point that it's even
used in artistic installations

01:48:15.990 --> 01:48:18.340
around the planetarium.

01:48:18.340 --> 01:48:21.440
I like very much the fact
that this sculpture is just

01:48:21.440 --> 01:48:24.840
by the lake which serves
in a sense as a reminder

01:48:24.840 --> 01:48:30.690
that our galaxy is actually just
part of a much broader horizon.

01:48:30.690 --> 01:48:34.220
But by creating familiar
shapes and familiar forms

01:48:34.220 --> 01:48:37.690
and by somehow making
the heavens tangible,

01:48:37.690 --> 01:48:42.100
giving them dimensions,
bringing them closer to us,

01:48:42.100 --> 01:48:44.780
super-imposing the scale
of the heavens with scales

01:48:44.780 --> 01:48:48.810
of things we are more familiar
with like the scale of a city,

01:48:48.810 --> 01:48:52.760
and essentially trying
to present them in a way

01:48:52.760 --> 01:48:54.530
that gives a sense of place,

01:48:54.530 --> 01:48:58.180
I think we make the heavens
more familiar and apprehensible.

01:48:58.180 --> 01:49:01.840
And I would like to end by
saying that and going back

01:49:01.840 --> 01:49:03.290
to the story I told
in the beginning

01:49:03.290 --> 01:49:06.720
about that lady was overwhelmed
by the scale of the universe,

01:49:06.720 --> 01:49:11.930
I think imagining the
extraordinary is essentially an

01:49:11.930 --> 01:49:16.530
attempt to make it ordinary,
apprehensible and familiar.

01:49:16.530 --> 01:49:18.330
Thank you very much.

