01:52:32.340 --> 01:52:33.640
and image and meaning.

01:52:33.640 --> 01:52:36.240
And that actually
landed me a job working

01:52:36.240 --> 01:52:39.180
for NASA's Chandra
X-ray Observatory.

01:52:39.180 --> 01:52:40.750
Now, I got this job
when I was --

01:52:40.750 --> 01:52:43.380
let me see, it must
have been 1998

01:52:43.380 --> 01:52:45.040
so it's been almost 20 years.

01:52:45.040 --> 01:52:48.230
The Chandra X-ray Observatory
was just about to launch.

01:52:48.230 --> 01:52:51.410
And it's an amazing
technological achievement.

01:52:51.410 --> 01:52:54.200
It studies the high
energy universe so things

01:52:54.200 --> 01:52:58.450
like exploding stars, black
holes, colliding galaxies --

01:52:58.450 --> 01:53:02.630
these really violent
cosmic events

01:53:02.630 --> 01:53:06.650
that we can study high
energy information from.

01:53:06.650 --> 01:53:10.570
It was great to be a part
of that as it was launching.

01:53:10.570 --> 01:53:14.460
But again, this is where
I was starting out.

01:53:14.460 --> 01:53:15.760
This is actually an image

01:53:15.760 --> 01:53:19.230
of the spirochete
inside that tick stomach.

01:53:19.230 --> 01:53:21.140
It's Borrelia burgdorferi.

01:53:21.140 --> 01:53:24.850
And this each -- one of these
little spiral things is about 10

01:53:24.850 --> 01:53:26.990
to 25 micrometers long.

01:53:26.990 --> 01:53:30.450
So I had to translate that
information that I was used

01:53:30.450 --> 01:53:34.390
to dealing with into looking
at things like this instead.

01:53:34.390 --> 01:53:36.570
This is the [Inaudible]
galaxies.

01:53:36.570 --> 01:53:40.990
It's a sort of spiral-shaped
collision of two galaxies.

01:53:40.990 --> 01:53:43.880
And this is 60,000
light years across.

01:53:43.880 --> 01:53:46.710
Where a light year is the
distance that light travels

01:53:46.710 --> 01:53:49.830
in a year which is about
10 trillion kilometers.

01:53:49.830 --> 01:53:53.030
So 60,000 times 10
trillion kilometers.

01:53:53.030 --> 01:53:57.120
So it's a pretty big
scale difference, I think.

01:53:57.120 --> 01:54:01.650
But really, what I want to talk
about today is this idea and I'm

01:54:01.650 --> 01:54:04.520
so happy that the
historians went before me

01:54:04.520 --> 01:54:06.060
because I'm not a historian.

01:54:06.060 --> 01:54:08.920
So it's great that that language
has already been introduced

01:54:08.920 --> 01:54:11.110
and I can just ride
on their coattails.

01:54:11.110 --> 01:54:13.990
Because I want to talk about
this idea of a visual language

01:54:13.990 --> 01:54:17.200
which both speakers earlier
talked about briefly.

01:54:17.200 --> 01:54:20.460
And they also introduced
Galileo's moon

01:54:20.460 --> 01:54:21.760
which I will show too.

01:54:21.760 --> 01:54:23.360
But I won't have
to talk about all

01:54:23.360 --> 01:54:24.950
because you're all
experts obviously

01:54:24.950 --> 01:54:26.370
in Galileo's moon by now.

01:54:26.370 --> 01:54:29.060
So when we talk about
how our images

01:54:29.060 --> 01:54:32.120
of the universe are really how
any image in science is created.

01:54:32.120 --> 01:54:34.240
It's through a selection
of choices.

01:54:34.240 --> 01:54:39.820
It's through a human using
software that has been created

01:54:39.820 --> 01:54:44.600
by humans using data that
was collected by hardware

01:54:44.600 --> 01:54:46.370
that was made by humans.

01:54:46.370 --> 01:54:48.400
So there are these
strings of choices

01:54:48.400 --> 01:54:50.790
and human biases along the way.

01:54:50.790 --> 01:54:53.280
I'm going to try to
talk about some of that.

01:54:53.280 --> 01:54:55.470
So to make images like this,

01:54:55.470 --> 01:55:00.660
there's this visual language
scale, context, dimensionality,

01:55:00.660 --> 01:55:03.970
field of view, cropping,
selection itself.

01:55:03.970 --> 01:55:06.840
These things are done
to make a point, right.

01:55:06.840 --> 01:55:10.760
There is a science story to
tell but there's also this idea

01:55:10.760 --> 01:55:14.780
that you want your image to be
memorable, to be persuasive.

01:55:14.780 --> 01:55:19.580
So we're going to look at
bugs because obviously,

01:55:19.580 --> 01:55:23.210
I love bugs if I spent so
much time looking at them.

01:55:23.210 --> 01:55:27.170
These are from Hooke's
<i>Micrografia </i>who we also heard

01:55:27.170 --> 01:55:30.480
about from, I think, both
-- no, Gaskell mostly.

01:55:30.480 --> 01:55:32.420
And we've got a couple
of examples here

01:55:32.420 --> 01:55:34.330
that I particularly like.

01:55:34.330 --> 01:55:35.730
One, I just think
they're beautiful.

01:55:35.730 --> 01:55:37.920
These are really
beautiful illustrations.

01:55:37.920 --> 01:55:41.180
Hooke, I think, had a really
amazing talent for being able

01:55:41.180 --> 01:55:44.420
to bring his objects to life.

01:55:44.420 --> 01:55:46.980
But he's also using very
specific visual techniques

01:55:46.980 --> 01:55:49.860
to translate something that
started out in three dimensions

01:55:49.860 --> 01:55:51.660
into a two-dimensional form.

01:55:51.660 --> 01:55:53.830
He's collapsing that
information onto a version

01:55:53.830 --> 01:55:55.510
that works on the page.

01:55:55.510 --> 01:55:59.160
And he's carefully
creating his images through,

01:55:59.160 --> 01:56:01.620
you guessed it, a
series of choices.

01:56:01.620 --> 01:56:05.570
So in this case, Hooke is
really placing his instrument,

01:56:05.570 --> 01:56:08.700
a microscope typically but he
did also work with telescopes

01:56:08.700 --> 01:56:11.140
as an extension of our senses.

01:56:11.140 --> 01:56:15.190
With this introduction of this
new equipment in the 1600s,

01:56:15.190 --> 01:56:19.280
it offered that the observer
could then function as a bridge,

01:56:19.280 --> 01:56:21.140
a bridge between
an invisible world

01:56:21.140 --> 01:56:23.830
and in other interested parties
who didn't necessarily have

01:56:23.830 --> 01:56:25.400
to do the observing themselves.

01:56:25.400 --> 01:56:28.300
That immediately gives you
a sense of distance already

01:56:28.300 --> 01:56:29.950
as the third party viewer,

01:56:29.950 --> 01:56:33.680
not just the distance
physically but also in time.

01:56:33.680 --> 01:56:36.700
So what kind of visual
strategies did Hooke use?

01:56:36.700 --> 01:56:38.470
Well, he used his
space really well.

01:56:38.470 --> 01:56:41.650
Isolation, composition,
contrast, shading,

01:56:41.650 --> 01:56:44.290
dimensionality, all these
really important things

01:56:44.290 --> 01:56:48.180
that we use today, hundreds
of years later in astronomy.

01:56:48.180 --> 01:56:51.310
So a really quick description
of what it is we're looking at.

01:56:51.310 --> 01:56:53.500
On the left, we've
got a lovely gnat.

01:56:53.500 --> 01:56:56.860
And this beautiful gnat has
been zoomed in quite a bit

01:56:56.860 --> 01:56:59.410
so that you don't
see all of its body.

01:56:59.410 --> 01:57:01.690
That's a very intentional
framing.

01:57:01.690 --> 01:57:04.810
It's just enough so you can
see the details of the wings,

01:57:04.810 --> 01:57:08.450
of the body on the
bottom, of just the hairs

01:57:08.450 --> 01:57:10.660
on its legs, really lovely.

01:57:10.660 --> 01:57:14.230
On the right, we actually
have the eye of a drone fly.

01:57:14.230 --> 01:57:17.390
I think it's a grey
drone fly, to be precise.

01:57:17.390 --> 01:57:19.590
And again, with this
image, we're cropped

01:57:19.590 --> 01:57:21.570
in really, really tight.

01:57:21.570 --> 01:57:25.240
Hooke is taking you to a very
specific place really guiding

01:57:25.240 --> 01:57:28.240
your eye on what to see
and what's important.

01:57:28.240 --> 01:57:30.080
There's a really
interesting perspective here

01:57:30.080 --> 01:57:32.020
on what he is choosing to do.

01:57:32.020 --> 01:57:34.940
So this sort of visual
language then has

01:57:34.940 --> 01:57:37.080
to be essentially
decoded, right.

01:57:37.080 --> 01:57:40.920
By the cropping, by the framing,
he's giving you a very specific

01:57:40.920 --> 01:57:45.730
but also very dramatic and quite
beautiful thing to look at.

01:57:45.730 --> 01:57:47.910
He was always one for drama.

01:57:47.910 --> 01:57:50.260
So how do we compare
with astronomy?

01:57:50.260 --> 01:57:52.220
And I had a little
fun here because both

01:57:52.220 --> 01:57:55.710
of these nebulas are
named, nicknamed after bugs.

01:57:55.710 --> 01:57:59.630
So on the left, we have the
Ant Nebula because why not?

01:57:59.630 --> 01:58:02.930
But you can see, here I chose
to crop in pretty tightly.

01:58:02.930 --> 01:58:05.060
This is using optical
or visible data

01:58:05.060 --> 01:58:06.720
from the Hubble Space Telescope.

01:58:06.720 --> 01:58:08.980
And what a planetary
nebula like this is,

01:58:08.980 --> 01:58:12.720
is essentially a sun-like
star that is slowly dying.

01:58:12.720 --> 01:58:15.370
As they die, they puff
off their outer layers

01:58:15.370 --> 01:58:18.350
and create these beautiful
nebulas that you see here.

01:58:18.350 --> 01:58:19.820
Now, in both of these examples,

01:58:19.820 --> 01:58:22.220
they're really nice
with their symmetry.

01:58:22.220 --> 01:58:24.420
So I also picked that on
purpose besides the fact

01:58:24.420 --> 01:58:25.950
that they were named after bugs.

01:58:25.950 --> 01:58:28.700
And I've cropped in really
tightly for a reason.

01:58:28.700 --> 01:58:30.540
So there is more
data to see here

01:58:30.540 --> 01:58:32.400
but I'm not allowing
you to see it.

01:58:32.400 --> 01:58:35.250
The cropping is a
very specific intent.

01:58:35.250 --> 01:58:37.830
You want to see all of the
action, all of the things

01:58:37.830 --> 01:58:42.100
that are going on as this
sun-like star is throwing off

01:58:42.100 --> 01:58:43.400
its outer shell.

01:58:43.400 --> 01:58:45.250
And then, of course,
on the right,

01:58:45.250 --> 01:58:47.430
that one's called
the Bug Nebula.

01:58:47.430 --> 01:58:49.570
It's also nicknamed the
Butterfly Nebula but I'm going

01:58:49.570 --> 01:58:52.320
to use bugs since it's
closer to the previous slide.

01:58:52.320 --> 01:58:53.620
And it's the same thing.

01:58:53.620 --> 01:58:55.130
It's the same type
of planetary nebula.

01:58:55.130 --> 01:59:00.080
This beautiful death of a star
and we're cropped in so tight

01:59:00.080 --> 01:59:02.120
because right inside
the center point

01:59:02.120 --> 01:59:06.980
of that bipolarization is the
star itself that we can't see

01:59:06.980 --> 01:59:09.390
because in this case,
we're using optical light.

01:59:09.390 --> 01:59:12.870
And optical light cannot get
through that gas and dust.

01:59:12.870 --> 01:59:16.580
So again, very intentional.

01:59:16.580 --> 01:59:19.520
Now, we're going to look at
rosemary and other leaves,

01:59:19.520 --> 01:59:23.900
not as exciting as a topic
but what I really liked is

01:59:23.900 --> 01:59:29.000
that the scope view provides a
sort of secondhand experience

01:59:29.000 --> 01:59:32.100
that makes it feel more virtual
like you're actually there.

01:59:32.100 --> 01:59:35.000
You're actually looking
through the microscope yourself.

01:59:35.000 --> 01:59:36.920
Of course, by doing
this, you get to tie

01:59:36.920 --> 01:59:38.450
in really close again.

01:59:38.450 --> 01:59:40.240
You get to look at this texture.

01:59:40.240 --> 01:59:42.620
You get to look at how he's
done the shading in the area

01:59:42.620 --> 01:59:44.980
that he selected of interest.

01:59:44.980 --> 01:59:47.000
But it's also again
quite intentional.

01:59:47.000 --> 01:59:49.380
And in astronomy, we
can do similar things.

01:59:49.380 --> 01:59:52.950
So here, I picked these images
because well, they're round

01:59:52.950 --> 01:59:54.770
and I thought the symmetry
was nice for the texture.

01:59:54.770 --> 01:59:56.320
But essentially, we're looking

01:59:56.320 --> 01:59:59.080
at three examples
of exploded stars.

01:59:59.080 --> 02:00:01.320
So these are stars
larger than our sun

02:00:01.320 --> 02:00:03.940
that have, you guessed it, died.

02:00:03.940 --> 02:00:06.180
And I'm not like really
morbid but it's just --

02:00:06.180 --> 02:00:08.640
this is, you know, the nature
of the universe in some sense.

02:00:08.640 --> 02:00:11.670
So we're going to be talking
about a lot of dead stars today.

02:00:11.670 --> 02:00:15.510
But again, what this really
tight closed circular crop

02:00:15.510 --> 02:00:18.180
allows us to do is to
see a lot of the detail

02:00:18.180 --> 02:00:22.250
and also it's a practical thing
because in all three examples

02:00:22.250 --> 02:00:25.000
of these super nova remnants,
all the data was taken

02:00:25.000 --> 02:00:28.060
by the Chandra X-ray
Observatory.

02:00:28.060 --> 02:00:31.360
Outside of those frames,
there's not really much to see.

02:00:31.360 --> 02:00:35.010
It's just kind of black space
and a little bit of x-ray noise.

02:00:35.010 --> 02:00:37.580
So if you leave an
entire frame like that

02:00:37.580 --> 02:00:41.650
around this important x-ray
observation, it gives a sense

02:00:41.650 --> 02:00:44.680
to the viewer that there is
nothing else around that object.

02:00:44.680 --> 02:00:46.160
And that's actually not true.

02:00:46.160 --> 02:00:49.140
It's just we can only
see this in x-ray light.

02:00:49.140 --> 02:00:51.860
If we were to combine it
with say, an optical field

02:00:51.860 --> 02:00:55.870
or infrared, we would see yet
more of the universe behind it.

02:00:55.870 --> 02:00:58.200
So by cropping in really
closely to the objects,

02:00:58.200 --> 02:01:01.480
we're actually helping to view,
to help guide the viewpoint

02:01:01.480 --> 02:01:03.160
that these are specific objects

02:01:03.160 --> 02:01:05.970
that we're just concentrating
on right here.

02:01:07.690 --> 02:01:11.050
Now, not bugs but
looking at seeds.

02:01:11.050 --> 02:01:14.440
Why I selected these images
from Hooke's drawings was

02:01:14.440 --> 02:01:15.740
that I just thought the texture

02:01:15.740 --> 02:01:18.180
and the dimensionality
were really exquisite.

02:01:18.180 --> 02:01:21.390
On the left, we have
poppy seeds.

02:01:21.390 --> 02:01:23.690
So this magnification
is really quite amazing.

02:01:23.690 --> 02:01:27.740
And on the right, we have
seeds of thyme, I believe.

02:01:27.740 --> 02:01:32.840
Now, you can see all the
little mottling, the texturing,

02:01:32.840 --> 02:01:36.510
the ridging, you can see
where his light is coming

02:01:36.510 --> 02:01:38.770
from because it's
casting shadows.

02:01:38.770 --> 02:01:42.780
And that kind of dimensionality
again makes it feel more real

02:01:42.780 --> 02:01:46.890
as if you're closer to the
observation, to the information,

02:01:46.890 --> 02:01:49.450
to the data than you
might be otherwise.

02:01:49.450 --> 02:01:52.930
In astronomy, dimensionality
is incredibly important too.

02:01:52.930 --> 02:01:55.880
Now, this image, I just selected
because it kind of looked

02:01:55.880 --> 02:01:57.360
like the seeds in a way.

02:01:57.360 --> 02:02:00.150
But again, you're looking
at individual galaxies

02:02:00.150 --> 02:02:03.170
that are many, many
billions of light years away.

02:02:03.170 --> 02:02:04.910
A light year is the distance
that light travels in a year,

02:02:04.910 --> 02:02:06.950
10, you know, trillion
kilometers.

02:02:06.950 --> 02:02:09.140
So these are billions
upon billions.

02:02:09.140 --> 02:02:12.590
This is pretty much as far as
we can see in astronomy today

02:02:12.590 --> 02:02:14.360
in the observable universe.

02:02:14.360 --> 02:02:17.250
And still when we're talking our
image, when we're creating them,

02:02:17.250 --> 02:02:19.150
we are trying to make
sure that the idea

02:02:19.150 --> 02:02:21.240
of dimensionality
is still there.

02:02:21.240 --> 02:02:24.780
But probably an even better
example is this image which is,

02:02:24.780 --> 02:02:26.080
I think, kind of famous.

02:02:26.080 --> 02:02:28.280
It's from the Hubble
Space Telescope.

02:02:28.280 --> 02:02:30.450
It's called the "Pillars
of Creation"

02:02:30.450 --> 02:02:34.750
and it's also nicknamed
the Eagle Nebula and M-16.

02:02:34.750 --> 02:02:36.050
Astronomy has a thing for names.

02:02:36.050 --> 02:02:37.350
We've got a lot of nicknames.

02:02:37.350 --> 02:02:41.470
But these are really beautiful,
tall columns of gas and dust

02:02:41.470 --> 02:02:43.460
where stars are being born.

02:02:43.460 --> 02:02:44.760
So there's -- so there we go.

02:02:44.760 --> 02:02:47.580
It's not all about death.

02:02:47.580 --> 02:02:51.410
The column on the left is
about four light years tall.

02:02:51.410 --> 02:02:53.850
So four times 10
trillion kilometers.

02:02:53.850 --> 02:02:56.120
So it's quite a difference
in scale,

02:02:56.120 --> 02:02:58.360
four times 10 trillion
kilometers

02:02:58.360 --> 02:03:01.230
versus the 400 times
magnification that we looked

02:03:01.230 --> 02:03:02.900
at in the previous slide.

02:03:02.900 --> 02:03:08.190
But the way this image was
created again, was intentional.

02:03:08.190 --> 02:03:11.850
It was to talk about the science
and the science in this case,

02:03:11.850 --> 02:03:17.240
is this idea of these immense
pillars of gas and dust

02:03:17.240 --> 02:03:20.650
where these baby
stars are being made.

02:03:20.650 --> 02:03:25.310
And to get across the point
of the dimensionality, we --

02:03:25.310 --> 02:03:26.670
well, the image processers

02:03:26.670 --> 02:03:30.190
on this specific data
set applied colors

02:03:30.190 --> 02:03:34.670
in a very strategic way to
encourage that dimensionality

02:03:34.670 --> 02:03:37.810
to be immediately
visible to the viewer.

02:03:37.810 --> 02:03:40.500
And that was purely
by color selection.

02:03:40.500 --> 02:03:41.800
So I'll talk a little bit

02:03:41.800 --> 02:03:44.570
about more how we make
astronomy images in a second

02:03:44.570 --> 02:03:48.660
but essentially for this
image, the colors were chosen

02:03:48.660 --> 02:03:53.170
by chemical elements, by the
light emission due to them.

02:03:53.170 --> 02:03:57.320
So red was from sulfur and
the blue color was assigned

02:03:57.320 --> 02:03:59.350
to hydrogen and helium.

02:03:59.350 --> 02:04:01.610
And I think green was
assigned to oxygen.

02:04:01.610 --> 02:04:04.530
So it's kind of like
an elemental map

02:04:04.530 --> 02:04:10.070
of the stuff that's going on in
this really beautiful nebula.

02:04:10.070 --> 02:04:12.770
By choosing those colors,

02:04:12.770 --> 02:04:14.830
now this is something we
can't see with our human eyes.

02:04:14.830 --> 02:04:19.040
Even though it's mostly optical
light, our eyes are kind of puny

02:04:19.040 --> 02:04:22.200
in the grand scheme of things
and we could never detect all

02:04:22.200 --> 02:04:26.030
of this information with
just the eyes that we have.

02:04:26.030 --> 02:04:29.030
So these telescopes give
us superhuman vision.

02:04:29.030 --> 02:04:31.210
So when we're working
with our data,

02:04:31.210 --> 02:04:34.220
it doesn't particularly
matter what colors these are

02:04:34.220 --> 02:04:37.550
because it's not something we
could really observe directly.

02:04:37.550 --> 02:04:40.900
So the color assignment was
meant to help further the idea

02:04:40.900 --> 02:04:43.850
that this has dimension
and shape to it.

02:04:43.850 --> 02:04:46.010
And so with blue being
more on the background

02:04:46.010 --> 02:04:48.090
and the reds being
more in the foreground,

02:04:48.090 --> 02:04:50.730
that idea of dimensionality
and shading, I think,

02:04:50.730 --> 02:04:53.670
was really made a lot stronger.

02:04:54.940 --> 02:04:58.380
When we think about things
like scale, which is, I think,

02:04:58.380 --> 02:05:01.220
a really difficult thing to
talk about when you're looking

02:05:01.220 --> 02:05:03.310
at something really, really
small or when you're looking

02:05:03.310 --> 02:05:05.700
at something really, really big.

02:05:05.700 --> 02:05:10.120
One of the easiest techniques
to do is to provide some sort

02:05:10.120 --> 02:05:13.510
of sense of scale through
a physical representation.

02:05:13.510 --> 02:05:16.920
So on the left here, we have
this really lovely louse

02:05:16.920 --> 02:05:19.620
and I don't think that's
probably something I say

02:05:19.620 --> 02:05:20.920
very often.

02:05:20.920 --> 02:05:25.610
But it's grasping a
single strand of hair.

02:05:25.610 --> 02:05:28.750
So that immediately gives
you a sense of scale.

02:05:28.750 --> 02:05:31.470
But also context because
well, let's face it.

02:05:31.470 --> 02:05:33.650
Lice, they like hair.

02:05:33.650 --> 02:05:37.970
So it provides so much more
than just a little, you know,

02:05:37.970 --> 02:05:39.450
something for it to hold on to.

02:05:39.450 --> 02:05:42.490
It gives you that immediate idea
of scale and contextualization.

02:05:42.490 --> 02:05:47.410
On the right is essentially
another idea of scale.

02:05:47.410 --> 02:05:51.150
The idea here that he was trying
to show was that sometimes,

02:05:51.150 --> 02:05:54.110
things that seem so
smooth are really not.

02:05:54.110 --> 02:05:58.230
And the pollen grain
looking-like thing is actually a

02:05:58.230 --> 02:06:00.650
printed full stop, a period.

02:06:00.650 --> 02:06:04.480
And for scale, you can
also see the needle point

02:06:04.480 --> 02:06:06.710
and then underneath
that is the razor.

02:06:06.710 --> 02:06:10.810
So it's this idea of you know,
known things and looking at them

02:06:10.810 --> 02:06:13.750
in a different way but still
providing a relationship

02:06:13.750 --> 02:06:16.050
to each other.

02:06:18.040 --> 02:06:20.900
Scale in astronomy is hard.

02:06:20.900 --> 02:06:22.260
It's really hard.

02:06:22.260 --> 02:06:26.570
So our sun is kind of small
in the grand scheme of things.

02:06:26.570 --> 02:06:28.430
It's just an ordinary star.

02:06:28.430 --> 02:06:30.140
It's kind of on the
smaller size.

02:06:30.140 --> 02:06:32.140
It's not super exciting.

02:06:32.140 --> 02:06:33.440
It's perfect for us.

02:06:33.440 --> 02:06:34.740
Don't get me wrong.

02:06:34.740 --> 02:06:36.040
I love our sun.

02:06:36.040 --> 02:06:38.550
I'm not, you know,
dabbling at that much.

02:06:38.550 --> 02:06:40.670
So when it comes to
talking scale, well,

02:06:40.670 --> 02:06:43.990
you could fit maybe a
million Earths inside our sun.

02:06:43.990 --> 02:06:47.910
So we can show the idea
of scale by positioning

02:06:47.910 --> 02:06:50.200
that one single Earth
in relation

02:06:50.200 --> 02:06:53.230
to this one outburst
coming out of the sun.

02:06:53.230 --> 02:06:56.640
And that single outburst which
was not particularly big,

02:06:56.640 --> 02:06:59.720
dwarfs the Earth by quite a lot.

02:06:59.720 --> 02:07:01.400
Now, the issue is as soon

02:07:01.400 --> 02:07:05.890
as you get beyond something
that's a little bit more doable

02:07:05.890 --> 02:07:08.860
in size like the sun
is to bigger things,

02:07:08.860 --> 02:07:13.720
how do you portray the scale in
a meaningful way to the viewer

02:07:13.720 --> 02:07:18.430
who might not necessarily have
any sort of personal connection

02:07:18.430 --> 02:07:22.650
to sizes of these things,
like not of us really do?

02:07:22.650 --> 02:07:24.910
Scale bars have been
used for a while.

02:07:24.910 --> 02:07:27.820
As you can see, Hooke
used quite a lot of them

02:07:27.820 --> 02:07:29.300
in his <i>Micrografia </i>.

02:07:29.300 --> 02:07:33.320
This is blue mold that's
been magnified, I think 200

02:07:33.320 --> 02:07:36.040
or 300 times, really lovely.

02:07:36.040 --> 02:07:39.080
Again, he's using the
circular view but this idea

02:07:39.080 --> 02:07:41.520
of the scale bar
was really useful.

02:07:41.520 --> 02:07:44.510
We apply scale bars
in astronomy as well.

02:07:44.510 --> 02:07:47.740
In this case, however, the
scale is quite difficult.

02:07:47.740 --> 02:07:49.070
We actually are looking here

02:07:49.070 --> 02:07:53.260
at the El Gordo cluster
of galaxies.

02:07:53.260 --> 02:07:56.640
This is the most
massive distant cluster

02:07:56.640 --> 02:07:59.840
of galaxies we've ever been
able to detect with a mass

02:07:59.840 --> 02:08:02.740
of about three quadrillion suns.

02:08:02.740 --> 02:08:08.070
This image is seven
million light years across.

02:08:08.070 --> 02:08:11.580
Again, light year, 10
trillion kilometers.

02:08:11.580 --> 02:08:13.000
It's really huge.

02:08:13.000 --> 02:08:16.230
We provide a scale in
[inaudible], not super helpful.

02:08:16.230 --> 02:08:18.960
So typically, when I'm
talking about scale,

02:08:18.960 --> 02:08:20.790
I really do like to
try to break it down,

02:08:20.790 --> 02:08:22.970
at the very least,
into light years.

02:08:22.970 --> 02:08:24.910
But even light years, I think,

02:08:24.910 --> 02:08:29.930
are hard to really
grasp the size of them.

02:08:29.930 --> 02:08:33.450
When we talk about how we
represent these objects

02:08:33.450 --> 02:08:37.270
physically, I was always
struck by this image

02:08:37.270 --> 02:08:39.990
from <i>Micrografia</i>
which is the flea.

02:08:39.990 --> 02:08:43.750
And if you've ever seen it
in person, it's like the size

02:08:43.750 --> 02:08:46.400
of a cat or maybe a
small dog even, right?

02:08:46.400 --> 02:08:48.720
I think it's kind of
ironic because, you know,

02:08:48.720 --> 02:08:50.020
fleas like cats and dogs.

02:08:50.020 --> 02:08:51.320
So I don't know if that
was intentional or not.

02:08:51.320 --> 02:08:53.940
But I've always thought
it was really funny.

02:08:53.940 --> 02:08:58.360
But it's this idea of the
outsized, it adds such a sense

02:08:58.360 --> 02:09:02.580
of drama and spectacle
for the viewer.

02:09:02.580 --> 02:09:06.520
And I think spectacle might
perhaps be a little undersold

02:09:06.520 --> 02:09:07.820
as a technique.

02:09:07.820 --> 02:09:11.170
I really do appreciate
the artistic merit

02:09:11.170 --> 02:09:14.020
that creating something
like this took

02:09:14.020 --> 02:09:16.380
and what effect it has.

02:09:16.380 --> 02:09:19.310
In astronomy, it's
difficult to go really big

02:09:19.310 --> 02:09:22.610
because the objects are so huge.

02:09:22.610 --> 02:09:25.600
So we can show something
on a wall.

02:09:25.600 --> 02:09:27.890
I guess you guys are looking
at a pretty large version.

02:09:27.890 --> 02:09:29.190
That's kind of cool.

02:09:29.190 --> 02:09:32.650
We can go, you know, a little
bit more dimensional and big

02:09:32.650 --> 02:09:34.890
and really the only reason
I chose this picture is

02:09:34.890 --> 02:09:36.240
because when I was
looking through it,

02:09:36.240 --> 02:09:40.050
I saw that Her Majesty
the Queen was in there.

02:09:40.050 --> 02:09:43.400
I thought we would maybe
take a little quick stop

02:09:43.400 --> 02:09:46.430
for all the talking this
morning and play a game.

02:09:46.430 --> 02:09:53.040
What I thought we would do is
look at a few modern images

02:09:53.040 --> 02:09:56.270
from microscopy because I didn't
want it to be just historical.

02:09:56.270 --> 02:09:59.040
A lot of the things that I'll be
talking about and haven't talked

02:09:59.040 --> 02:10:03.040
about so far reflect on new
just as much as the old.

02:10:03.040 --> 02:10:08.170
And so here, I've actually
gathered pairs of images

02:10:08.170 --> 02:10:12.030
from microscopy as well as
astronomy just to showcase some

02:10:12.030 --> 02:10:15.100
of the unintentional
similarities that are

02:10:15.100 --> 02:10:18.810
to be found in these
things across such very,

02:10:18.810 --> 02:10:20.110
very different scales.

02:10:20.110 --> 02:10:24.260
So if we look at the --
let's take the bottom right.

02:10:24.260 --> 02:10:26.520
Now, one of these is
really big and one

02:10:26.520 --> 02:10:27.820
of these is really small.

02:10:27.820 --> 02:10:30.300
How many people think
the one on the left

02:10:30.300 --> 02:10:34.560
