02:12:52.600 --> 02:12:55.830
Now I think, you know, a lot
of you got the answers right.

02:12:55.830 --> 02:12:57.480
Not that you know, it's a quiz.

02:12:57.480 --> 02:13:02.170
But I think it is -- there are
visual cues that you can follow,

02:13:02.170 --> 02:13:04.960
resolution and scale
and structure.

02:13:04.960 --> 02:13:06.440
But I just thought it
was really interesting

02:13:06.440 --> 02:13:08.180
to see so many similarities.

02:13:08.180 --> 02:13:10.470
And when I'm talking about
that visual language,

02:13:10.470 --> 02:13:14.350
it still applies to modern
microscopy images as well

02:13:14.350 --> 02:13:16.450
as astronomical images.

02:13:16.450 --> 02:13:20.720
So I'm just going to
do a little brief segue

02:13:20.720 --> 02:13:23.580
into what I do all day.

02:13:23.580 --> 02:13:25.860
So this is an image of our sun

02:13:25.860 --> 02:13:27.960
and it's actually showing
the many different kinds

02:13:27.960 --> 02:13:29.940
of light that our sun emits.

02:13:29.940 --> 02:13:33.700
One of the really important
tools in astronomy is the fact

02:13:33.700 --> 02:13:37.040
that there is this entire
multi-wavelength spectrum

02:13:37.040 --> 02:13:39.060
of information in order

02:13:39.060 --> 02:13:41.880
to understand things
in the universe.

02:13:41.880 --> 02:13:45.360
And we really need to understand
many different kinds of light

02:13:45.360 --> 02:13:48.970
in order to grasp the
objects that we're looking at.

02:13:48.970 --> 02:13:52.040
This is one of my favorite
objects in the entire universe.

02:13:52.040 --> 02:13:57.620
And I get to see that because
essentially it's the first

02:13:57.620 --> 02:14:01.220
object that the telescope that
I work for ever looked at.

02:14:01.220 --> 02:14:04.840
It's Cassiopeia A which
is a star that exploded.

02:14:04.840 --> 02:14:06.400
Yes, I know.

02:14:06.400 --> 02:14:07.700
It's a super nova remnant.

02:14:07.700 --> 02:14:11.260
It is about 10 to
11,000 light years away

02:14:11.260 --> 02:14:13.770
so 10,000 time 10
trillion kilometers.

02:14:13.770 --> 02:14:15.750
And we're looking
at it with data

02:14:15.750 --> 02:14:18.030
from the Hubble Space
Telescope, quite beautiful,

02:14:18.030 --> 02:14:22.730
showing this 10-million-degree
filamentary structure.

02:14:22.730 --> 02:14:26.130
We look at that exact same
field of view that I've selected

02:14:26.130 --> 02:14:29.060
from Chandra's X-ray Observatory

02:14:29.060 --> 02:14:31.500
and we get a completely
different view

02:14:31.500 --> 02:14:33.360
of the same patch of sky.

02:14:33.360 --> 02:14:34.750
So utilizing different kinds

02:14:34.750 --> 02:14:36.690
of light is really
important for us.

02:14:36.690 --> 02:14:39.110
If we composite the
two images together,

02:14:39.110 --> 02:14:40.940
we get a better sense
of what's going on.

02:14:40.940 --> 02:14:43.890
Because as we noticed from the
exercise earlier, sometimes,

02:14:43.890 --> 02:14:46.540
if you're looking at
an image like that,

02:14:46.540 --> 02:14:49.010
if you don't have some
sort of recognizable sense

02:14:49.010 --> 02:14:51.560
or if the fact that you know
there's an astronomy person

02:14:51.560 --> 02:14:53.960
in front of you talking about
it, you might not be aware

02:14:53.960 --> 02:14:56.760
that it is actually an
image of a universal scale

02:14:56.760 --> 02:14:59.580
versus something small.

02:14:59.580 --> 02:15:01.600
But images of the universe,

02:15:01.600 --> 02:15:03.330
they start out looking
a little bit more

02:15:03.330 --> 02:15:05.820
like this or maybe like that.

02:15:05.820 --> 02:15:07.220
But really, it's this.

02:15:07.220 --> 02:15:10.970
So these images start
out in this digital way.

02:15:10.970 --> 02:15:12.700
We create them.

02:15:12.700 --> 02:15:16.260
You know, these are not
giant cosmic selfies.

02:15:16.260 --> 02:15:21.150
We have to create them from
the stream of ones and zeroes.

02:15:21.150 --> 02:15:24.610
And the way we do that
is we have the object

02:15:24.610 --> 02:15:26.660
in the sky quite far
away, Cassiopeia A

02:15:26.660 --> 02:15:28.700
in this example,
10,000 light years.

02:15:28.700 --> 02:15:31.250
That light has been
travelling for a while.

02:15:31.250 --> 02:15:34.110
It's recorded by this spacecraft

02:15:34.110 --> 02:15:35.630
and this is the Chandra
X-ray Observatory.

02:15:35.630 --> 02:15:38.500
And then that information is
bundled up in the form of ones

02:15:38.500 --> 02:15:45.980
and zeroes and sent down to my
laptop wherever that might be.

02:15:45.980 --> 02:15:50.770
We then get to turn it into a
table which is very exciting.

02:15:50.770 --> 02:15:55.840
This table essentially records
the distance of the location X

02:15:55.840 --> 02:16:00.460
and Y, the amount of energy,
how long it was observed,

02:16:00.460 --> 02:16:03.120
very fascinating
to look at, I know.

02:16:03.120 --> 02:16:04.440
But then we use more software

02:16:04.440 --> 02:16:09.160
and then we finally get a visual
representation of the object.

02:16:09.160 --> 02:16:12.890
So we have quite a few steps
before it gets to here.

02:16:12.890 --> 02:16:15.210
And this is pretty
far along already.

02:16:15.210 --> 02:16:18.490
I've scaled it, removed
artifacts,

02:16:18.490 --> 02:16:21.480
perhaps composited a couple
of observations together

02:16:21.480 --> 02:16:22.780
to get a deeper data set.

02:16:22.780 --> 02:16:25.560
And then the final
step is color.

02:16:26.830 --> 02:16:31.310
Typically, we use again the
science to tell the story.

02:16:31.310 --> 02:16:32.790
We have a perspective.

02:16:32.790 --> 02:16:35.040
We are trying to get
something across.

02:16:35.040 --> 02:16:38.100
And in this case, the
way we cut up the colors

02:16:38.100 --> 02:16:41.840
and the energy cuts, we can
see the blue was assigned

02:16:41.840 --> 02:16:43.690
to the highest energy x-rays.

02:16:43.690 --> 02:16:46.150
The green, to the medium x-rays.

02:16:46.150 --> 02:16:48.450
And the red to the
lowest energy x-rays

02:16:48.450 --> 02:16:51.420
to create what we call
a chromatic ordering.

02:16:51.420 --> 02:16:55.640
Now, it's like a weather map on
weather.com or the nightly news.

02:16:55.640 --> 02:16:59.620
The point is to help fit
more information to add

02:16:59.620 --> 02:17:01.500
to the information
quotient of this image.

02:17:01.500 --> 02:17:07.160
It's important to see where that
high energy x-ray material is,

02:17:07.160 --> 02:17:08.460
for example.

02:17:08.460 --> 02:17:10.110
As you can probably
tell, it's along the rim

02:17:10.110 --> 02:17:13.520
and that's essentially the
expanding shockwave going

02:17:13.520 --> 02:17:14.940
out into space.

02:17:14.940 --> 02:17:17.440
So we've colored
it this way here

02:17:17.440 --> 02:17:19.600
but we could color
it a different way

02:17:19.600 --> 02:17:20.900
for a different purpose.

02:17:20.900 --> 02:17:23.710
For example, we put out a
release not that long ago

02:17:23.710 --> 02:17:27.750
that had this image color-coded
by chemical element so similar

02:17:27.750 --> 02:17:29.310
to the one I talked
about earlier.

02:17:29.310 --> 02:17:32.000
And the whole point of
that image was to show

02:17:32.000 --> 02:17:35.740
that essentially, the
elements that we have inside

02:17:35.740 --> 02:17:38.680
of us come from,
they originate the --

02:17:38.680 --> 02:17:42.560
original originals from stars
like this when they explode.

02:17:42.560 --> 02:17:43.940
So we have this data.

02:17:43.940 --> 02:17:45.930
We don't have to look
at it just in 2D.

02:17:45.930 --> 02:17:48.350
We can look at it
in two D over time.

02:17:48.350 --> 02:17:50.230
This is looking at
versions of the data

02:17:50.230 --> 02:17:53.620
from 2000, 2002, 2004, and 2007.

02:17:53.620 --> 02:17:56.630
And we can see that this
observation is changing

02:17:56.630 --> 02:17:59.020
and that this image
is expanding.

02:17:59.020 --> 02:18:02.040
And what we learned from
this is that outer shockwave

02:18:02.040 --> 02:18:03.990
that I mentioned a
minute ago is traveling

02:18:03.990 --> 02:18:06.760
at around 11 million
miles per hour.

02:18:06.760 --> 02:18:10.010
So adding time to our
data, again adds more

02:18:10.010 --> 02:18:12.370
to that information quotient.

02:18:12.370 --> 02:18:15.200
But we wanted to do more so
we worked with a scientist,

02:18:15.200 --> 02:18:19.930
Tracey DeLaney to figure out how
to create a 3D map of this data.

02:18:19.930 --> 02:18:24.690
We included optical and infrared
data to get a stronger picture

02:18:24.690 --> 02:18:27.730
and mapped it by using
the Doppler Effect

02:18:27.730 --> 02:18:31.800
by a simple assumption of the
geometry that it was radiating

02:18:31.800 --> 02:18:33.730
out from a specific point.

02:18:33.730 --> 02:18:37.830
And also by borrowing
brain imaging software

02:18:37.830 --> 02:18:39.960
from a local Boston hospital

02:18:39.960 --> 02:18:42.600
because we didn't have our
own free software at the time.

02:18:42.600 --> 02:18:45.420
So again, big and
small, who knows?

02:18:45.420 --> 02:18:48.460
But this image is the
first time we're ever able

02:18:48.460 --> 02:18:52.400
to see a data-driven map of
our friend, Cassiopeia A,

02:18:52.400 --> 02:18:54.480
this exploded star
10,000 light years away,

02:18:54.480 --> 02:18:56.170
10,000 times 10 trillion
kilometers.

02:18:56.170 --> 02:18:58.730
And we're seeing it
in three dimensions.

02:18:58.730 --> 02:19:02.110
Now, it does not look very
recognizable in that form

02:19:02.110 --> 02:19:05.000
so we took a wire frame of
that data and we brought it

02:19:05.000 --> 02:19:08.010
into a 3D software package
so that we could apply colors

02:19:08.010 --> 02:19:10.080
and textures that
looked a little bit more

02:19:10.080 --> 02:19:11.860
like this thing might look.

02:19:11.860 --> 02:19:14.240
That made it look a little
bit more astronomical

02:19:14.240 --> 02:19:18.060
to help give it that
visual contextualization.

02:19:18.060 --> 02:19:21.300
And so, it's data-driven in this
sense but it's a step removed

02:19:21.300 --> 02:19:23.450
from the last version
which is a step removed

02:19:23.450 --> 02:19:26.650
from the version before
that, et cetera, et cetera.

02:19:26.650 --> 02:19:30.100
So this is the first time we're
ever able to see through, below,

02:19:30.100 --> 02:19:32.050
above, behind a star

02:19:32.050 --> 02:19:34.240
that exploded 10,000
light years away,

02:19:34.240 --> 02:19:36.630
10,000 times 10 trillion
kilometers.

02:19:36.630 --> 02:19:40.410
But it was created by data.

02:19:40.410 --> 02:19:42.200
We weren't quite done.

02:19:42.200 --> 02:19:44.990
We thought, "Wouldn't it
be fun to hold this thing?"

02:19:44.990 --> 02:19:46.290
Yes, we did.

02:19:46.290 --> 02:19:48.850
So we worked with our friends
from the Smithsonian and then

02:19:48.850 --> 02:19:51.890
over here but we figured
out how to 3D model

02:19:51.890 --> 02:19:56.970
or a 3D print this 3D model
and we finally just last week,

02:19:56.970 --> 02:20:00.200
figured out how to add
color to our 3D model.

02:20:00.200 --> 02:20:03.340
So now, we can hold a
dead star in our hands.

02:20:03.340 --> 02:20:06.010
And we can understand
in this case,

02:20:06.010 --> 02:20:09.300
the various chemical elements so
where the sulfur is coming from.

02:20:09.300 --> 02:20:10.840
I think that was the
red in this version,

02:20:10.840 --> 02:20:13.620
where the silicon is coming
from, where is the iron.

02:20:13.620 --> 02:20:17.370
And the only thing I noticed
just for posterity is that I had

02:20:17.370 --> 02:20:19.460
to leave the jets at home
because they're so fragile

02:20:19.460 --> 02:20:21.060
and I was on an early
flight this morning.

02:20:21.060 --> 02:20:23.140
I just didn't want to deal so
just pretend there are a couple

02:20:23.140 --> 02:20:26.140
of jets sticking out of that.

02:20:26.140 --> 02:20:28.450
But yeah, so this is the first
time we could hold the dead star

02:20:28.450 --> 02:20:29.750
in our hands.

02:20:29.750 --> 02:20:32.230
Again, hugely scaled down.

02:20:32.230 --> 02:20:36.660
This is about 40 million
billion times the area

02:20:36.660 --> 02:20:39.430
of our sun and eight planets.

02:20:39.430 --> 02:20:40.730
You could toss in Pluto.

02:20:40.730 --> 02:20:45.140
It wouldn't make a difference
but it's really big, right.

02:20:45.140 --> 02:20:47.880
And it's dynamic, as
I mentioned before.

02:20:47.880 --> 02:20:49.560
It's changing over time.

02:20:49.560 --> 02:20:53.000
So you're seeing it, you
know, small in plastic.

02:20:53.000 --> 02:20:54.480
So take that for what it will.

02:20:54.480 --> 02:20:56.540
It's another representation.

02:20:56.540 --> 02:20:58.960
But we weren't done yet.

02:20:58.960 --> 02:21:00.260
Let's see.

02:21:00.260 --> 02:21:01.560
I think this is the only video

02:21:01.560 --> 02:21:03.190
that does not play
on automatically.

02:21:03.190 --> 02:21:04.490
Here we go.

02:21:04.490 --> 02:21:08.250
I thought wouldn't it fun if we
can walk inside this dead star?

02:21:08.250 --> 02:21:10.270
So we took it to
Brown University

02:21:10.270 --> 02:21:13.120
and some fantastic
collaborators there.

02:21:13.120 --> 02:21:15.340
We were able to create a
virtual reality version

02:21:15.340 --> 02:21:17.260
of that same data.

02:21:17.260 --> 02:21:19.640
And now, you can see this
is one of my students.

02:21:19.640 --> 02:21:21.750
She is walking inside
a dead star.

02:21:21.750 --> 02:21:23.400
The camera person
is outside the star

02:21:23.400 --> 02:21:24.700
which is why it looks
like she's not it.

02:21:24.700 --> 02:21:26.000
But she's in it.

02:21:26.000 --> 02:21:29.840
Trust me. So she's walking
around inside a dead star,

02:21:29.840 --> 02:21:33.110
Cassiopeia A, 10,000 light
years away, and she's inside it.

02:21:33.110 --> 02:21:34.410
And this is data.

02:21:34.410 --> 02:21:36.390
This is data representations.

02:21:36.390 --> 02:21:40.040
So we've created many
different versions

02:21:40.040 --> 02:21:44.620
of this one famous super nova
remnant and I think as --

02:21:44.620 --> 02:21:48.190
I think Roger mentioned this
point, very collaborative.

02:21:48.190 --> 02:21:49.560
This is not me doing this.

02:21:49.560 --> 02:21:50.920
This is not one person
doing this.

02:21:50.920 --> 02:21:53.970
This is just teams upon
teams of people working

02:21:53.970 --> 02:21:56.330
to create different
versions of their data

02:21:56.330 --> 02:21:59.920
for very specific reasons.

02:21:59.920 --> 02:22:02.340
But they all started here.

02:22:02.340 --> 02:22:04.340
All of these data versions came

02:22:04.340 --> 02:22:06.330
out of this original
bit of code.

02:22:06.330 --> 02:22:08.600
So really quick.

02:22:08.600 --> 02:22:11.990
I thought [inaudible] to
do a little case study,

02:22:11.990 --> 02:22:15.050
I guess, of images over time.

02:22:15.050 --> 02:22:18.790
And it was this whole
idea of the image as truth

02:22:18.790 --> 02:22:20.850
that I thought would
be really interesting.

02:22:20.850 --> 02:22:23.200
I think there is this idea

02:22:23.200 --> 02:22:28.970
that modern photography
has removed the objectivity

02:22:28.970 --> 02:22:32.920
of these things or
subjectivity, I should say.

02:22:32.920 --> 02:22:35.490
And that they are
more truthful now.

02:22:35.490 --> 02:22:39.600
Well, perhaps but when we look
at this image from Galileo

02:22:39.600 --> 02:22:41.630
of the moon, we already
heard there was an issue

02:22:41.630 --> 02:22:42.930
with it, right?

02:22:42.930 --> 02:22:46.040
So this is not "accurate
representation."

02:22:46.040 --> 02:22:49.050
He was creating this
version for his own purposes

02:22:49.050 --> 02:22:51.170
and it's really lovely.

02:22:51.170 --> 02:22:55.050
We can look at this version
which is a daguerreotype

02:22:55.050 --> 02:22:57.210
and that's essentially
a process that was kind

02:22:57.210 --> 02:22:59.430
of like a precursor
to modern photography

02:22:59.430 --> 02:23:02.000
that uses a combination of
chemical agents essentially

02:23:02.000 --> 02:23:04.190
to create something that
looks very photographic.

02:23:04.190 --> 02:23:06.180
This is the oldest
surviving daguerreotype

02:23:06.180 --> 02:23:07.480
of the moon, by the way.

02:23:07.480 --> 02:23:10.860
I think it was from
John Whipple.

02:23:10.860 --> 02:23:15.630
And then, we can see the moon
from the Apollo missions.

02:23:15.630 --> 02:23:22.290
And this was as Apollo 11
was on their way back home.

02:23:22.290 --> 02:23:26.230
And I think this was maybe
10,000 nautical miles away.

02:23:26.230 --> 02:23:29.380
And it was one of
them snapped a photo

02:23:29.380 --> 02:23:31.490
and we have this
version of the moon.

02:23:31.490 --> 02:23:35.970
Is that more real than
this one or this one?

02:23:35.970 --> 02:23:38.820
Perhaps. Is it more truthful?

02:23:38.820 --> 02:23:41.830
Perhaps. Then we
have this version.

02:23:41.830 --> 02:23:45.450
This is using a special
nine-millimeter telescope,

02:23:45.450 --> 02:23:47.080
super top of the line,

02:23:47.080 --> 02:23:50.320
the
astrophotographer/astrophysicist

02:23:50.320 --> 02:23:53.620
who's a friend of mine who's
working on this, Travis Rector,

02:23:53.620 --> 02:23:55.670
got this great deep data set.

02:23:55.670 --> 02:23:57.600
It's just incredible,
high resolution

02:23:57.600 --> 02:23:59.540
that we're able to
see the moon in.

02:23:59.540 --> 02:24:02.270
But he wanted to put
it in the perspective

02:24:02.270 --> 02:24:04.280
of its cosmic background.

02:24:04.280 --> 02:24:06.370
So he grabbed a shot from
a different telescope

02:24:06.370 --> 02:24:09.720
of the exact placement of the
moon from the stars behind it.

02:24:09.720 --> 02:24:13.090
So this was a composite of
the two images together.

02:24:13.090 --> 02:24:16.260
You can't physically take
these two images as one just

02:24:16.260 --> 02:24:18.710
because of the brightness
and the resolution issues.

02:24:18.710 --> 02:24:20.520
So is this one more truthful?

02:24:20.520 --> 02:24:22.020
Is this one more real?

02:24:22.020 --> 02:24:26.480
And because you know, I'm paid
by NASA's Chandra Observatory,

02:24:26.480 --> 02:24:29.790
this is a version from the
Chandra X-ray Observatory.

02:24:29.790 --> 02:24:32.360
The x-rays are shown
in blue and mapped

02:24:32.360 --> 02:24:35.230
over an optical image
of the same phase.

02:24:35.230 --> 02:24:38.610
And here, it was really
useful for us to understand

02:24:38.610 --> 02:24:40.670
where x-rays from the
moon were coming from

02:24:40.670 --> 02:24:44.430
and they are essentially a
reflection of the solar x-rays.

02:24:44.430 --> 02:24:47.240
But we understood that
fluorescence has happened here

02:24:47.240 --> 02:24:49.490
and it helps resolve a
mystery that had been

02:24:49.490 --> 02:24:51.260
around for decades
so it was cool.

02:24:51.260 --> 02:24:53.560
Is this one more truthful?

02:24:56.040 --> 02:25:01.070
So my last little
mini-story that I want to tell

02:25:01.070 --> 02:25:03.960
because I'm sure the [inaudible]
is getting a little antsy is

02:25:03.960 --> 02:25:07.620
just that it's one thing to
talk about how people like me

02:25:07.620 --> 02:25:11.230
or teams of me create
images like this.

02:25:11.230 --> 02:25:14.330
But when we talk about who
we're creating them from,

02:25:14.330 --> 02:25:15.730
that's a whole other
thing together.

02:25:15.730 --> 02:25:18.610
You can have as much data
in an archive as you want.

02:25:18.610 --> 02:25:21.270
But that has potential value.

02:25:21.270 --> 02:25:24.610
Data that's been visualized
for a specific point

02:25:24.610 --> 02:25:29.520
but for a specific audience has
even more added value to it.

02:25:29.520 --> 02:25:33.550
So we started a research project
called Aesthetics and Astronomy.

02:25:33.550 --> 02:25:36.620
It's me and a couple
of other folks imaging,

02:25:36.620 --> 02:25:39.150
psychologist, aesthetics types.

02:25:39.150 --> 02:25:43.050
And we were able to
understand how experts

02:25:43.050 --> 02:25:45.390
and non-experts approach images

02:25:45.390 --> 02:25:48.020
of our universe quite
differently.

02:25:48.020 --> 02:25:50.760
In this case, we're looking at
the Bullet Cluster of galaxies.

02:25:50.760 --> 02:25:56.580
It's this really tremendous
image about where the separation

02:25:56.580 --> 02:25:58.890
of normal matter and
dark matter occurs.

02:25:58.890 --> 02:26:00.720
And it's actually a
visual representation

02:26:00.720 --> 02:26:02.040
of that process happening

02:26:02.040 --> 02:26:04.570
which we have never
been able to see before.

02:26:04.570 --> 02:26:07.780
The normal matter is in
pink and this dark matter

02:26:07.780 --> 02:26:09.780
of which there's an awful
lot of it in the universe

02:26:09.780 --> 02:26:12.820
that we know very little
about, is shown in blue.

02:26:12.820 --> 02:26:14.940
And when an astronomer
looks at this image,

02:26:14.940 --> 02:26:17.700
they immediately want to know
what telescopes are involved.

02:26:17.700 --> 02:26:19.000
So what's the science?

02:26:19.000 --> 02:26:20.550
What's the interesting,
you know,

02:26:20.550 --> 02:26:22.810
observational thing
going on here?

02:26:22.810 --> 02:26:25.450
When a non-expert looks at
the same image, it's wow,

02:26:25.450 --> 02:26:27.240
that's beautiful first.

02:26:27.240 --> 02:26:29.230
Then eventually, they
want to know things

02:26:29.230 --> 02:26:30.990
like well, what is it?

02:26:30.990 --> 02:26:34.150
What does the scientist
see when he or she looks

02:26:34.150 --> 02:26:35.690
at something like this?

02:26:35.690 --> 02:26:39.230
The expert, after formulating
those first questions,

02:26:39.230 --> 02:26:41.340
slowly drifts into,
"Wow, that's beautiful."

02:26:41.340 --> 02:26:43.630
Or maybe, you might get a
"That's cool," if they're,

02:26:43.630 --> 02:26:46.450
you know, a little
more on the down low.

02:26:46.450 --> 02:26:50.880
But so, that idea of wonder
is immediate for a non-expert

02:26:50.880 --> 02:26:54.290
and secondary for an expert.

02:26:54.290 --> 02:26:56.380
Color, incredibly important.

02:26:56.380 --> 02:26:58.680
As I mentioned, we're looking
at something we can't see

02:26:58.680 --> 02:27:01.500
with our sad, puny
human eyes, right.

02:27:01.500 --> 02:27:04.770
So does it matter
what colors I choose?

02:27:04.770 --> 02:27:06.330
If it doesn't really
have anything to do

02:27:06.330 --> 02:27:08.910
with the science story, in
this case, we're looking

02:27:08.910 --> 02:27:11.190
at a galaxy, NGC 4696.

02:27:11.190 --> 02:27:14.150
I think it's about 50
million light years away.

02:27:14.150 --> 02:27:16.340
Relatively close in the
grand scheme of things.

02:27:16.340 --> 02:27:18.790
There is this super
massive black hole inside

02:27:18.790 --> 02:27:22.870
that white core that is spewing
out these high energy particles

02:27:22.870 --> 02:27:25.410
and then causing all of this
material that you're looking

02:27:25.410 --> 02:27:27.370
at to be super-heated.

02:27:27.370 --> 02:27:29.810
This was the way the
image looked at first.

02:27:29.810 --> 02:27:33.000
The main difference
between those two,

02:27:33.000 --> 02:27:36.300
the x-ray is colored
blue in this version

02:27:36.300 --> 02:27:38.390
and colored red in this version.

02:27:38.390 --> 02:27:41.150
Now this image was meant to
be for a non-expert audience.

02:27:41.150 --> 02:27:45.130
We were trying to talk about
the heat in this galaxy.

02:27:45.130 --> 02:27:48.120
So which version should we
have released to the public?

02:27:48.120 --> 02:27:49.730
Who likes the red version?

02:27:49.730 --> 02:27:51.250
Raise your hands.

02:27:51.250 --> 02:27:52.550
Yeah, who likes the blue?

02:27:52.550 --> 02:27:53.850
All right.

02:27:53.850 --> 02:27:56.900
You're a physicist,
aren't you [laughter]?

02:27:56.900 --> 02:28:02.390
So physicists like this version
because in physics, blue is hot.

02:28:02.390 --> 02:28:05.990
But the rest of us
non-physicists,

02:28:05.990 --> 02:28:07.570
who says to their
kid, "Don't touch

02:28:07.570 --> 02:28:09.870
that stove, it's blue hot?"

02:28:10.960 --> 02:28:12.260
Maybe you do.

02:28:12.260 --> 02:28:15.730
But I don't so the whole point
is color has a very specific

02:28:15.730 --> 02:28:18.320
cultural context, a very
specific power to it.

02:28:18.320 --> 02:28:21.860
And if you're trying to get a
point across, red versus blue?

02:28:21.860 --> 02:28:23.450
It doesn't matter for the data.

02:28:23.450 --> 02:28:25.250
The data does not care.

02:28:25.250 --> 02:28:28.480
But it does matter for
who's looking at it.

02:28:28.480 --> 02:28:31.050
Scale, I know [Inaudible]
talked about this briefly.

02:28:31.050 --> 02:28:34.510
What I'm just bringing up
very quickly is that again,

02:28:34.510 --> 02:28:38.060
scale is hard in astronomy
to do in a really well way.

02:28:38.060 --> 02:28:40.940
But people at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art in New York,

02:28:40.940 --> 02:28:43.760
they typically spend about 17
seconds on standing in front

02:28:43.760 --> 02:28:46.970
of a masterpiece, define
masterpiece how you will.

02:28:46.970 --> 02:28:50.050
People looking at astronomical
images on a screen just

02:28:50.050 --> 02:28:52.720
about the same amount of
time, that 17-second mark.

02:28:52.720 --> 02:28:56.420
However, you add a scale bar and
it could have very minimal text,

02:28:56.420 --> 02:29:00.460
just something like this,
doubles that, that viewing time

02:29:00.460 --> 02:29:03.310
because it gives them
something to think about.

02:29:03.310 --> 02:29:06.370
Now, why am I showing
this picture?

02:29:06.370 --> 02:29:11.010
So this is one of my favorite
stories by an artist that --

02:29:11.010 --> 02:29:13.430
I just love his taste.

02:29:13.430 --> 02:29:16.240
This is Madame Henri-Francois
Riesener --

02:29:16.240 --> 02:29:18.860
I don't speak French so
excuse my pronunciation --

02:29:18.860 --> 02:29:22.660
by the artist Eugene
Delacroix, 1835.

02:29:22.660 --> 02:29:26.430
Now, I'm not an artist or an
art expert or a historian.

02:29:26.430 --> 02:29:29.780
If I were in a gallery at the
Smithsonian and there were tons

02:29:29.780 --> 02:29:31.970
of pictures to look at,
I wouldn't know to look

02:29:31.970 --> 02:29:33.830
at this one specifically.

02:29:33.830 --> 02:29:38.490
But this woman was
the artist's aunt.

02:29:38.490 --> 02:29:41.590
And really you can see kind
of like this frank tenderness,

02:29:41.590 --> 02:29:43.000
I think, in the portrait.

02:29:43.000 --> 02:29:44.960
But I just want to read
this one little bit.

02:29:44.960 --> 02:29:46.490
She was known for her beauty.

02:29:46.490 --> 02:29:48.600
Some 30 years before the
date of this portrait,

02:29:48.600 --> 02:29:51.530
she served as a lady-in-waiting
to Empress Josephine

02:29:51.530 --> 02:29:52.900
and having caught
Napoleon's eye,

02:29:52.900 --> 02:29:54.690
engaged in a brief
liaison with him.

02:29:54.690 --> 02:29:58.330
After she died, Delacroix wrote
to his friend, George Sand,

02:29:58.330 --> 02:30:01.620
"Each of the beings necessary
to our existence who disappears,

02:30:01.620 --> 02:30:04.160
takes away with him a
whole world of feelings

02:30:04.160 --> 02:30:08.190
that no other relationship
can revive."

02:30:08.190 --> 02:30:09.490
My husband's here.

02:30:09.490 --> 02:30:10.790
I hope he would write
something like that about me

02:30:10.790 --> 02:30:14.640
after I'm gone because that's a
pretty powerful letter, right?

02:30:14.640 --> 02:30:18.040
But that immediately makes this
piece so much more interesting.

02:30:18.040 --> 02:30:20.690
Now that I know the
story, I would stop.

02:30:20.690 --> 02:30:23.370
It's the similar situation
in astronomy, right?

02:30:23.370 --> 02:30:26.190
We see that this is
beautiful and now,

02:30:26.190 --> 02:30:29.610
I can kind of see something in
there that I didn't see before.

02:30:29.610 --> 02:30:32.810
But if we're just looking
at a picture such as Saturn

02:30:32.810 --> 02:30:34.650
in ultraviolet light, it's great

02:30:34.650 --> 02:30:36.730
to have scientific
purpose, absolutely.

02:30:36.730 --> 02:30:38.030
But if we're trying

02:30:38.030 --> 02:30:39.950
to communicate something
interesting about it,

02:30:39.950 --> 02:30:42.700
the one thing that typically
gets people is that --

02:30:42.700 --> 02:30:44.400
oh, if you can see
on the screen.

02:30:44.400 --> 02:30:47.210
Let me see if I can -- oh, yeah.

02:30:47.210 --> 02:30:48.510
There it is.

02:30:48.510 --> 02:30:49.810
See that little dot?

02:30:49.810 --> 02:30:52.480
That's Earth waving back

02:30:52.480 --> 02:30:54.960
at the Cassini mission
that took this image.

02:30:54.960 --> 02:30:59.530
So we are in the context of
this image taken very far away

02:30:59.530 --> 02:31:01.960
from us and in a
different kind of light.

02:31:01.960 --> 02:31:04.860
But that idea that we
can add to the story,

02:31:04.860 --> 02:31:06.470
I think is really helpful.

02:31:06.470 --> 02:31:11.540
And we found that when we
add really important, useful,

02:31:11.540 --> 02:31:15.450
relevant, interesting
descriptions or images,

02:31:15.450 --> 02:31:17.530
we increase the viewing
time dramatically,

02:31:17.530 --> 02:31:20.460
not just the amount of time
it takes them to read the text

02:31:20.460 --> 02:31:23.150
but also in just how much
people will ponder it.

02:31:23.150 --> 02:31:27.630
But beyond just the viewing
time, the aesthetic appreciation

02:31:27.630 --> 02:31:31.250
for this image improved
dramatically

02:31:31.250 --> 02:31:34.040
when we had the contextual
information presented with it

02:31:34.040 --> 02:31:36.860
than when it was
presented just on its own.

02:31:36.860 --> 02:31:38.470
So there is a time for spectacle

02:31:38.470 --> 02:31:40.660
and then there is
a time for context.

02:31:40.660 --> 02:31:42.370
So, I'm pretty much done.

02:31:42.370 --> 02:31:44.960
I'll just say, "I read books
about this stuff because I'm

02:31:44.960 --> 02:31:46.260
so fascinated about it.

02:31:46.260 --> 02:31:48.210
I'm really happy to
be here today to learn

02:31:48.210 --> 02:31:51.090
from everybody else and see
what everybody else is doing.

02:31:51.090 --> 02:31:52.700
But essentially, you
know, these images

02:31:52.700 --> 02:31:56.590
of our universe are not
just cosmic selfies.

02:31:56.590 --> 02:31:57.890
We create them.

02:31:57.890 --> 02:31:59.190
We have a viewpoint.

02:31:59.190 --> 02:32:00.490
We are people.

02:32:00.490 --> 02:32:01.790
We have our biases.

02:32:01.790 --> 02:32:05.310
We should be more transparent
with how we do them and why.

02:32:05.310 --> 02:32:09.520
We try very hard to be for the
telescopes that I worked for,

02:32:09.520 --> 02:32:13.620
using descriptions and having
features on how we made things

02:32:13.620 --> 02:32:16.640
and breaking down the
image into various pieces.

02:32:16.640 --> 02:32:19.020
But I just want to
end with this quote.

02:32:19.020 --> 02:32:22.270
"By means of telescopes, there
is nothing so far distant

02:32:22.270 --> 02:32:24.900
but maybe represented to
our view and by the help

02:32:24.900 --> 02:32:27.020
of microscopes, there
is nothing so small

02:32:27.020 --> 02:32:28.630
as to escape our inquiry.

02:32:28.630 --> 02:32:30.860
Hence there is a new
visible world discovered

02:32:30.860 --> 02:32:32.160
to the understanding."

02:32:32.160 --> 02:32:34.290
That is Robert Hooke
from <i>Micrografia </i>.

02:32:34.290 --> 02:32:35.590
I leave some websites.

02:32:35.590 --> 02:32:36.890
If you want to see how
you did on the quiz,

02:32:36.890 --> 02:32:39.280
you can go to
chandra.is.edu/micro.

02:32:39.280 --> 02:32:41.590
If you want to learn more about
the research, go to the last one

02:32:41.590 --> 02:32:43.130
in the list and then the
other ones are just probably

02:32:43.130 --> 02:32:44.430
more obvious.

02:32:44.430 --> 02:32:46.230
Thank you.

02:32:46.230 --> 02:32:59.050
[ Applause ]

